<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Stoning     05-09 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Stoning,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Young Whites Convicted Of Fatal Stoning Of Black Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young white men have been
convicted of murdering an 8-year-old black boy who was struck in
the skull by a paving stone hurled from the back of a
four-wheel-drive vehicle.
   According to testimony, the young men were part of a group of
high school students who skipped classes on Oct. 12, 1987 and who
decided to throw stones at pedestrians while on their way back from
a picnic grounds where they had been drinking.
   Ronnie Pitso, 8, died of brain injuries after he was struck by a
paving stone hurled by Shane Mitchell, now 18, according to
Monday's judgment in Johannesburg Supreme Court.
   Timothy Beddingfield, now 20, also was convicted of murder on
the grounds that he knew the stone was about to be thrown and did
nothing to stop Mitchell.
   Sentencing was scheduled for May 22.
   A murder conviction can carry the death penalty in South Africa,
but that will not happen in this case because the court ruled that
there were extenuating circumstances, including the defendants' age.
</TEXT>
