<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Notebook     05-09 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Notebook,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Beirut Restaurants, It's B.Y.O.B. _ Bring Your Own Bread</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dining out in Beirut during lulls in the
artillery battles between Christians and Moslems is pretty much a
do-it-yourself affair these days.
   Some restaurants that open for a few hours between bombardments
now ask customers to bring their own bread.
   And if they've got anything else to vary the diet of canned
food, which most people live on for days on end while huddled in
their bunkers, they can bring that along as well.
   The menus at restaurants like Socrates and Sofar, which always
were packed in the days when Beirut was the playground of the
Middle East, are pretty plain, mainly ``homemade dishes'' of stew
and rice.
   Only a few restaurants open during the lulls. The seaside fish
restraurants along the corniche, which in quieter times are usually
packed, remain closed.
   The Syrians have positioned artillery and rocket launchers on
the corniche to fire across the bay into the Christian enclave,
which makes the area a target for retaliatory shellfire.
   Flour, like sugar, water and electricity, is in short supply. No
one is starving, but the belt-tightening has affected everyone.
   The flour shortage has spawned ``bread mafias'' _ people who buy
up as much flour as they can when it's available, then sell bread
at high prices.
   A crowd of about 50 people, yelling and pushing, were seen
around a car in the street recently in the Hamra district of Moslem
west Beirut.
   It looked like an accident, but it was actually a man selling
the flat loaves of pita bread. The carload sold out in minutes,
despite the fact that it was four times the price before the latest
round of fighting erupted March 8.
   Moslem militiamen in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley in east
Lebanon last week hijacked three truckloads of flour, totalling
about 75 tons, heading for Beirut.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The electricity shortages also have worsened the plight of the
Lebanese.
   A European woman said she needed a whole week to watch the Peter
Sellers movie, ``Being There'' because of the electricity rationing.
   The woman, who has lived in Beirut for a year, began watching
the two-hour videocassette one night last week. But the power,
rationed to a random two hours a day, went off after only a few
minutes.
   ``I thought I'd finish it the next day,'' said the woman, who
asked that her name not be used. ``I had no idea what time our turn
for electricity was.
   ``But at 5:55 a.m. the lights suddenly came on in my apartment.
I wasn't wildly excited about getting up that early, but I was
anxious to finish the film even though I could hardly open my eyes.
   ``I got up, made a strong cup of coffee and was really getting
into the movie when, just like that, the electricity went off 10
minutes later. It didn't come back all that day.
   ``Over the next days, the electricity came on when I was out so
I couldn't watch the film. A friend who has a generator at home
said I could finish it at his place but the videocassette got stuck
in the player.''
   It took her three days to get it it out. But she finally did get
to see the movie all the way to the end.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Among the nearly 300 people killed since March 8 were four
members of the Itani family, who are Sunni Moslem. They died when a
Christian 155mm shell hit their home in west Beirut.
   Ten other members of the family were wounded, dragged from the
rubble by civil defense rescue teams. The rescuers frequently had
to run for cover as more shells exploded around them in the
indiscriminate barrage.
   That's probably why they didn't notice the family's baby _
7-month-old Zeina _ buried under the debris. Her mother, Rana, was
among the dead.
   Several hours later, the baby's wounded relatives being treated
at the American University Hospital realized she was not accounted
for and went back to their wrecked home to find her.
   They clawed through the jagged concrete slabs until they found
Zeina, who was not injured.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Not everyone curses the bombardments.
   Christian shells blew down an outside wall of one of the
cellblocks in the gendarmerie prison in Moslem west Beirut's Verdun
district on one recent night.
   The guards were in underground bunkers, and 53 of the prisoners,
serving sentences for theft and drug trafficking, escaped.
   Later, 33 were rounded up; the other 20 are still at large.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
