<FIRST>u a AM-FightersCollide 1stLd-Writethru a0715 05-09 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fighters Collide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighter Jets Collide Over Sierra Nevada</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with one pilot dead; picks up 10th
graf, `One of ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Navy jet fighters collided in
flight Monday over the Sierra Nevada, killing one pilot who went
down with his aircraft and injuring the other, officials said.
   The FA-18 Hornets, based at Point Mugu Naval Air Station,
collided around 11 a.m.
   The single-seat jets went down about 45 miles apart _ one into
the remote foothills of the Inyo National Forest, the other into
sand dunes to the south.
   Witnesses reported seeing one parachute and a Navy spokesman
said the dead pilot did not eject from his aircraft.
   ``We have one confirmed fatality and one injured,'' Navy Lt.
Cmdr. Gene Okamoto said from Point Mugu. ``The pilot who was found
dead was found in his aircraft.''
   The pilots' names were withheld until relatives could be
notified, Okamoto said. The surviving aviator's condition wasn't
immediately available, but a Navy spokeswoman said his injuries
weren't serious.
   Vicki Wood, owner of a gas station, heard an explosion and
looked up to see the aftermath of one jet's plunge onto the desert
floor.
   ``It was like a big sonic boom,'' Ms. Wood said. ``It went down
in the sand dunes and this big mushroom cloud came up. There was
one big orange parachute.''
   The injured pilot was taken to Lone Pine Hospital for treatment.
``He felt good enough (that) he felt he didn't need to go,'' said
Loretta King, spokeswoman for nearby China Lake Naval Weapons
Center.
   One of the planes went down in the foothills of the Inyo
Mountains, 10 miles northeast of Independence, about 175 miles
north of Los Angeles. The other crashed in sand dunes 4{ miles east
of Olancha, said Cynthia Krell, spokeswoman for the Inyo National
Forest.
   Smoke was seen pouring from the aircraft that crashed in the
forest and there was no sign of the pilot, Ms. Krell said.
   The $23 million FA-18 Hornet is a single-seat, twin-engine jet
fighter that can be used for either air-to-air combat or
air-to-ground attack.
   The plane, the Navy's most modern jet fighter, is built by
McDonnell Douglas Corp. The aircraft flies more than 1.7 times the
speed of sound and can be fitted with a variety of air-to-air and
air-to-ground missiles and bombs.
</TEXT>
