<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Abuses     05-09 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Abuses,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Former Reagan Cabinet Members Summoned to Testify on Possible
HUD Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel is calling on two Reagan Cabinet
members to address an official's claim that he was unfairly singled
out in a probe of favoritism in a $225 million federal housing
program.
   A House Government Operations subcommittee Monday said it would
seek the testimony of former Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Samuel Pierce and former Interior Secretary James Watt to
help evaluate former federal housing commissioner Thomas Demery's
claims.
   Demery was targeted in a HUD inspector general's report two
weeks ago that alleged ``a perception of favoritism'' in awarding
money to renovate housing for the poor. HUD Secretary Jack Kemp
temporarily halted the program and blocked some $100 million
pending contracts.
   An angry Demery, who complained about being ``singled out for
top billing,'' told the subcommittee on employment and housing
Monday that the report by Inspector General Paul A. Adams was
motivated by ``malice, negligence and a coverup, or a combination
of the three.''
   Demery testified that problems existed in the ``moderate
rehabilitation program'' before he assumed his post in October
1986. He served until last November.
   Demery said one of his HUD predecessors, Silvio Debartolomeis,
was reluctant to sign funding requests for the program in 1986. He
also questioned why Deborah Gore Dean, former executive assistant
to Pierce, was mentioned only briefly in the 700-page report.
   Demery ``made a lot of statements on the record that need to be
verified'' by future witnesses, said subcommittee member Rep.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   Adams told the committee poor documentation contributed to the
problem, and said highly paid consultants _ including former HUD or
other government officials _ used their clout to win contracts for
developers.
   The subcommittee wants Watt, President Reagan's first interior
secretary, to testify about his work as consultant on behalf of a
312-unit project in Essex, Md. Watt earned a $300,000 fee despite
indicating that he had little knowledge of the program, Adams said.
   ``Mr. Watt's only known experience in the field of housing was
making Bambi homeless,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif.
   Other consultants included the late John Mitchell, attorney
general under President Nixon; former Republican Sen. Ed Brooke of
Massachusetts; former Kentucky Gov. Louis Nunn, also a Republican;
and other top HUD officials under Pierce.
</TEXT>
