<FIRST>u a PM-Names     05-09 0968</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,1006</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bluesman B.B. King, who has traveled the
world with his guitar ``Lucille,'' is looking for a home in Memphis
and plans to open a club in the Beale Street entertainment district
next year, his manager says.
   King got his professional start and his stage name in Memphis in
the late 1940s.
   ``After all, he is named B.B. King, which is `Beale Street Blues
Boy,' and that goes back to the basic roots,'' manager Sid
Sidenberg said Monday by telephone from New York.
   From the late 1800s through the 1950s, Beale Street was a
bustling entertainment and commercial district for blacks. Recent
efforts to develop it into a major tourist center have been
disappointing.
   Sidenberg said the district is coming along, however, and the
time is right for the blues guitarist and singer to give it a try.
   ``We decided to open up a club so we can use it as sort of a
sounding board for new talent as well as B.B. himself coming down
and having fun playing in his hometown,'' Sidenberg said.
   King will move his primary residence from Las Vegas to Memphis
but will still be on the road most of the time, Sidenberg said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``New Hampshire Vice'' doesn't have quite
the same alluring ring as ``Miami Vice.'' But no matter, Gov. Judd
Gregg is trying to entice its star, Don Johnson, to New Hampshire.
   Gregg sent a letter to the television celebrity Monday, inviting
Johnson to film his next movie in New Hampshire. The invitation was
prompted by the star's income tax problems in neighboring Vermont,
where he owes $50,000.
   ``We regret the impasse you have reached with our sister state.
Still, a good Yankee never passes up an opportunity, so I want to
point out that New Hampshire has no state income tax and no sales
tax,'' Gregg wrote.
   Johnson has appealed the tax bill, and Vermont officials say
he's threatened to blackball the state in the film industry if he
is forced to pay.
   Residents of Hyde Park, Vt., where Johnson filmed ``Sweetheart's
Dance'' in 1987, were outraged when the Senate Finance Committee
last week approved legislation to exempt movie stars from the
Vermont state income tax. The committee reversed its decision a few
days later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Osmond clan _ Donny and most of his
brothers, Marie, and their parents _ helped dedicate a new wing at
the Arkansas Children's Hospital named in the family's honor.
   The show business family was honored on Monday for their work in
raising money for the hospital through the Children's Miracle
Network Telethon. The family started the telethon seven years ago
through the Osmond Foundation.
   Marie Osmond said her two oldest brothers are hard of hearing
and the Osmond Foundation was established to help the hearing
impaired.
   ``That was the vision that started everything,'' she said. ``It
is because of them.''
   Also in attendance were Osmond brothers Donny, Virl, Tom,
Merrill, Wayne, Jay and Alan. Youngest brother, Jimmy, couldn't
make it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop plans to write a
partly autobiographical book after he steps down as the nation's
top health officer this summer, his agent said.
   Owen Laster, of the William Morris Agency, said Monday that
Koop's book will focus on his seven-year tenure as surgeon general.
Koop also will give his opinon on various health issues, Laster
said.
   Koop, 72, is leaving his post July 13 and retiring Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Mickey Rourke wants to make a new
version of the steamy movie ``9{ Weeks'' in which he starred. He
feels the original is too commercial and insipid.
   Rourke made the comment during a weekend news conference in
Salvador, on Brazil's northeast Atlantic coast, where he and
Jacqueline Bisset are shooting scenes for a new movie, ``Wild
Orchid,'' directed by Zalman King.
   Rourke said he's willing to direct a new ``9{ Weeks'' himself,
to make his character John ``more mature, more intimate.''
   The original film, co-starring Kim Basinger, produced only so-so
box office revenues in the United States, but has become a widely
seen cult film in Brazil and much of Western Europe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPEARFISH, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Balladeer Burl Ives and his wife,
Dorothy, turned over a shovelful of gravel at groundbreaking
ceremonies for a theater to be named after them.
   Ives has donated an estimated $200,000 worth of costumes and
other memorabilia to the High Plains Heritage Center, which is
scheduled to open this summer in this city on the edge of the Black
Hills in western South Dakota. The collection will be displayed in
the theater's Burl and Dorothy Ives Theater of Performing Arts.
   Mayor Fred Romkema gave Ives a key to the city during the
weekend ceremony and sculptor Dale Lamphere unveiled a bust of the
singer.
   ``Dale, I'd just be happy if I looked that good,'' the
80-year-old Ives joked. Ives and his wife live in Santa Barbara,
Calif.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arrest warrant for American actress
Elizabeth Ashley was issued after she failed to appear for a second
time to stand trial for possession of cocaine.
   Ashley, 49, was charged with cocaine possession after her arrest
in March 1986 at Edmonton International Airport. She was to appear
in a Wetaskiwin, Alberta, court for jury selection on Wednesday,
and her trial would have begun Monday.
   ``We don't want to comment,'' the actress' publicist, Lisa
Kasteler, said Monday in Los Angeles.
   It was the second time an arrest warrant was issued for Ashley.
The first was issued in December 1986 after she failed to show up
at a pretrial proceeding. It was canceled when she appeared in
court 20 months later.
</TEXT>
