<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Talks     05-09 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Talks,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Make Progress, but Hard Bargaining Ahead</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest round of Cambodian peace
talks ended in a rosy glow of optimism but the hard bargaining has
yet to begin.
   The encouraging results in Jakarta, the unprecedented dialogue
in recent months and the general warming of ties among the United
States, China and the Soviet Union have created a momentum toward
peace. Differences still divide the warring factions in Cambodia,
however.
   In the jargon of negotiators, the quest for an end to Cambodia's
10-year jungle war is divided into ``external'' and ``internal''
factors.
   The external include the withdrawal of Vietnam's troops and the
halt of outside aid to the warring guerrilla factions. The big
internal factor is how the factions will share power.
   Vietnam has promised to withdraw the last of its estimated
50,000 to 70,000 soldiers by the end of September, regardless of
whether a political settlement is reached.
   The warring factions have agreed to allow international
observers to monitor the withdrawal. Details are to be worked out
at an international conference in Paris July 24-25.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev confers with Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping in Beijing May 15-18 in the first China-Soviet
summit in 30 years. The Cambodian question, a major obstacle in
normalizing relations between the two nations, is expected to be
high on the agenda.
   The Vietnamese Communists and Cambodian Khmer Rouge guerrillas
came to power in the spring of 1975, defeating U.S.-backed
governments in South Vietnam and Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge forcibly tried to turn Cambodia into an agrarian
commune and hundreds of thousands of people died in purges or of
starvation.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the Khmer
Rouge and set up another communist government.
   Moscow has supported Vietnam and its regime in Phnom Penh.
Beijing has backed the Khmer Rouge, still widely feared by many
Cambodians and now the strongest of three factions in a guerrilla
resistance coalition.
   Some officials fear the Soviet Union and China could reach
agreement swiftly and, as in Afghanistan, give up their supporting
roles in the conflict before the Cambodian rivals have made peace.
   They fear the civil war would only drag on in such a situation.
   Persistent but unconfirmed reports say the Soviets, seeking
better relations with China and non-communist Southeast Asian
nations and an end to costly foreign military involvements, have
been pressuring Vietnam for a speedy withdrawal.
   Peace negotiations began in July after years of deadlock when
Indonesia played host for informal talks involving most of those
involved.
   The most important development came last week when guerrilla
coalition leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, 67, said he would return
to Cambodia as head of state if the Vietnamese pullout is
independently confirmed and the constitution rewritten to his
satisfaction.
   Sihanouk's supporters and the non-communist Khmer People's
National Liberation Front are the other groups in the guerrilla
coalition.
   Diplomatic observers say Sihanouk seems ready to return with or
without the Khmer Rouge guerrillas, who are said to be worried they
might be left out of a peace settlement.
   The Khmer Rouge was not directly represented at the Jakarta
talks. Sihanouk dismissed them as only interested in continuing the
war and he quoted Cambodian Premier Hun Sen as saying let them
``stay in the jungle.''
   Hun Sen and Sihanouk insist that Pol Pot and other Khmer Rouge
founders be barred from any future government and the resistance
wants to reach a political settlement with Hun Sen before Vietnam
withdraws its forces.
   Without such an agreement, there is concern the Khmer Rouge
might regain power in Phnom Penh because of their superior military
capability.
   However, in a joint declaration last month, Vietnam and Cambodia
said that if any of the guerrilla factions continued to receive
outside aid, the Cambodian government reserves the right to call
for outside help.
   The United States, which provides the guerrillas of Sihanouk and
former Premier Son Sann with diplomatic support and non-lethal aid,
stepped up its campaign against the Khmer Rouge as the Jakarta
meeting began.
   ``The United States is totally opposed to a return to dominance
in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge,'' said state department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler in Washington.
   China's once unequivocal backing of the Khmer Rouge stymied
peace efforts for years. But now even Beijing has said the
guerrillas should not be allowed to return to power.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Kenneth L. Whiting has been covering Southeast
Asia from his base in Singapore for 15 years.
</TEXT>
