<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-09 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Tests to Start in England on AIDS Vaccine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests will begin soon in England on the safety
of a proposed vaccine for AIDS, an American researcher says.
   Allan Goldstein, an AIDS researcher at the George Washington
University School of Medicine, said 24 volunteers are being sought
in London to test the safety of a vaccine known as HGP-30.
   The volunteers, he said, must be free of any AIDS infection. A
second 24, to be used as a control group, also will be selected.
   Goldstein said the purpose of the year-long trial is to
determine if the candidate vaccine is safe to use on humans.
Earlier tests on laboratory animals did not reveal any problems of
toxicity or other adverse effects, he said.
   Control trials in the United States have not started, Goldstein
said, because the drug has not been approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for human experimentation.
   In laboratory tests, Goldstein said HGP-30 has been shown to
stimulate the production of antibodies which attack and kill both
the AIDS virus and cells in the body that are infected with the
AIDS virus.
   Two other vaccines, developed by other researchers, are also in
early safety trials, according to an FDA spokesman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bentsen Seeks Continuation Of Hurricane Flights</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military weather reconnaissance flights should
not be halted because they provide necessary ``last-minute
warning'' to coastal areas when a hurricane is approaching, says
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   But Defense Secretary Dick Cheney contends the flights, which
help forecasters predict the intensity and position of an
approaching hurricane, are not an Air Force mission.
   As a budget-cutting move, Cheney wants to deactivate the weather
reconnaissance units at Keesler Air Force Base in Mississippi at a
savings of $14 million. Bentsen contends the total annual cost is
closer to $25 million.
   Bentsen, D-Texas, is asking Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, chairman of
the Senate defense appropriations subcommittee, to continue funding
the Air Force's flights into the eye of an approaching hurricane.
   Bentsen said the cost is a mere fraction of the destruction that
could occur if coastal residents don't have the flights'
``last-minute warning needed to protect lives and property.''
   Unless the money is provided in next year's budget, Bentsen said
the flights could be halted Sept. 30. In this decade alone, eight
major hurricanes have hit the United States after Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>McDonnell Douglas Still Top Defense Research Company</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The McDonnell Douglas Corp. won almost $2.9
billion in defense research contracts last year, easily retaining
its top position in the field, the Defense Department says.
   The Martin Marietta Corp. ranked second for the second year in a
row with contracts totaling $2.03 billion, the Pentagon added.
   Among educational and non-profit entities, the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology continued to hold the top ranking, winning
research contracts during the year worth $403.7 million. The
Aerospace Corp. of El Segundo, Calif., was close behind with
contracts worth $367 million, followed by Johns Hopkins University
with $353.9 million.
   Overall, the Pentagon increased its spending on research by just
over 3 percent in fiscal 1988, with awards worth a total of $22.5
billion. By contrast, the department spent $21.8 billion on
research in fiscal 1987.
   A great deal of last year's spending appeared to be related to
work on the ``Star Wars'' anti-missile defense system. The amount
of money invested in research on ``missile and space systems''
totaled $7.8 billion in fiscal 1988, or 34.6 percent of the total,
the Pentagon said.
   Those numbers were little changed from fiscal 1987, when missile
and space systems research consumed $7.9 billion.
</TEXT>
