<DOCNO> AP890509-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RetardationFunding     05-09 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retardation Funding,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Says Services for Retarded Aren't Guaranteed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Constitution doesn't guarantee programs
for the mentally retarded living at home, a U.S. appeals court
ruled in reversing a judge's decision.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected arguments that
cuts in services to the mentally retarded in Philadelphia violated
rights to equal protection and due process.
   ``It is impossible to find an affirmative state duty to protect
the mentally retarded living at home,'' the three appeals judges
said Monday.
   A group of 32 mentally retarded people and the Phildelphia
Police and Fire Association for Handicapped Children Inc. filed
suit in July after the city cut off services to 9,000 in a
cost-cutting measure.
   Attorney David Ferleger, who represented the plaintiffs, said he
was ``very disheartened'' by the ruling. He said it would be
appealed.
   In November, U.S. District Judge Raymond J. Broderick ordered
the city and state to continue providing the programs. Three months
later, Broderick ruled the state in contempt of his decision and
forced it to pay the city $4.93 million for the programs.
   The appeals court said the city could classify retarded
residents living with relatives and those at group homes
differently for a legitimate purpose.
   ``Jurisprudence on the equal protection clause recognizes that
the act of governing often requires a state to bestow a benefit on
some, but not all, of its citizens,'' wrote Chief Judge John J.
Gibbons.
   The panel rejected the lower court's ruling that the decision to
single out those living at home was arbitrary and irrational,
saying the action followed the city's desire to reduce spending
with a minimal disruption to the system.
   The court said even if retarded patients living at home
regressed because of the cutback, relatives might be willing to
continue providing care.
   But if cutbacks at community homes caused regression, the staffs
might be unable to handle the increased demands, forcing the
patients to enter institutions, the court said.
   To minimize the cuts, city officials opted to curtail services
they considered less critical, such as case-management and
family-support services, and maintain services they considered
vital, such as vocational training.
   Philadelphia Solicitor Seymour Kurland and a spokeswoman for the
Department of Public Welfare, which administers the state's
programs for the retarded, could not be reached for comment Monday
night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
