<FIRST>r w PM-SeabrookLicense     05-09 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook License,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seabrook Foes Ask For NRC Stay Of Low-Power License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts officials and other opponents of
the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear plant are urging federal regulators to
delay approval of a license that would permit low-power testing at
the plant.
   Seabrook foes filed a 10-page stay request Monday with the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission, the last regulatory maneuver in a
prolonged campaign to block a low-power license.
   ``It would be arbitrary and capricious to issue (the license)
... in light of the great uncertainty that Seabrook will ever
receive an operating license,'' wrote lawyers for Massachusetts,
the town of Hampton, N.H., and the New England Coalition on Nuclear
Pollution.
   The opponents cited Seabrook's financial condition _ the lead
owner has filed for bankruptcy protection _ coupled with geographic
and demographic conditions around the plant that they say make it
``virtually impossible to provide adequate sheltering or reasonably
prompt evacuations.'' Seabrook must have evacuation plans approved
to receive a full-power commercial license.
   Opponents argue that conducting low-power tests could endanger
workers and residents, make decommissioning much more expensive and
eliminate the chances of converting the $6 billion plant to another
form of energy production.
   ``Even temporary operation at low power will result in
irreversible plant contamination caused by radiation of the reactor
and its component parts, and the creation of high-level radioactive
waste,'' the opponents said in the petition. ``Should a
radiological accident occur at the Seabrook plant, it could cause
irreversible health damage to the population around the plant.''
   If the NRC refuses the stay request, the license will be issued
immediately, according to a March commission order. That decision
can come any time after Friday, the deadline for the plant owners
to respond to Monday's stay request.
   But the opponents also asked the NRC to grant a ``one-week
housekeeping stay'' if the commission rules against the initial
petition. That would give the opposition enough time to seek a
court-ordered stay pending a court appeal, attorneys argued.
   The opponents asked for a decision within two days on whether
they would receive the week-long postponement if the initial stay
is rejected.
   ``If not told that by Wednesday, we intend to go to federal
court by the end of the week,'' Massachusetts Attorney General
James Shannon said in a telephone interview from Boston. Shannon
said the appeal would be filed in the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here.
   NRC spokesman John Kopeck declined comment on the stay requests,
noting only that the commissioners' schedule calls for a decision
after the plant's owners file their counter-arguments.
   Seabrook officials say they are ready to begin preparations for
low-power testing within 24 hours of receiving the license.
</TEXT>
