<FIRST>r a PM-JeffersonFeud     05-09 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jefferson Feud,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Office Complex Near Monticello Entrance Opens Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RM1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legend has it that Thomas Jefferson
used to look down by telescope from his hilltop Monticello home and
watch the construction of the university he designed.
   Officials of the Thomas Jefferson Memorial Foundation,
proprietors of Monticello, are afraid the third president would not
look so lovingly on the development the University of Virginia has
planned for the foot of his ``Little Mountain.''
   The proposal, an $11 million office complex for four state
agencies, has sparked what Daniel P. Jordan, executive director of
the foundation, calls ``a family squabble'' between the group and
Jefferson's university.
   The complex would not be visible from Monticello, where
Jefferson lived from his retirement in 1809 to his death in 1826,
only from the highway that winds its way up the heavily wooded
mountain to the red-brick mansion and its perfectly manicured
grounds.
   But Jordan said the ambiance of the roadway is terribly
important to seeing Monticello as it was when Jefferson lived
there. More than a half-million visitors each year begin their trip
to the home on that road, he said Monday.
   ``We are trying to preserve the integrity of the Monticello
entranceway,'' he said. ``You can't understand Jefferson unless you
understand the setting.''
   The foundation owns about 2,000 of the 5,000 acres that once
comprised Jefferson's estate. The university owns land to about
halfway up the mountain, including the 20-acre site of the proposed
development. Jordan said the foundation always assumed that land
was safe from encroachment.
   ``We never thought they'd want to do this,'' Jordan said. ``It
was a surprise and a shock.''
   The university plans to deed the land to the state Forestry
Department, which would then return to the school its current,
smaller quarters, located in the middle of campus.
   The foundation has objected to the plan, and is awaiting a
written proposal of possible alternatives from the university.
Those alternatives include flipping the blueprint of the
development so that it faces away from the access to Monticello
onto a different road.
   But Jordan said the foundation would prefer no development. He
would like to see the road become a protected parkway, like the
Mount Vernon parkway that leads eight miles from Alexandria to
George Washington's home. The road to Monticello is only 1{ miles
long, and the foundation already owns much of it, Jordan said.
   William Fishback, associate vice president for university
relations, would not speculate on whether the school might be
willing to give up the site, saying negotiations with the
foundation are still in ``the working-out stage.''
   ``Some other site may or may not be acceptable,'' he said. ``The
site that we're discussing is a preferable site to us.''
   Jordan and Fishback said they are optimistic the situation will
be resolved to the satisfaction of both parties, who have always
been close.
   ``We hope that it will be resolved within the family. Nobody
wants a public furor,'' Jordan said.
   But Jordan said the proposal has made the foundation aware of
the threat of development on other, privately owned land near
Monticello.
   ``This issue has opened our eyes to the larger need of
protecting the setting,'' he said. ``We are the stewards of a
finite resource.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0037 </DOCNO>
