<FIRST>u i PM-Panama-Observers     05-09 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Observers,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter: Noriega Believed His Side Would Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Panama, Bjt ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
apparently allowed international observers to monitor Panama's
presidential elections because he was sure his man would win,
former President Jimmy Carter said.
   ``He didn't have a clue that his man might lose,'' Carter told a
news conference Monday night.
   Carter, who said he met with Noriega on Saturday, was made to
feel unwelcome after he accused Panama's de facto leader of
stealing Sunday's election from opposition candidate Guillermo
Endara.
   Government candidate Carlos Duque denounced what he called
``obvious American intervention in affairs that only concern Panama
and the abuse by observers of Panamanian hospitality.''
   Duque also was referring to a delegation of observers sent by
President Bush that concluded Noriega's soldiers intimidated voters
and carried out widespread fraud.
   ``The delegation cannot certify that the election was a free and
fair election,'' said delegation chairman Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa.
   Carter said he discovered proof of fraud when he examined vote
tallies being tabulated at the election center. He confronted
election officials, and his relationship with the government
quickly deteriorated, he said.
   The Georgian was forced to hold his news conference in a narrow
lobby of the Marriott Hotel because he was denied use of the nearby
government press center. A crowd of Noriega supporters stood
outside and jeered.
   Carter said the military had seized thousands of vote tally
sheets in a nighttime sweep.
   ``During the day those records have been discarded and
counterfeit documents have been substituted,'' he said.
   ``It's a military dictatorship rejecting the election it
condoned and set up,'' Carter said.
   Both Murtha and Carter cited a Roman Catholic Church exit poll
that gave Endara a 3-1 margin over Duque as evidence of a sweeping
opposition win.
   The Panamanian Committee for Human Rights, which invited 279
observers from 21 nations, also condemned the election as
fraudulent.
   The Bush delegation steered away from policy questions, saying
it would have to consult Congress and the White House first.
   However, Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., an observer who left early
Monday, said the United States ``should now consider the use of
force in Panama.''
   ``We've tried economic sanctions, which have had almost no
effect on Noriega,'' Graham said.
   Carter disagreed, saying he didn't think the ``international
community ought to isolate Panama.''
   He said the treaties that bind the United States to turn over
the Panama Canal should on no account be violated.
   The question, he said, was, ``How do we exert proper influence
without punishing innocent people?''
   ``I hope there will be a worldwide outcry against this dictator
stealing this election from his own people,'' Carter said.
   At the White House delegation's news conference, former U.S.
Ambassador to Panama Jack Hood Vaughn said Washington should soon
be united on a plan to oust Noriega.
   ``If I was to talk with Manuel, I'd say `Watch yourself,'''
Vaughn said.
</TEXT>
