<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-09 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar at Eight-Month High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index fell today
after climbing for six trading days, while the dollar hit an
eight-month high against the yen despite central bank intervention,
market sources said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 103.37 points, or 0.30
percent, closing at 34,031.87. The index had gained 180.25 points
for a 34,135.24-point record closing on Monday.
   A Nomura Securities dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the index's fall resulted mainly from profit-taking selling
following continuous gains since April 26.
   ``Uncertainties over the foreign exchange rate also discouraged
Japanese investors' buying interest,'' he said.
   He said the dollar's rise to the 140-yen level might lead to an
interest rate hike, which would further discourage stock buying.
   ``An interest rate hike is unlikely if you consider only the
recent rate of growth in the Japanese economy, but it is very
likely if the dollar rises further, reaching the 140-yen level, for
instance,'' the dealer added.
   Trading was rather active, dominated by sell orders, with first
section volume estimated at 1.1 billion shares.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 135.00 yen, up 0.48
yen from Monday's 134.52-yen close and its highest close since
135.60 yen last Sept. 6.
   The dollar now has gained 3.83 yen since April 25.
   It opened today at 134.95 yen. When it reached its high for the
day of 135.05 yen in early trading, the Bank of Japan sold dollars
to check the rise, said Minori Takeuchi, a dealer at Chemical Bank.
   The central bank, which does not comment on its market
intervention, also was reported to have sold dollars on Monday.
   Ms. Takeuchi said the bank sold about $100 million today. The
dollar, however, went no lower than 134.90 yen during the day.
   Daiwa Bank dealer Takamasa Yamasaki said speculative investors
also sold dollars near the 135-yen level.
   Ms. Takeuchi said trading was thin, especially in the afternoon,
following the central bank intervention.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told a news conference the
current yen-dollar exchange rate ``isn't that much of a concern. We
should wait to see what happens.''
</TEXT>
