<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Politics     05-09 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Politics,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kinnock Presses For End To Unilateral Disarmament Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock has called for
scrapping his Labor Party's vote-losing policy of unilateral
nuclear disarmament as well as the ``naive, shopping-list
socialism'' of party left-wingers.
   At the start of a two-day meeting of Labor's national executive
committee, Kinnock on Monday accused left-wingers of trying to
dissociate the party completely from the capitalist, market economy
system.
   ``It's the system we live in, and we have got to make it work
more efficiently, more fairly and more successfully in the world
market place,'' Kinnock told a news conference.
   ``That's what the policy review report is about, and we shall
reject any sort of naive, shopping-list socialism,'' he said.
   Labor, which has lost three elections in a row since 1979 and
has lurched further left in opposition, is midway through a
two-year review of its policies. The next general election will
probably be held in 1991.
   Kinnock and other party leaders want to water down the
unequivocal policy of unilateral nuclear disarmament, which has
undermined the party's chances of regaining support. The committee
was expected to vote on that policy today.
   The policy would commit a Labor government to scrap Britain's
nuclear weapons unilaterally and shut down U.S. nuclear bases in
this country within five years.
   On Monday, the committee voted by 23-4 in favor of a
Kinnock-backed policy to jettison commitments to renationalize all
state-owned industries sold by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
The policy favors renationalizing only the telephone and
telecommunications giant British Telecom, and the English and Welsh
water supply system, which is due to be sold within a year.
   The committee also voted in favor of raising income tax for
high-earners to 50 percent from the current 40 percent limit. A
Labor government also would build no more new nuclear power
stations, the committee agreed.
   On the economy, Kinnock has already succeeded in edging his
party to the right and denied that a Labor government would be
profligate.
   Labor, he said, would not ``promise to spend that which we have
not got. We will make stark decisions about priorities.''
   Left-wingers, such as former Cabinet minister Tony Benn, have
accused Kinnock of trying to dilute Labor's left-wing doctrines and
simply copy Mrs. Thatcher's Conservatives.
   ``These policies are asking the electorate to disregard our
campaigns in the last two general elections,'' Benn said.
</TEXT>
