<FIRST>r a PM-RagingBulls     05-09 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Raging Bulls,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Bulls, Two Cows Shot After Fleeing Overturned Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six rodeo bulls and two cows escaped from
an overturned truck and charged a California Highway Patrolman and
several cars during a nearly 10-hour rampage before authorities
shot them.
   ``They charged anything that moved,'' Highway Patrol spokesman
Jim Gregg said.
   The animals ran loose after a trailer tipped over early Monday
near this central California town. One other bull was killed in the
crash.
   Owner Frank Pires of Strathmore asked authorities to kill them
instead of trying to round them up, Gregg said. The bulls, which
were being driven home from the Riverdale rodeo grounds, were
valued at $1,500 to $2,000 each.
   ``We were advised by the owner that they definitely were not
friendly, they were very aggressive stock,'' Gregg said. ``The
owner said `don't try to take them alive because somebody is going
to get hurt. Just eliminate them.'''
   Authorities closed the highway and diverted traffic while animal
control officers stalked the animals in the darkness with
high-powered rifles.
   One bull chased a patrolman onto the hood of his car, Gregg
said. Others charged cars. No injuries were reported, though, and
the last of the animals was destroyed 9{ hours after the accident.
   ``There was some real hazard if we didn't get them eliminated,''
Gregg said. ``It's very unfortunate, but it's one of those things.''
</TEXT>
