<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CensusCelebration     05-09 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Census Celebration,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>1990 Census Officials Hope to Improve on 1790 Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESTERTOWN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special advertising campaigns will be
directed toward blacks, Hispanics and Asians in an effort to ensure
minorities are not underrepresented in the 1990 census.
   C. Louis Kincannon, deputy director of the Census Bureau, said
Monday that undercounting is a problem today as it was 200 years
ago during the first census.
   He and other federal officials joined Gov. William Donald
Schaefer in kicking off a national publicity campaign for the
census next year and urged Americans to stand up and be counted.
   This town of about 3,100 people on Maryland's Eastern Shore was
picked for the celebration because in 1790, it was the young
American nation's population hub. About the same number of people
lived north, south, east and west of Chestertown.
   The day's main event was a parade down Chestertown's tree-lined
streets commemorating American history from 1790.
   The parade featured old trains and cars, a covered wagon and a
rocket, a make-believe George Washington _ state Comptroller Louis
L. Goldstein in a burgundy period costume _ and an astronaut, Air
Force Col. Loren J. Shriver, who served as grand marshal.
   In 1790, Thomas Jefferson and Washington were hoping the census
would show there were more than 4 million people. They were
disappointed when the count came in at 3.9 million, according to
the Census Bureau's Raymond Bancroft.
   Undercounting was a problem 200 years ago that persists today,
he said.
   The two American leaders wanted a larger population ``to show
England we were a big country,'' Bancroft said. But there are more
practical reasons today for making sure everyone is counted, he
said.
   Kincannon said a great deal is at stake in the census, including
about $35 billion a year in federal aid distributed to state and
local governments according to population.
   Census statistics also determine the makeup of elected
legislative bodies from the U.S. House of Representatives to city
councils.
   Kincannon estimated that about 99 percent of the people who live
in the United States were counted in the 1980 census.
   Regional Census Director Laverne Collins said she hopes people
realize census information is confidential. Illegal aliens are not
reported to immigration officials, and income levels are not turned
over to the Internal Revenue Service, she said.
   The 1990 census will cost about $2.6 billion during a 10-year
period, and about 500,000 people will be employed at the peak
counting, Ms. Collins said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
