<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     05-09 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Night Stalker' Defendant Snarls at Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Night Stalker'' defendant Richard Ramirez
snarled at reporters covering his serial murder trial, calling them
``sensation-seeking parasites.''
   Monday's outburst came after he emerged from a conference in the
chambers of Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan about whether
defense lawyers would present evidence in his behalf. The
prosecution already has rested its case.
   Tynan gave Ramirez' lawyers an extra day to decide whether to
call witnesses, or rest their case without presenting evidence.
   The tall, shaggy-haired Ramirez had made no public statements
since he said ``Hail Satan!'' and flashed a pentagram drawn on his
palm at his arraignment nearly four years ago.
   As Ramirez was being led back to his holding cell with shackles
rattling around his ankles, he turned toward the courtroom
spectator section where reporters were taking notes.
   ``Media!'' he growled in a loud, gravelly voice,
``Sensation-seeking parasites!''
   The 29-year-old drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged with 13
murders and 30 related felonies in Los Angeles County during a
series of nighttime attacks that terrified the state in the summer
of 1985.
   Authorities said pentagrams _ upside-down five-pointed stars in
circles used to symbolize Satan _ were found at some murder scenes.
One victim's eyes were gouged out; a woman testified that her
attacker raped and sodomized her and made her ``swear to Satan'' as
she lay beside her slain husband.
   Ramirez was arrested on Labor Day weekend 1985 after a mob
recognized him, ran him down and beat him as he tried to steal a
car, authorities said.
   Since testimony began in his trial Jan. 30, six survivors of
``Night Stalker'' attacks have identified Ramirez as their
assailant. A total of 138 witnesses have testified against him.
   Ramirez's lawyers had said he was emotionally distraught last
week and wanted no defense because he felt it would do no good.
   ``We're still talking to our client. There are many things we
have to consider overnight,'' defense attorney Daniel Hernandez
told reporters as he left the courthouse Monday.
</TEXT>
