<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-Politics     05-09 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-Politics,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Opposition Parties Each Get A New Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of Australia's two main
opposition parties were simultaneously dumped today in party room
coups that could reshape the country's conservative political camp.
   The backroom maneuvering changed the leadership of the Liberal
and National parties, which in coalition dominated Australia's
postwar government until Prime Minister Bob Hawke's Labor Party won
parliamentary elections in 1983.
   The Liberal Party restored its old leader Andrew Peacock in
place of John Howard and the Nationals, the junior opposition
partner, deposing Ian Sinclair for Charles Blunt.
   ``The people who mounted the coups smell the scent of
government,'' said Michelle Gratton, respected political
commentator for The Age newspaper in Melbourne. ``They are
embarking on a ruthless exercise to try to ensure that the
opportunity of the next election is not lost.''
   The change had been brewing since the last federal election in
July 1987 that gave Hawke's government a record third straight
victory, with 86 seats in the 148 seat House of Representatives.
   Howard, as opposition coalition leader, had been widely viewed
as bungling the coalition's chances of victory after miscalculating
in a tax reform proposal.
   Ballots for the new positions were called unexpectedly Monday
night, and Howard was clearly surprised by the challenge.
   As he entered the federal Parliament today, Howard declared that
his political career was not in jeopardy: ``I have the numbers. I
will not resign.''
   Peacock, a former foreign minister, led the Liberals when they
lost the 1983 election. Howard ousted Peacock as party leader in
1985 and on Tuesday Peacock got his old job back, winning the
ballot by 44 votes to 27.
   Perhaps more significant was Sinclair's ousting as National
Party leader. The position had never before been challenged.
   Unlike Peacock's well-orchestrated effort, Blunt's run for the
National crown was sudden. Several others entered the fray but he
received the numbers. Blunt had been the party's aviation and
transport minister. The National Party vote was kept secret.
   In coalition, the Liberals and Nationals have governed Australia
for most of the past 40 years, barring the last six under Hawke's
centrist labor government. Hawke is regarded as the country's most
popular leader ever but his party _ which has embarked on radical
economic reform _ is not.
   Peacock and Howard are both 50, but Howard has often been
ridiculed by Labor politicians as ``tired old John''. Peacock is
known as the father of the Liberal Party, having entered the
political arena in 1966.
   Sinclair, the ousted National leader, is 59. His successor,
Blunt, is 38.
   But Hawke, in his only comment on today's opposition
maneuvering, told Labor stalwarts that he does not intend to call
early elections. The next federal balloting is scheduled for May
1990.
   Under Howard, the Liberal Party had undergone a marked shift to
the right and public opinion polls had consistently shown the
Liberal-National coalition under Howard as being unlikely to
successfully contest a federal election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
