<FIRST>r a PM-MyrnaStatue     05-09 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Myrna Statue,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous Myrna Loy Statue Imprisoned Because Of Vandals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unending assault by vandals has put a
statue of Myrna Loy behind bars.
   The statue depicting the goddess Venus rising from the sea has
been struck by vandals at least a dozen times during the past
decade. Artist William Van Orden is in the process of restoring it
_ again.
   A protective iron cage with three heavy locks has been built
around the statue at Venice High School to prevent another attack.
The most recent damage was discovered in February.
   ``It's the imprisonment of Myrna,'' said the 66-year-old artist,
who lives in Venice and has restored the statue after each attack.
``Something is wrong with society when we find ourselves locking up
our art to preserve it.
   ``We used to put only criminals behind bars, now we live behind
bars. The statue is a symbol of the school and, you know, the bars
are a symbol to what we have become.''
   Principal Andrea Natker said the cage was the only way to
protect the 7-foot-tall statue, originally sculpted in the 1920s by
former Venice High art teacher Harry Winebrenner.
   The $1,500 for the iron cage was donated by New York producers
of a planned musical based on the lighthearted mystery film ``The
Thin Man,'' starring Miss Loy and William Powell.
</TEXT>
