<FIRST>r a PM-SecondAbduction     05-09 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Book on Hiding People Found in Parents' Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book explaining how to hide a person has
been found in the home of a couple suspected in the deaths of their
baby daughters in similar circumstances three years apart,
authorities say.
   ``The Stash Book'' was among the items taken by police from the
Alton home of Robert and Paula Sims, according to documents filed
Monday in Madison County Circuit Court.
   The Simses' 6-week-old daughter, Heather Lee, was found dead of
suffocation Wednesday night in a trash can on the Missouri side of
the Mississippi River _ four days after the couple reported her
abducted.
   The couple also had reported their first daughter, 13-day-old
Loralei, was abducted on June 17, 1986. Authorities said the
remains of a baby believed to be Loralei were found a week later
near the couple's home, then in nearby Brighton, just to the
northeast of St. Louis.
   In both cases, Mrs. Sims said her daughter was kidnapped by an
armed, masked gunman while her husband was at work, authorities
said. The case of Loralei Sims was never solved, although the
Simses remain suspects, Jersey County Sheriff Frank Yocom said.
   Sgt. Rick McCain, chief of detectives in Alton, said the seized
book dealt with hiding different kinds of items and included ``one
section on hiding a person.'' He said the section explained how to
build a false wall that someone could live behind in a home.
   Asked how the book might relate to the case, McCain said,
``Because the body might have been hidden.''
   Police have said tests showed Heather's body had been frozen
before it was dumped. Investigators said they found hairs in the
bottom of the freezer at the home of Mrs. Sims' parents, Orville
and Nylene Blew of Cottage Hills.
   Police in Alton asked the Simses again Monday for more
information about the deaths, but the Simses declined, police said.
   ``If they have a story to tell, we're here to listen,'' McCain
said. ``I think I've made it fairly clear that we want to talk to
them. If not, we'll go on with our case as it is.''
   On Monday, the couple's attorney told police the Simses would
not submit to polygraph tests, McCain said. But he said he believed
Heather's killing would be solved even if the Simses don't provide
more information.
   McCain said Robert Sims told police last week he doubted his
wife's stories about the abductions. The 37-year-old Sims told
police he believed his wife might have killed their daughters
accidentally, McCain said.
   Mrs. Sims had been upset at not having had boys after she gave
birth to both her daughters, the officer said.
   Paula Sims, 29, has declined to talk with police.
   The state took custody of the couple's 15-month-old son, Randy,
on Friday.
   The Simses met for about an hour Monday with their attorney,
Donald E. Groshong. The couple declined to comment afterward and
Groshong said much of what police have said ``isn't even worth
commenting on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
