<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-H-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0442 05-09 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-H-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Asks Washington for Explanation on 1965 H-Bomb Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more comment from officials, details
of anti-nuclear protests, clarifies that request made Monday. No pickup.
^By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has formally asked the United States to
explain a 1965 accident in which a U.S. carrier lost a hydrogen
bomb in the Pacific near a Japanese island while bound for a
Japanese port, officials said Tuesday.
   ``This happened in international waters so we have no right to
make a loud demand,'' said a senior Foreign Ministry official who
declined to be named. ``We are just asking the United States to
give us an explanation.''
   Japanese opposition politicians and citizens' groups claim the
U.S. government covered up the accident. Japan is the only country
ever attacked with nuclear weapons, and popular sentiment is
strongly against nuclear arms.
   The bomb was aboard an A-4 Skyhawk jet that fell off the carrier
Ticonderoga about 80 miles from a small island in Japan's Ryukyu
chain and 200 miles east of the heavily populated island of
Okinawa, a U.S. military spokesman in Japan said.
   The carrier was on its way from Vietnam to the Japanese port of
Yokosuka and the plane's pilot was killed in the accident.
   After a report in the current issue of Newsweek magazine raised
the issue, Japan asked Monday for a U.S. explanation.
   ``We are interested and concerned (about the details),'' the
Foreign Ministry official said.
   Other officials said Japan's government does not know the
location and condition of the B-43 bomb, and there had been no
discussions with the United States about how to deal with it.
   The magazine report, quoting nuclear expert William Arkin of the
Washington-based Institute for Policy Studies, said the U.S. Navy
kept the incident secret until a 1981 Pentagon report that listed
accidents involving nuclear weapons.
   But at the time of the 1981 report, the United States ``did not
bring it to our attention,'' said the Foreign Ministry official.
The report said only that the accident occurred 500 miles from the
Asian mainland.
   Arkin said there was scant danger the bomb would detonate,
although the 33 pounds of plutonium in the bomb could threaten the
environment as it deteriorates.
   The Ticonderoga was on a mission that included readiness to
launch a nuclear strike, a declassified U.S. Navy document released
by Arkin and the environmental group Greenpeace said.
   The disclosure raised the possibility that the carrier entered
Yokosuka with nuclear arms, despite Japan's ban on nuclear weapons.
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that U.S. ships still transit
Japan with nuclear weapons aboard,'' Arkin said in Washington on
Monday.
   The Navy declined comment on Arkin's findings.
   Opposition parties and citizens have charged that Navy ships
routinely visit Japanese ports carrying nuclear bombs with the
tacit agreement of the Japanese government.
   Japan has said the United States is not permitted to bring in
nuclear weapons without prior consultations, and there have been no
such consulations.
   The United States refuses to confirm or deny the presence of
nuclear weapons in specific locations.
   The lost one-megaton hydrogen bomb was about 70 times as
powerful as the bomb that fell on the port city of Hiroshima in
August 1945 in the closing days of World War II, Kyodo News Service
reported.
   Disclosure of the 1965 accident has stirred the ire of citizens
on Okinawa, the site of one of the bloodiest battles in World War
II, and the continued presence of some 35,000 U.S. troops has led
to tensions and frequent protests over such problems as target
range accidents.
   Leaders of Okinawan citizens groups protesting nuclear arms
denounced the way the incident has been handled, news reports said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-EdwardsRunning     05-09 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Edwards Running,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Edwards Says He'll Run For Governor In 1991</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, who dominated
Louisiana politics for nearly two decades but was dogged by
racketeering charges in his last term, said he will run for an
unprecedented fourth term in 1991.
   His announcement Monday came little more than one week after
voters defeated Gov. Buddy Roemer's tax revision package, which
some political analysts called a referendum on the governor's
political strength.
   ``I can tell you that Buddy Roemer will not be the next
governor, so I decided to make the run,'' said Edwards, 61, looking
fit and tanned during a brief visit to the Capitol.
   Jeff Cowart, a spokesman for Roemer, said, ``We normally don't
respond to Edwin's fantasies.''
   Edwards ran second to Roemer in the 1987 primary and then
dropped out of a runoff.
   Edwards served two four-year terms in the 1970s and was barred
by the constitution from seeking a third consecutive term.
   In 1983, he became the first governor elected three times by
defeating Dave Treen, the state's first Republican governor since
Reconstruction.
   That term was marked by Edwards' trial and acquittal on federal
racketeering charges and the collapse of oil prices that threw the
state into a deep recession.
   Edwards said he would establish a campaign office ``in about a
year.'' He promised to revive his 1987 campaign theme _ creation of
a state lottery and casino gambling for New Orleans.
   Roemer opposed the lottery and new taxes and vowed to reduce the
budget.
   Nearly two dozen lottery bills have been filed in the
Legislature as lawmakers look for new revenue to meet a projected
$700 million deficit for the fiscal year that starts July 1.
   ``A lottery and casino gambling are the only answers in these
economic times. There are some long-range things that can be done
but the state needs something sooner, and not taxes on the backs of
the people,'' Edwards said.
   He said Roemer doomed himself by making ``irresponsible campaign
promises inconsistent with reality and now he must retreat. He
admits he can't solve all of the problems by scrubbing the budget.''
   In his first year in office, Roemer pushed through sales tax
increases and borrowed $1 billion to retire an accumulated deficit.
   His tax package, which was rejected by 55 percent to 45 percent,
would have reduced business taxes and sales taxes and increased
individual income taxes. Roemer said the package was necessary to
create jobs and reduce the state's dependence on the oil industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
