<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-09 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Stronger, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened in early European trading
today. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar, which weathered
reported Bank of Japan intervention earlier in the day, had a
clearly bullish undertone.
   Many expected European central banks to step into the market to
halt the dollar's rise, but were divided on whether it would work.
   ``If the central banks intervene massively, it might have an
impact,'' said one trader at a large West German bank in Frankfurt.
   But another said, ``Intervention hasn't been successful, and I
doubt it will be today.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.48 yen to a closing 135.00. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _2.0000 West German marks, up from 1.8975
   _1.7010 Swiss francs, up from 1.6945
   _6.4408 French francs, up from 6.4025
   _2.1528 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1400
   _1,392.75 Italian lire, up from 1,385.00
   _1.1865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1850
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6658, cheaper for buyers
than $1.6710 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $376.20 a troy ounce,
down from $377.50 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $376.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $376.00, down from $377.75 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.34 to close at a bid $377.07.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.59 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $5.64.
</TEXT>
