<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     05-09 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leadership Strips Kadar of His Last Posts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders have stripped
former longtime party boss Janos Kadar of his last posts, saying
the man who took over when the Soviets crushed a 1956 popular
revolt is too ill to carry on.
   The 76-year-old Kadar, replaced as Hungary's leader last year,
was stripped by the party's governing Central Committee Monday of
the post of honorary party president and his seat on the committee.
   The state news agency MTI said Kadar was retired ``on the basis
of information received'' about his state of health.
   But the action followed disclosure of Kadar's role in past
political repressions and increasing public criticism of his
failure to keep pushing reforms during his 32 years in power.
   MTI said the Central Committee ``addressed a written message''
to Kadar, indicating he did not attend Monday's meeting, and that
its contents would be published later.
   Kadar had been replaced as party chief by Karoly Grosz, who is
leading a slow transition to the politics of competing parties and
who criticized the role Kadar played after Soviet forces crushed
the 1956 popular revolt.
   Kadar, who last month was said by officials to be so ill that he
could not carry out his duties, has been seen rarely in public
since losing the party to Grosz last May.
   That shift ushered in a time of fast-paced reforms, with
Communists who advocate greater democracy gradually gaining
strength.
   Such party members have made it clear that they viewed Kadar's
removal from all party posts as a step to gaining trust and
confidence with the public before elections next year, the first
multiparty balloting in four decades.
   Politburo member Mihaly Jasso gave the first public hint that
Kadar would be relieved of his last posts when he told a Budapest
newspaper Sunday that Kadar was ``very ill'' but refused to leave
for treatment at a Soviet health spa in the Crimea.
   Kadar's role in repressions while interior minister after the
Communist takeover in 1948 and in the bloody end of the anti-Soviet
revolt in 1956 have come under increasing public criticism recently.
   The government daily Magyar Hirlap on Saturday published a
full-page document from July 1956 authored by Mihaly Farkas, the
No. 3 figure in the Communist leadership before the revolt that
year.
   The document disclosed that Kadar, then head of the Interior
Ministry, approved of the beating of Laszlo Rajk, a leading
Communist accused of treason and executed in a 1949 purge.
   At a meeting of top historians last week, academician Maria
Ormos called for the leadership to make public other documents she
claims may show Kadar had a part in the capture, imprisonment and
execution of Imre Nagy, leader of the short-lived 1956 revolt.
   Kadar's role at the end of the revolt has never been fully
explained.
   As Kadar's political star waned, Nagy's rose. Executed in 1958
and buried with other leaders of the revolt in an anonymous, remote
corner of a Budapest cemetery, Nagy is to be reburied next month in
a marked grave in the same spot.
   Tens of thousands of Hungarians are expected to attend the
funeral. A new book about Nagy and lapel pins with his portrait are
selling fast at Budapest kiosks.
   Once shunned by the West for taking over after the revolt, Kadar
had slowly gained respect abroad and at home by ushering in
economic reforms in the 1960s.
   But reform was halted in the 1970s. Unwise borrowing eventually
led to economic stagnation and the highest per capita debt in the
East bloc.
</TEXT>
