<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Shamir     05-09 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shamir,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir: Rejection of Palestinian State Before Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in an
interview published today that Palestinians who run in his proposed
elections must agree that the occupied lands will not become an
independent Palestinian nation.
   Shamir told the Jerusalem Post the agreement would apply to an
interim period of autonomy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and to
negotiations on the final status of the territories, seized by
Israel in 1967.
   ``Agreement has to be for the whole process,'' he said.
   Shamir has suggested previously that he might ask for such an
agreement before elections can be held. But his interview with the
Post is his most wide-ranging statement on his plan.
   Leading Palestinians in the occupied lands and the Palestine
Liberation Organization have said any elections must be part of a
plan leading to Palestinian independence.
   They have turned down Shamir's proposal, but he has said he does
not consider the rejection final.
   Under his proposal, Palestinians in the occupied lands would
elect people to negotiate with Israel on a five-year autonomy plan.
Talks on the final status of the territories would begin in the
third year.
   Shamir said he wanted agreement with a ``Palestinian body''
before the balloting to ensure that those elected would not
``proclaim themselves the government of Palestine, or something
like that.''
   He did not make clear what ``body'' he had in mind but repeated
his government's refusal to negotiate with the PLO, which Israel
considers a terrorist organization.
   ``It will have to be a Palestinian body. Perhaps if Egypt and
Jordan will want to join, we will welcome them,'' Shamir said. The
West Bank was captured from Jordan, the Gaza Strip from Egypt.
   Today is Memorial Day in honor of Israel's war dead. In a speech
in observance of the day, Shamir said the creation of a Palestinian
state was out of the question because it would bring a
``Beirut-like situation in the very midst of our country.''
   ``The reality of the Middle East is that we must be a strong
nation,'' he told the United Israel Appeal, a group of Jews from
around the world.
   ``First strength, then peace,'' Shamir said.
   He told the Post that for elections to take place, Israel also
must convince Palestinians that it can crush the 17-month uprising
against Israeli occupation.
   The uprising, in which 465 Palestinians and 21 Israelis have
been killed, is seen in the occupied lands as the reason why
sympathy with the Palestinian cause has grown around the world.
   Shamir also said he would oppose having international observers
for the elections, as suggested by some Palestinians.
   ``We are sure if we proclaim general, free and democratic
elections, then that's the way it will be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
