<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BordenRecall     05-09 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Borden Recall,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Borden Dairy Products Recalled for Fear of Contamination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borden Inc. removed milk and other dairy
products from stores in Louisiana and Mississippi for fear they
might be contaminated, but officials in both states said they
believed there was no health threat.
   Borden, the world's largest dairy company, pulled the products
off store shelves Monday in north Louisiana and throughout
Mississippi after learning that milk from 32 northwest Louisiana
and east Texas dairies might contain traces of a barium substance
used in rat poison.
   However, Gwen Stewart, a spokeswoman for the Louisiana
Department of Health and Hospitals, said officials believed no milk
containing dangerous amounts of barium carbonate got as far as
store shelves.
   ``The bottom line is, there is not and has not been any
contaminated milk on the market,'' she said.
   Dr. Ed Thompson of the Mississippi Department of Health said the
traces of barium carbonate found in Mississippi were too small to
be dangerous.
   ``There's just not a significant health risk involved,''
Thompson said in Jackson, Miss.
   Ms. Stewart said some milk with traces of barium was allowed on
the market, but it was considered an acceptable level _ less than
half that allowed in drinking water.
   There were no reports of illness stemming from contaminated milk.
   Deaths of cattle at an east Texas dairy farm on April 22 and a
Louisiana dairy farm on April 24 led officials in those states to
withhold milk produced at those farms, Ms. Stewart said.
   A check with a Purina feed mill in Shreveport revealed that feed
used by the two farms had been carried in a rail car that had been
used to carry barium carbonate.
   Barium carbonate is a white powder used in rat poison and in a
variety of processes, including manufacture of some kinds of glass
and ceramics, according to the Mississippi Emergency Management
Agency. It is toxic if swallowed.
   Ms. Stewart said frozen milk samples revealed the presence of
barium _ from two parts per million to five parts per million.
   She said there are no standards set for barium in milk. However,
she and Borden spokeswoman Chris Tilton said government standards
for water limit barium to one part per million.
   Ms. Tilton, contacted at Borden's headquarters in Columbus,
Ohio, said the company did not know whether any of the milk, ice
cream and other products it distributed to stores was contaminated,
but decided to withdraw them after learning Louisiana tests
detected barium.
</TEXT>
