<FIRST>r i PM-China-Quakes     05-09 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Quakes,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes in Southern China Kill One, Injure Up to 91</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earthquakes that shook Yunnan province in
southwest China over the weekend left at least one person dead,
injured as many as 91 people and destroyed about 5,000 homes,
official media reported today.
   The earthquakes, the strongest measuring 6.3 on the Richter
scale Sunday in the mountainous areas of Gengma county, also
damaged 17 reservoirs, five power stations and 110 miles of roads,
the state-run Xinhua News Agency said. About 575 acres of farmland
were ``severely affected'' by the quake.
   The quakes caused more than $54 million in damage, the report
said.
   Xinhua reported only 11 people injured, but the official
English-language China Daily, quoting the Yunnan Provincial
Ministry of Civil Affairs, said 91 were hurt in the quake,
including 20 who received serious injuries.
   A provincial ministry official reached by telephone from Beijing
refused to say how many people were injured.
   The quake-prone region near the Burmese border, which is largely
inhabated by members of the farming Va and Dai minorities, was
devasted in November by a temblor measuring 7.6 on the Richter
scale that killed 730 people.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, and each increase of one number means the ground motion
is 10 times greater. A magnitude 6 quake can cause severe damage in
populated areas while a magnitude 7 temblor is capable of
widespread, heavy damage.
</TEXT>
