<FIRST>r a PM-DeadlyFish     05-09 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deadly Fish,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rotting Fish Kill Two Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a fishing boat apparently turned off
the refrigeration to thaw up to 16 tons of tuna, but the rotting
fish created a lethal gas that killed two of the men, a Coast Guard
investigator said.
   A cloud of hydrogen sulfide overcame the captain and the
engineer when they entered the hold, Lt. Cmdr. Phil Dyer said
Monday. A third crewman, Lawrence Moon of Micronesia, abandoned
ship in a life raft 300 hundred miles off Hawaii.
   The boat had left Samoa April 23 after failing to sell its catch
and sailed for Hawaii 2,300 miles away, Dyer said. After turning
off the refrigeration, crew members threw as much of the fish
overboard as they could, he said.
   When the odor forced the crew out of the hold, Dyer said, they
tried to wash the fish out, but the screens clogged. On April 30,
the captain went below to try to clear the screens, followed by the
engineer. Both died in the hold.
   The bodies of the captain, David James Dowie, and the engineer,
Martin Ferguson, both of Alaska, were removed from the vessel
Sunday after it was towed to Honolulu. Moon was picked up by a
Japanese vessel.
   Chemicals were pumped into the hold to neutralize the gas before
the vessel was allowed to enter port.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
