<FIRST>r a PM-Weapons-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0499 05-09 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weapons-Philippines, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0499,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arms Smuggler Admits Trying to Get Weapons to Marcos Backers In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to raise sentence; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs,
`Dicker was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 69-year-old former Army captain has been
placed on three years' probation and fined $10,000 for conspiring
to ship weapons to forces loyal to former Philippine President
Ferdinand Marcos.
   U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner Jr. on Monday also ordered
Leon Dicker to perform 600 hours of community service.
   Dicker pleaded guilty Monday, admitting he tried to make the
shipments in 1987, months before two coup attempts failed to return
Marcos to power.
   Dicker was convicted in 1987 and sentenced to four years in
prison, but a federal appeals court ruled that testimony was
improperly introduced and overturned the verdict.
   Gemmo Trinidad, Marcos' spokesman in Hawaii, said he had not
heard of the case and could not comment on it.
   Known as ``The General'' to his associates, Dicker was an Army
captain in World War II and is a disbarred Hewlett, N.Y., attorney.
He said he believed it would be in the United States' interest to
ship the arms to the Philippines.
   Marcos fled the Philippines Feb. 26, 1986, amid an uprising that
carried Corazon Aquino to power.
   Dicker was arrested in 1987 in a sting operation as he drove to
what he believed was a warehouse containing the weapons.
   The indictment said he conspired to ship M-60 machine guns and
Israeli-made Uzi submachine guns to Thailand. Dicker told the court
that Thailand was identified as a destination only to obtain an
export license.
   Federal law requires that arms exports be licensed by the State
Department.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Claudia J. Flynn said an investigation
was continuing in the case. She supported the judge's request for
no prison time, citing Dicker's cooperation with the investigation
and his age.
</TEXT>
