<FIRST>u w AM-ShipFire     05-09 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Fire,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire On Navy Ship Kills Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six sailors were killed and five were injured
today when fire broke out aboard a U.S. Navy combat supply ship in
the South China Sea, a Navy spokeswoman said.
   ``It appeared to be a fuel leak,'' the spokeswoman said,
declining to be further identified. The ship was identified as the
USS White Plains, which normally carries a crew of about 428
officers and enlisted men.
   The spokeswoman said the fire broke out at 2 a.m. EDT in the
main engine spaces ``while conducting operations'' at an
undetermined location in the South China Sea. She said the five
injured were evacuated by helicopter to the U.S.S. Sacramento.
   According to the authoritative reference work Jane's Fighting
Ships, the White Plains is 581 feet long and displaces 9.400 tons.
It was commissioned Nov. 23, 1968.
</TEXT>
