<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Switzerland-Drugs     05-09 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Switzerland-Drugs,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Drug Deaths Reach Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deaths from drug abuse rose to a record
high of 205 last year, authorities said today.
   Rudolf Wyss, chief of the Federal Narcotics Police, said the
death rate per capita in Switzerland was far higher than in
neighboring European states. He said there was no explanation for
this.
   In West Germany, which has 10 times the population of
Switzerland, there were 674 drug-related deaths last year, he said.
   Over the past 10 years more than 1,500 people in Switzerland
have died from drug abuse. After a drop in the number of fatalities
in the middle of the decade, the death rate has risen sharply since
1986.
   Although most deaths are due to heroin addiction, Wyss said the
most significant feature in 1988 was a glut of cocaine. South
American suppliers have turned to Europe because of plummeting
prices on the drug-saturated U.S. market, he said.
   Wyss said there was little sign of crack cocaine, the highly
addictive drug used widely in the United States. He said only two
grams were seized in Switzerland last year.
</TEXT>
