<FIRST>r a PM-SkidRow-Moms     05-09 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Skid Row-Moms,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skid Row Moms Treated To Mother's Day Makeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Pansy in 4th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless shelter is honoring the moms of
Skid Row by opening a temporary beauty salon where professional
makeup artists, hair stylists and manicurists are giving homeless
women complete makeovers.
   About 200 women came to the Fred Jordan Mission on Monday for
the makeovers, which will be offered through Thursday along with
new clothes and hot lunches at tables with tablecloths.
   ``Sometimes you got to take the makeup off and just look like
one of the fellas to make it down here,'' said Katheryn Burroughs,
a 27-year-old mother getting her hair styled for the first time in
nearly two years. ``But I'm still a woman, and I like to remember
that.''
   Mission staffer Pansy Newbill said the makeovers, done just
before Mothers Day, were an effort to brighten the lives of the
women on Skid Row.
   ``We've seen so much need among the women that we decided to do
something special for them,'' she said.
   But looking good on Skid Row can be dangerous, some of the women
said.
   ``Most of the guys, when you're pretty, they think you're
working the streets. And if you're not working, they get pretty
rough with you,'' said Sherry Wright, 38, who is pregnant.
   ``I've got a guy living with me now that poses as my boyfriend
just so guys will leave me alone. Daytime's not so bad. Only when
the sun goes down.''
</TEXT>
