<FIRST>r a PM-SuicideMixup     05-09 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Suicide Mixup,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suicide Hotline Mixup Mystifies Businesswoman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LaVon Davis says she's still
answering the phone, but apprehensively, since the toll-free number
for her craft shop was advertised as a suicide prevention hotline.
   Davis said Monday she and an employee at her House of France
have received 15 to 20 calls from despondent people in the two
weeks since the number appeared on television. One call came Friday
from someone ``who just wanted to talk.''
   ``It just seemed like these calls would always come in when we
were in the back,'' Davis said. ``We'd run like 60 to get up here
... and it'd be one of these people.''
   Mental health officials have given Davis their numbers to pass
along to callers, she said. She has no plans to change her number.
   ``We've had this number for eight or 10 years,'' she said. ``I'd
have to print all new stationery, and my customers might not
remember the new number. ... I'm just taking a wait-and-see
attitude.''
   The source of the ad remained a mystery. There is no statewide
toll-free suicide hotline. Thomas DeLoach, a Department of Mental
Health spokesman, said he was checking into national organizations
that might have produced the ad.
</TEXT>
