<FIRST>r a PM-SaginawShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0509 05-09 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saginaw Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disgruntled Landlord Fires Shotgun Through City Hall Window</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5 pvs, `Mike Thompson ...' with one graf to CORRECT
by deleting that the building was unlicensed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAGINAW, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord ejected from a City Council
meeting fired a shotgun blast through a City Hall window, barely
missing the mayor and other officials, police said.
   ``I didn't realize that being the mayor of Saginaw would involve
this much danger,'' Mayor Delbert Schrems said after Monday
evening's shooting.
   The slug passed about a foot over his head before lodging in the
ceiling. The gunman was arrested in a bar about 45 minutes later,
said Lt. Robert Rosenberg. He said formal charges would probably be
filed today.
   Mike Thompson, a Saginaw News reporter at the meeting, said the
landlord had been ordered to close an unlicensed apartment. The man
spoke to the council for about five minutes, using profanity.
Schrems finally ordered police to remove him.
   Rosenberg said the man went to his car, pulled out a shotgun and
fired from about 200 feet away through a second-story window.
   Two City Council members, both former law officers, shouted for
others in the room to lie down, then ran to the window and got a
description of the car in which the man fled. The meeting was
immediately adjourned.
   Schrems was elected in 1987, three months after a neighbor was
charged with making bomb threats to Schrems' home. ``This is the
second time my life has been threatened, and I really don't know
how to deal with it right now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
