<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 2ndLd-Writethru a0532 05-09 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0532,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strike Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `A tornado ...' to CORRECT Alabama to Arkansas.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled over the south-central part of the nation
early today, dropping heavy rain and spawning tornadoes in Oklahoma
and Mississippi that destroyed homes and knocked out power.
   Storms extended from Oklahoma and northeastern Texas across
Arkansas and Louisiana to Mississippi.
   A tornado in eastern Oklahoma near the Arkansas border destroyed
at least a dozen homes, knocked down power lines and blew trees
onto roads Monday evening, authorities said. No serious injuries
were reported.
   A tornado touched down near the front gate of the Mississippi
State Penitentiary at Parchman, injuring a guard and destroying
three mobile homes, prison officials said. A prison spokesman said
the guard was in stable conditon. The National Weather Service said
it hadn't confirmed if it was a tornado or high wind.
   A twister was sighted six miles from the prison, but no damage
was reported. Marble-size hail, 60 mph wind and uprooted trees were
reported elsewhere in the state.
   As much as 5 inches of rain fell overnight around Clarksdale,
Miss., causing minor flooding that blocked some streets and
highways and extensive damage to newly planted cotton fields.
   Stuttgart, Ark., got 5 inches of rain this morning, including 3
inches in just two hours, the weather service said. Severe
thunderstorms late Monday dropped dime-size hail in Iowa and golf
ball-size hail at Goodland, Kan.
   Rain extended eastward into much of the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys and over much of Alabama and Georgia.
   Elsewhere, showers dampened Wyoming and Colorado. Showers and a
few thunderstorms extended over California and Oregon.
   In Arizona, Phoenix hit 110 degrees Monday, breaking a
104-degree record set in 1934 and marking the earliest date in the
year that temperature has been reached.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast, the Tennessee and Ohio
valleys, the Appalachians and much of the East Coast; possible
severe thunderstorms over central Mississippi, northern and central
Alabama and northern Georgia; and widely scattered thunderstorms
across parts of the West Coast, eastern Colorado and western Kansas.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s in the middle and
northern Atlantic Coast, the Appalachians, the Ohio Valley, the
Great Lakes, the middle and upper Mississippi Valley and the
Pacific Coast; in the 90s from southern Texas across southern New
Mexico; near 100 in the Desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 30 degrees at Traverse
City, Mich., and Duluth, Minn., to 89 degrees at Phoenix and
Glendale, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 57 rain; Boston 45 fair; Buffalo 39 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 59 fair; Cincinnati 52 rain; Cleveland 50 cloudy;
Detroit 52 cloudy; Miami 74 fair; New York 45 fair; Philadelphia 45
fair; Pittsburgh 47 cloudy; Portland, Maine 43 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 fair; Chicago 47 foggy; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 fair; Denver 51 drizzle; Des Moines 50 rain; Indianapolis 52
rain; Kansas City 55 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 40 fair; Nashville
59 cloudy; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 61 rain.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 fair; Anchorage 40 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 81 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 62 partly cloudy; Phoenix 86
fair; Salt Lake City 59 partly cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San
Francisco 55 drizzle; Seattle 54 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 cloudy; Toronto 36 fair.
</TEXT>
