<FIRST>r a PM-AmputeeSlaying     05-09 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amputee Slaying,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted In Amputee's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handyman has been convicted of murder
in the death of an elderly amputee who suffered a fatal heart
attack while being raped.
   Jeffrey Washington, 32, could receive life in prison without
parole because the jury ruled Monday the case involved aggravated
battery. No sentencing date was set.
   Relatives discovered Alice Carcieri, 73, dead in her bed the day
after the attack on Christmas night 1987.
   Washington, who sometimes did chores for Carcieri, told police
that the woman had told him she was depressed and hated the
holidays because she didn't have anybody, and he interpreted that
to mean she wanted sex.
   Neighbors and relatives testified Carcieri, whose legs were
amputated several years ago, was a very religious woman who never
dated and never married. They said Carcieri did not seem depressed
as the holidays approached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     05-09 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Chief To Resign On May 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal reformer Stipe Suvar will
step down as Communist Party chief next week to take a seat in the
collective presidency, and retain an influential role in national
affairs.
   News reports said today Suvar will resign as head of the party
on May 17.
   Because the party leadership rotates annually, Suvar would have
had to give up that post next month in any case. Beginning in June,
the leadership transfers to a party official from the republic of
Macedonia.
   Suvar recently was elected to represent the republic of Croatia
in the nine-man presidency, and a party regulation adopted last
year forbids officials from holding state and party jobs
simultaneously.
   Suvar is to be formally inaugurated as a member of the federal
presidency on May 15. This assures Suvar a continued role on the
national political stage, where he is battling his Serbian
political rival, Slobodan Milosevic.
   Milosevic is a more authoritarian, orthodox Communist than
Suvar, although both men have backed market-oriented reforms to try
and ease Yugoslavia's economic crisis.
   Milosevic on Monday was proclaimed president of the republic of
Serbia, which allows him to play a figurehead role in Yugoslavia's
largest republic, where he is already a hero for strengthening
Serbian influence in the nation.
   But Milosevic's new post does not give him a seat in the federal
presidency, and he will have to give up his position as a member of
the party's national Politburo now that he has become head of state
in Serbia.
   Suvar and Milosevic have battled over political issues, but
their disputes also reflect ethnic divides between the Serbs, the
dominant ethnic group in Yugoslavia's patchwork of nationalities,
and the rival Croats and other northern people.
   Yugoslavia's late leader, Josip Broz Tito, bequeathed the
current political maze with the 1974 Constitution that attempted to
prevent any one of the country's republics or nationalities from
dominating national affairs.
   But Milosevic has strengthened Serbian authority in the province
of Kosovo, where the ethnic Albanian majority rioted against
Milosevic's policies in March clashes that left at least 24 dead.
   Media reports today quoted Suvar as saying that ``because of the
political quarrels within the party, tomorrow we could have brutal
clashes'' because of the mounting economic and political strife.
Yugoslavia suffers an annual inflation rate of about 500 percent,
which has helped to fuel ethnic tensions.
   Suvar also complained that during his term as the party leader,
the Serbian daily newspaper Politika, believed to be controlled by
Milosevic's supporters, has bitterly criticized him in 700 articles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
