<FIRST>r i PM-China-Iran     05-09 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Iran,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian President Calls for Closer Ties with China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran, the first
fundamentalist leader of his country to visit communist China,
called today for closer trade and cultural ties with Beijing.
   ``Our great revolution has led to the emergence of new points of
agreement between us and you,'' Khamenei said at a banquet given in
his honor by Chinese President Yang Shangkun. Khamenei also met
with Premier Li Peng, according to the official Xinhua News Agency.
   China sold Tehran about $1 billion worth of arms during Iran's
war with Iraq, including missiles and jet fighters, according to
Western officials. Iran and China, which also has good ties to
Iraq, both deny the arms traffic.
   Now that the war has ended, Iran is looking for Chinese help to
rebuild its economy. Since a cease-fire began in August, China and
Iran have signed agreements to build a dam and two major power
plants in Iran and to share communication technology.
   In his banquet speech, Khamenei recalled the early development
of sea and overland trade between China and Iran, then called
Persia.
   ``We believe there is a need to further develop and deepen our
economic, trade, technical and cultural relations,'' he said.
   Xinhua quoted Li as expressing similar hopes.
   Khamenei was to meet Wednesday with Communist Party General
Secretary Zhao Ziyang. He will visit North Korea after six days in
China.
</TEXT>
