<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua     05-09 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Calls for Renewed Military Aid for Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole today called
for resumption of ``significant military aid'' to Contra rebels if
the leftist government in Nicaragua fails to hold a free election
and abide by its results.
   Testifying before the privately financed Commission on Free and
Fair Elections in Nicaragua, the Kansas senator said he is not
optimistic about the outlook for next year's balloting.
   The panel of three Democrats and three Republicans was
established by the World Freedom Foundation, a self-styled research
and educational organization based in Alexandria, Va.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega signed an agreement with El
Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica in February in which
he promised electoral and other legal reforms to ensure fair
general elections, which are to be held in February. Last week,
however, the Sandinista government rejected an opposition demand to
negotiate further reforms.
   ``In my view,'' Dole said, ``by far the best way to keep
pressure on the Sandinistas would have been to continue effective
aid to the freedom fighters,'' the term given to the Contras by
their supporters in the United States. ``But realistically, that is
not an option for the immediate future.''
   Congress ended military aid to the Contra rebels at the end of
February 1988.
   ``And I am not optimistic that there are enough remaining points
of leverage to put real heat on Managua to live up to its own
commitments, and its responsibility to the citizens of Nicaragua. I
hope I am wrong.''
   ``I hope so. But, candidly, I am not very optimistic,'' Dole
said. ``The record so far _ as manifest, for example, in the sham
of a new elelction law recnetly promulgated by the comandantes _ is
hardly encouraging.''
   ``What if next February comes and goes, and there is no free
elelction, perhaps not even any election?'' Dole asked. ``What if
the Sandinistas `win' the election through fraud, or lose the
elelction but refuse to yield power ...?
   In that event, he said, ``I hope that we will articulate and
implement a policy that will apply direct and effective pressure on
the Sandinistas, including through the resumption of significant
military aid to a revitalized Democratic resistance.''
   The Bush administration has abandoned plans to seek immediate
military aid, which was the consistent policy of the Reagan
administration, and recently reached a bipartisan agreement with
Congress providing for non-military assistance.
   The World Freedom Foundation is headed by L. Brent Bozell III, a
prominent conservative. The co-chairmen of the commission are
Curtin Winsor Jr., former U.S. ambassador to Costa Rica in the
Reagan administration; Gaylord Nelson, former Democratic senator
from Wisconsin; Sergio Bendixen, a Democratic political consultant;
Alan Keyes, former assistant secretary of state for international
organization affairs in the Reagan administration; Elaine Kamarck,
a Democratic political consultant; and Victor Gold, who served as
an advisor to President Bush in 1980 and 1984.
</TEXT>
