<FIRST>r i PM-Zambia-ANC     05-09 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zambia-ANC,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zambia Warns Law-Breaking ANC Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government vowed today to prosecute
law-breaking African National Congress guerrillas but said it will
not disarm them.
   Alex Shapi, defense and security secretary, said his government
expects guerrillas taking refuge in Zambia to abide by the laws of
this southern African nation.
   Shapi's statement came after a guerrilla of the South African
nationalist movement on Sunday shot and killed his Zambian
girlfriend, then turned his AK47 assault rifle on himself.
   ``Where they contravene the law, we will take action,'' Shapi
said.
   He said authorities will not seize guerrillas' weapons because
``not all of them lack discipline.''
   The ANC, the main guerrilla organization fighting the South
African government, has its external headquarters in Lusaka.
   In the past four years, the guerrillas have lost many southern
African bases as Pretoria has negotiated rapprochement with nearby
black governments, or bombed countries like Botswana and Zimbabwe,
where it charges the ANC have bases used to plan attacks on South
Africa. Botswana and Zimbabwe say they give sanctuary only to
unarmed ANC officials and South African exiles.
   ANC bases in Lesotho, Mozambique, Swaziland, and most recently
this year in Angola, have been shut down as the black-ruled nations
signed non-aggression pacts with Pretoria. About 6,000 ANC fighters
were transferred from Angola to Tanzania in East Africa.
</TEXT>
