<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     05-09 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Demand Dialogue, Students Demonstrate Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Students, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists for China's official media gave the
government a petition Tuesday with more than 1,000 signatures
calling for a dialogue on censorship, while hundreds of students
chanted their support.
   ``Restrictions of every kind have prevented full, objective and
fair reporting'' on recent student protests for democratic reform,
said the petition. It was a rare expression of discontent by
China's reporters, many of whom are members of the ruling Communist
Party.
   The petition said there was a need for party propaganda
officials to meet with reporters on censorship and the recent
firing of the editor of China's most liberal paper after he
rejected censors' demands.
   Li Datong, an editor at the China Youth News and organizer of
the petition, later said he heard reports that Hu Qili, a top party
official responsible for media affairs, already had agreed to a
dialogue.
   ``We don't hope for this dialogue to have direct results,'' he
said. ``Such things are achieved by a process. But we think this
dialogue will be a good beginning.''
   Hundreds of journalists jammed the offices of the All-China
Journalists Association, a government-sponsored organization, to
hand in the petition with 1,013 signatures. Signers included
reporters from the Xinhua News Agency, the People's Daily and China
Central Television.
   Outside, about 500 students from Beijing University and other
schools waved banners on press freedom and chanted, ``The media
should tell the truth.''
   Yang Yi, an official at the Journalists Association who accepted
the petitition, said he would give it to party officials and would
try to help organize a dialogue. He also promised the associaton
would ``make efforts for media reform.''
   Li said he thought it was possible Shanghai authorities would
reinstate Qin Benli, the editor of the weekly World Economic
Herald, but only if more appeals are made on his behalf. Under Qin,
the Herald printed more lively, controversial articles than any
other Chinese publication, and his dismissal has caused outcries
from journalists, students and other academics.
   ``We are very embarrassed by our position during such a
large-scale student movement that aroused concern domestically and
overseas,'' said Guo Jiakuan, a reporter for China Youth News.
   The official media initially maintained silence on the student
protests that began April 15 and were the largest in 40 years of
communist rule. Xinhua later issued brief reports on the protests
and only a few newspapers made clear the huge scale of the marches
and the broad support from ordinary citizens.
   Many reporters attended the marches and handed in stories and
photographs but said their editors decided not to use most of it
for fear it would fuel the protests.
   Even Xinhua's report of the journalists' petition bore the
censor's mark. In quoting from the petition, Xinhua removed
references to ``restrictions'' and deleted the journalists' denial
that China has a free press. It added of the reporters' complaints,
``This is just a problem to be solved during the reform of the news
reporting system.''
   ``The students rely on the foreign press to promote China's
democracy,'' complained a woman from the Academy of Social
Science's News Research Department. ``This is a disgrace for the
Chinese press.''
   One of the key demands of the students is a free press.
   The students who gathered outside the Journalists Association
said they wanted to support the reporters' petition. The students
also are demanding their own dialogue with government leaders on a
broad range of political reforms, including guarantee of human
rights.
   ``We are extremely thankful for your support in our struggle,''
Li told the students.
   The students, who arrived on bicycle with red flags and banners
flying, regrouped in nearby Tiananmen Square, where tens of
thousands of students have rallied in the past three weeks. Then
they bicycled across town to hold an hour-long sit-in outside the
offices of the People's Daily, the mouthpiece of the ruling
Communist Party.
   ``Editor-in-chief, come out!'' they chanted. They also quoted
from writings of senior leader Deng Xiaoping saying society should
be changed democratically, not by violence.
   Student leader Wu'er Kaixi said in a speech directed at those in
the People's Daily office: ``Television, newspapers and radio must
speak the truth. The people no longer believe you. Reform
yourselves.''
   Student activists said they planned similar protests at the
offices of China Central Television and Xinhua.
</TEXT>
