<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Students Bjt   05-09 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Students, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing University Students Try to Keep Flame of Democracy Alight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beijing University students, proud of their
school's rich history of leading revolutionary and nationalist
campaigns, desperately are trying to keep alive the democracy
movement that has lost steam on other campuses.
   ``It has a long history of fighting for democracy,'' one
undergraduate said during a Monday night campus march to drum up
support for a 2-week-old class boycott. ``Beijing University is
always at the vanguard of the student movements.''
   Its students are remembered for leading the landmark May 4,
1919, uprising in which intellectuals demanded democracy and
science to modernize China.
   Now, 70 years later, Beijing University students have emerged as
the keeper of the flame of a nearly month-old movement for more
freedom in this authoritarian society.
   ``All of China watches Beijing. All of Beijing watches Beijing
University,'' one poster said after most other campuses ended the
class boycott this past weekend.
   Activists no longer talk of staging more mass marches that
brought tens of thousands of people into the capital's streets, but
say they will print newspapers and pamphlets to press their views.
   However, many of the more than 10,000 students at Beijing
University, the nation's most prestigious school, are hanging
tough. They argue that further pressure on the government is needed
to open a dialogue with communist officials to demand press freedom
and a halt to corruption.
   Within hours of the announcement that student activists planned
to end the citywide class strike, angry posters emerged at Beijing
University urging students to ``boycott to the end.'' Students
quickly voted to continue the strike until at least Friday, and
perhaps two-thirds of them stayed away from class Monday.
   About 1,300 Beijing University students staged a noisy march
around campus late Monday, chanting ``One, two, boycott class,''
and urging teachers to join. Some said they hope their continued
defiance will convince other major universities to resume the
boycott.
   ``This school is the seed of the democracy movement,'' said one
marcher, explaining why many Beijing University students have
refused to follow others back to class.
   ``I want to go to class, we all do,'' said another, ``but we
can't because we haven't got any real results.''
   On Tuesday, students at two other universities were planning to
rejoin Beijing University and resume the boycott, and a new wave of
the big character posters that provide a primary means of political
expression appeared.
   Some Beijing University students said they are considering a
bicycle procession through Beijing.
   Beijing University students remain feisty for several reasons.
Students say they have not experienced the strong pressure to end
the strike applied by authorities at other schools.
   Pride in the 90-year-old school for its leadership in previous
campaigns by intellectuals to awaken the masses also has spurred
the students to action.
   The school was set up as the Peking Imperial University in 1898,
during the ``100-Day Reform'' movement that attempted to introduce
some Western ideas in government and education to the fast
declining Qing dynasty.
   Among major personalities at the school in its first decades
were Chen Duxiu, a father of Chinese leftism, and Li Dazhao, one of
China's first Marxists. When he was school librarian, one of Li's
assistants was a country boy named Mao Tse-tung.
   Mao went on to establish the People's Republic of China in 1949.
Eight years later, when he encouraged critics to speak out, Beijing
University teachers declared that ``the masses want to overthrow
the Communist Party.'' They were among the first to be purged in a
subsequent crackdown.
   The school occupies 500 acres of wooded land in northwest
Beijing. It includes imperial-style buildings with red pillars and
slanted tiled roofs, as well as blocks of dank and dreary
dormitories where each room houses about six students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
