<FIRST>r w AM-Reich-Israel     05-09 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reich-Israel,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reich Urges Allowing Palestinians to Call for Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top American Jewish leader said Tuesday that
Palestinian participants in proposed elections should not be banned
from the elective process for advocating an independent state for
their people.
   ``I would not think that advocating such a position would be a
bar to being elected or engaging in the elective process,'' Seymour
Reich told reporters at the National Press Club.
   Reich is head of the national B'nai B'rith organization and
chairman of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Groups.
   His comments came in reaction to an interview with Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, published Tuesday by the Jerusalem Post,
in which Shamir said that Palestinians who run in elections that he
has proposed must agree that the occupied lands will not become an
independent Palestinian nation.
   Shamir told the newspaper the agreement would apply to an
interim period of autonomy in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and to
negotiations on the final status of the territories, seized by
Israel in 1967.
   ``If elections are to be conducted they have to be conducted in
a free atmosphere of speech, without threat of violence or
intimidation. And I would think someone seeking office, running on
a platform, can espouse any position that they want to including
land for peace, including an independent Palestinian state. I don't
see anything objectionable to that,'' Reich said.
   ``I think anyone can run as long as they are not terrorists or
identified as such,'' he added.
   Reich met with reporters to mark the 41st anniversary of the
founding of Israel, an event being celebrated starting at sundown
Tuesday.
   After 41 years of ``fighting in a sea of hostile countries,'' he
said, ``this tiny island of a state continues to exist in a
democratic environment.''
   Reich gave President Bush a rating of 98 in his dealings with
Israel, saying that ``98 out of 100 is not bad.''
   Bush has made many positive steps in working toward peace in the
Middle East, Reich said.
   The reason Bush got 98 instead of 100, Reich said, was because
of a statement opposing the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip which did not also note that the areas were occupied as a
defensive measure, not out of aggression.
   While Shamir has suggested previously that he might ask for such
an agreement by Palestinian candidates avoiding calls for
independence, his interview was his most wide-ranging statement on
his plan.
   Leading Palestinians in the occupied lands and the Palestine
Liberation Organization have said any elections must be part of a
plan leading to Palestinian independence.
</TEXT>
