<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     05-09 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Says He Intends to Keep Traveling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has dismissed criticism of his
foreign pilgrimages as ``prejudice'' and says he intends to keep
traveling.
   In an interview published Tuesday, he expressed hope of being
able to visit other countries in Eastern Europe besides his native
Poland, noting the winds of change blowing in the Communist bloc.
   ``I think we are talking often of prejudice,'' John Paul was
quoted as saying in the interview with an Italian newspaper group.
He returned Saturday from Africa, the 41st foreign trip in his
10{-year pontificate.
   At the start of his papacy, John Paul said, some at the Vatican
had advised against a visit to a meeting of Latin American bishops
in Mexico, which his predecessor, John Paul I, had decided not to
attend.
   ``It seemed to me that the pope should be present at that
important appointment of the church in Latin America,'' he said.
The trip in January 1979 was John Paul's first foreign pilgrimage.
   He acknowledged that ``some in the West, in Europe'' have
accused him of ``triumphalism (which) blocks the ecumenical
process'' and suggested it would be better for him to engage in
dialogue than draw crowds.
   But that is what he does, John Paul said, citing his meeting
with American bishops when he visited the United States in 1987 and
the recent meeting with a delegation of U.S. bishops at the
Vatican, which he termed ``very useful.''
   ``It's not dialogue what I will be doing within a few weeks with
the Lutheran brothers in Scandinavia?'' he asked, referring to his
next pilgrimage that begins June 1.
   John Paul said he's convinced the trips are useful.
   He noted that besides his three pilgrimages to Poland he has not
been able to go ``beyond the eastern frontier'' of Europe.
   ``I think, however, that with all that is happening there ... it
will be the circumstances, as always, to decide. I have always felt
myself guided by circumstances, that is, by Providence.''
</TEXT>
