<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Baker     05-09 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,390</SECOND>
<UNK>Baker Meets President Koivisto Before Moscow Visit</UNK>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III,
on a stopover here for his trip to Moscow, discussed Soviet affairs
and international relations Tuesday with Finnish President Mauno
Koivisto.
   Neutral Finland has traditionally close ties and a friendship
treaty with the Soviet Union. Koivisto was in Moscow last October.
   At a luncheon, ``both Baker and President Koivisto expressed the
wish to see a continuation in perestroika,'' said Arno Karhilo,
Foreign Ministry undersecretary of state.
   Baker also met separately with Prime Minister Harri Holkeri.
   Arriving here Monday night, Baker praised the state of
U.S.-Finnish relations and lauded the Finnish contribution to the
U.N. peacekeeping forces which he said ``give this country an
important role in many global issues of interest to both our
countries.''
   Baker heads to Moscow on Wednesday, seeking President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's help in forging peace in the Middle East and playing
down the issue of arms control.
   Baker is trying to prod Israel into negotiations with the
Palestinians and has concluded he needs the support of both Moscow
and the Palestine Liberation Organization. He is hoping the Soviets
under Gorbachev would bring the pressure it has refused to exert in
the past on Syria to support peace talks that do not hold out the
promise of a Palestinian state.
   On the arms control front, Baker heads to Moscow with a date _
the third week in June _ for the reopening of U.S.-Soviet
negotiations to reduce the superpowers' long-range bombers, nuclear
submarines and globe-girdling missiles.
   But he was not planning to outline the position the United
States would take at the table. Nor was he assuring the Soviets
that there would be no changes since the talks were recessed in
November.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Soviets ``can expect to see a considerable degree of continuity
with the positions of the prior administration'' but added: ``we
reserve the right to change and modify some of those positions.''
   The two sides had about 90 percent of a weapons-reduction treaty
completed when the talks recessed. But several knotty issues stood
in the way of an agreement.
   These included whether to try to ban mobile intercontinental
ballistic missiles and how to verify arsenals of cruise missiles
aboard ships and warplanes.
</TEXT>
