<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Panama 5thLd-Writethru   05-09 1077</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0558, 1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Joins Members of Congress in Denouncing Noriega Election Tactics</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Updates with 10 grafs to update, picks up graf 2 pvs ``He didn't
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today weighed options ranging
from military intervention to economic actions toward Panama in
reaction to an election U.S. officials say was riddled with fraud,
his spokesman said.
   White House Press secretary Marlin Fitzwater would not elaborate
on the possible options but hinted that provisions of the 1977
Panama Canal treaties might be used to intensify pressures against
Panama's defacto ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The bottom line U.S. posistion remains that ``Noriega must go,''
Fitzwater said.
   ``We are convinced that the oppossition candidates had the
support and the votes to fairly win this election and we are just
as convinced that the Noriega regime made every effort, took every
opportunity and had every intention of stealing this election
regardless of the actual vote,'' Fitzwater said of Sunday's
ballotting.
   In a formal statement read to White House reporters, the
spokesman said the United States has been considering options
``that range from the use of military force to varoius economic and
commerical moves related to United States pressure in that
country.''
   He said U.S. officials are in contact with democratic allies in
the region, seeking to enlist their support for the anti-Noriega
move.
   ``There is no plan to abrogate the canal treaties,'' under which
the United States has agreed to turn the American-built canal over
to Panamanian control on the last day of this century, Fitzwater
said. ``However we do have concerns about how they are carried
out.''
   He mentioned provisions dealing with protection of U.S. citizens
in the isthmus and the sea-to-sea strategic canal itself, saying
``Those could be very useful,'' to the United States in its
dealings with Noriega.
   Fitzwater said U.S. troops in Panama are on ``a very high state
of alert.''
   Fitzwater made the comments after Bush was briefed by members of
an official observer team that he sent to monitor the election
Sunday.
   ``He didn't leave anything out of the discussion. Every
conceivable range of options was discussed,'' said Rep. John
Murtha, D-Pa., who headed the delegation. Former President Jimmy
Carter, who led another observer group, was to meet with the
president tonight to give his report on the Sunday elections.
   The observers reported widespread fraud to favor Carlos Duque,
the presidential candidate of Panama's de facto ruler, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``There's a lot more support for that (military) option today
than there was say six months or a year ago,'' said Sen. Connie
Mack, R-Fla., another member of the observer team.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said ``the scenario of sending tanks
in the streets of Panama City is not one tht I could foresee under
any circumstances but the option of the military ... is one that
should not be totally ruled out but at the same time should not be
embraced without totally exhausting every other option.''
   Murtha said the president listened intently but gave no
indication as to what he might do.
   ``It seemed a sense of urgency in the room. I felt that the
president feels that this is something he can't let sit ... There's
a real sense of urgency that something has to be done,'' said
Murtha.
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said he was recommending a three-part
course of action: ``internationalize'' the issue by getting Latin
American allies to join in denunciations of Noriega; develop a
bipartisan consensus on U.S. action; and prepare the ``stricter
options'' the United States might take.
   ``Time is of the essence. There's a very brief period in which
world opinion will give us the environment in which we can take the
kind of action necessary to remove Noriega,'' said Graham.
   McCain suggested beefing up the U.S. bases in Panama with more
combatants, and not ruling out any military action. He said
military dependents should be moved out of the area, and U.S.
citizens there shoudl be warned there could be problems for them.
   ``We are deeply concerned by evidence pouring in of electoral
fraud on the part of the pro-Noriega forces,'' the State Department
said Monday night, joining members of Congress in criticizing the
elections.
   Bush brushed aside reporters' questions today as he sat down
with his observer team to get a firsthand report on what they saw
during and after Sunday's ballotting.
   Some 10,000 U.S. military personnel are based in Panama at
military installations which remain under U.S. control despite the
decade-old treaty that cedes control of the Panama Canal to that
Central American country at the end of the century.
   The official State Department statement, issued 24 hours after
the polls closed in Panama, appeared to lay the groundwork for an
official announcement that the United States was not prepared to
recognize the outcome of the election if the process was perceived
to be rigged in Duque's favor.
   President Bush indicated last week he would pursue that policy
rather than move toward a more normal relationship with the
Panamanian government.
   U.S. officials expected that Panamanian authorities at some
point will declare Duque the winner but some wondered whether
Noriega will be able to survive what they regard as an obvious
embarrassment for him.
   In addition to the allegations of fraud, the election day scenes
indicated strong backing for the opposition slate.
   Observers said members of the Noriega-led Defense Forces were
allowed to vote multiple times because, unlike other Panamanians,
they were not assigned to a specific voting station.
   ``People who were dead (were) all of a sudden reappearing on
rolls, when they had been dropped off,'' said Rep. Larry Smith,
D-Fla. ``So dead people could vote, but live people couldn't.''
   Sen. Richard Lugar, ranking minority member of the Foreign
Relations Committee, said the opposition appeared to be winning a
huge majority even though many of Noriega's supporters voted more
than once.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said the United States should
join with other hemispheric countries in applying diplomatic
pressure on Panama if the election outcome is based on fraud.
   U.S. officials saw the election as perhaps the best opportunity
in almost a year to achieve its goal of removing Noriega from
Panama's political life. He was indicted by a U.S. federal grand
jury last year on drug trafficking charges.
   Officials had hoped that the elections would become an event
around which Noriega's opponents could rally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
