<FIRST>r a PM-GreenwoodShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0560 05-09 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenwood Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Sentenced to the Electric Chair For School Rampage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf with two grafs to CORRECT number of years in
prison to 175 sted 155 and ADDS that it was first sentence of its kind.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who killed two children and wounded
nine other people in a shooting rampage at a school was sentenced
to the electric chair today.
   Judge James Moore imposed the death penalty rather than life in
prison on James Wilson 12 days after the 20-year-old pleaded guilty
but mentally ill to murder and other charges in the Sept. 26 attack
at Oakland Elementary School.
   Wilson, who had a history of mental disturbances from age 14,
walked in and opened fire with a handgun in a cafeteria and
classroom, killing Shequila Bradley and Tequila Thomas, both 8.
Seven students and two teachers also were wounded.
   Psychiatrists who examined Wilson agreed on a diagnosis of
borderline personality disorder, an illness bordering on
schizophrenia. Doctors testified he was fascinated with mass murder
and knew what he was doing was wrong but could not stop himself.
   The judge also sentenced Wilson to 175 years in prison for
aggravated assault, assault and battery and carrying a weapon onto
school grounds.
   Wilson was the first person sentenced to death under South
Carolina's 1984 guilty-but-mentally-ill law, said city Solicitor W.
Townes Jones IV.
</TEXT>
