<FIRST>r a PM-InmateBracelet     05-09 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Bracelet,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advocate of Electronic Monitors for Convicts Now Wears One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKEGAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who pioneered the use of
electronic ankle bracelets to ease overcrowding at the county jail
is wearing one himself these days for misuse of funds.
   George Gallaugher, 40, brought the electronic devices to Lake
County a year ago as director of the county's Department of Court
Services.
   The bracelets send out an electronic signal that enables
authorities to know if a person leaves his assigned location. They
also allow jails to release nonviolent inmates and make room for
people accused of serious crimes.
   A grand jury accused Gallaugher of profiting from the bracelet
program, but the charge was dropped when he pleaded guilty earlier
this year to making personal use of about $15,000 in other public
funds.
   He was sentenced to 30 days and had served 12 days on
work-release Monday when his lawyer persuaded a judge to release
him with a bracelet ``like any other prisoner.''
