<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Strike 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0514,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Break Down In Copper Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with talks breaking off; picks
up 8th pvs: The strike...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks aimed at ending a strike at four
copper mines broke off today just when a settlement appeared
imminent, and labor leaders blamed authorities for backing away
from promised wage increases.
   Authorities had promised to grant a 50 percent wage increase
demanded by the workers at the mines, said Solidarity spokeswoman
Barbara Hrybacz. The miners make between $118 and $176 monthly.
   She said that when the union bargainers returned to negotiations
to tell management that workers' had accepted the offer,
authorities changed the offer to only a 30 percent increase.
   The strike committee said it could not sign an agreement on
behalf of the workers and talks broke off, she said.
   The walkout has virtually shut down Poland's production of
copper, a crucial export. It is the biggest labor dispute since the
Solidarity trade union and the government signed a historic
cooperative accord on April 5.
   Workers went on strike Friday at the Lubin, Polkowice, Rudna and
Sieroszowice mines near the city of Lubin, 200 miles southwest of
Warsaw. The mines produce almost all of Poland's copper.
   Earlier, the official PAP news agency said a tentative accord
was reached by negotiators during ``difficult'' all-night talks at
the Lubin mine.
   A strike spokesman reached by telephone said strikers would be
polled on the agreement and that an end to the strike was near.
   The New Solidarity union newspaper said 15,000 miners were
supporting the strike that has affected a total of 20,000 workers.
   The strike has been a test of the wide-ranging agreement between
the communist government and Solidarity. The pact, which followed
two months of intense talks, resulted in the legalization of the
outlawed union and opposition participation in national elections.
   In return, Solidarity is to cooperate with the government on
economic reforms aimed at improving Poland's ailing economy. More
militant union splinter groups favor a more adversarial approach.
   The miners' strike committee included 10 members of the
independent Solidarity trade union, seven from the Communist
Party-dominated OPZZ union and 13 unaffiliated miners, Solidarity
said.
   Solidarity, which was the East bloc's first independent trade
union during its brief initial legal existence, was crushed during
the martial law crackdown of December 1981.
   Poland exported $233 million in copper to the West in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
