<FIRST>u w PM-Panama-USMilitary     05-09 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-US Military,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Military Monitoring Panamanian Situation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said today the Defense Department
is monitoring closely the situation in Panama and had extended a
travel alert for the U.S. armed forces and their families following
U.S. charges of election fraud in last weekend's balloting..
   Chief Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said service personnel and
their dependents are being told to avoid travel around the country.
There are about 10,000 American troops based at military
installations in Panama.
   Howard also said the signal of the U.S. Southern Command's local
television station, operated for the benefit of American military
personnel and their dependents, was being jammed in Panama City. He
added the station and the Cable News Network had been yanked from a
local cable system in the capital.
   The spokesman declined to discuss military contingency planning,
saying no decisions involving troop movements or any other
operation had been made.
   ``We have a very uneasy situation in Panama,'' Howard observed.
``The turmoil obviously has created an unhealthy environment, not
only for Americans but Panamanians as well.''
   The United States charges that Panamanian strongman, Gen. Manual
Antonio Noriega, rigged the presidential elections Sunday in favor
of his candidate, Carlos Duque.
   American election observers met with President Bush today and
discussed options ranging from military intervention to increased
economic sanctions.
</TEXT>
