<FIRST>u i AM-Yeltsin Bjt   05-09 1051</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin, Bjt,1078</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Says He Still Talks to Gorbachev Despite Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev accused him of being too
ambitious and had him fired from the Politburo, but Boris N.
Yeltsin says he still talks to _ and believes in _ the Kremlin
chief.
   Their rocky relationship has made headlines largely because
Yeltsin, one of the staunchest backers of Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or openness, also became its victim. His attacks on
the slowness of reform and the officials he believes are
responsible have put a dent in his political career he is only now
recovering from.
   Looking fit and tan from tennis, jogging and a vacation in the
Caucasus Mountains, the 58-year-old Yeltsin was as outspoken as
ever in a recent interview.
   He appeared buoyed by his landslide victory in the March 26
parliamentary elections, a win he scored despite a Communist Party
reprimand, a new party investigation into his views, and recent
publication of criticism of him by party officials including
Gorbachev.
   Yeltsin made clear his complaints about the slowness of reform
were not directed at Gorbachev but at those surrounding Gorbachev.
   Asked about his relationship with Gorbachev, the silver-haired
maverick from Sverdlovsk paused.
   ``Our relations are not as close as they were when I worked the
first year or so as first secretary of the Moscow city party
committee, before that as a Central Committee secretary,'' he
finally said.
   ``When we worked as first secretaries, I of the Sverdlovsk and
he of the Stavropol regional party committee, we maintained normal
human contact by phone and so forth. I would not say we were
friends, but we had normal relations. Then he supported me and all,
but after that _ not without someone's help _ a bit of a chill
started to creep in.''
   Now, he said, ``we meet, say hello, discuss things normally. You
can't say our relations are broken off. No. Not at all.''
   Yeltsin, interviewed in his State Construction Committee office
where he works as first deputy chairman, said he speaks to
Gorbachev by phone and sees him at party meetings.
   Gorbachev has made mistakes, he said, declining to elaborate. In
other public statements, Yeltsin has said he believes the Kremlin
chief made a tactical error by not making increased supplies of
food, consumer goods and housing the top priority of
``perestroika,'' or restructuring.
   Yeltsin said Gorbachev is a true reformer who is unhappy that
perestroika has not substantially improved people's lives. The
reason, Yeltsin believes, is that conservatives _ led by Politburo
member Yegor K. Ligachev, whom he refers to as ``my opponent'' _
are holding back reform.
   Yeltsin said some of the 10 others on the Politburo are tainted
by the legacy of the 18-year rule of President Leonid I. Brezhnev,
an era now branded the ``period of stagnation.''
   ``They will never say it aloud, but they have been in the
highest echelons in the stagnation zone, safe from any criticism
for so long that I doubt if half of them could restructure
themselves and move perestroika energetically ahead,'' Yeltsin said.
   Gorbachev already has done some housecleaning on the ruling
body, dropping Andrei A. Gromyko, the man who ran foreign policy
during Brezhnev's rule, and Mikhail S. Solomentsev, the premier of
Russia during much of the Brezhnev period.
   Ligachev remains, and Yeltsin said a further shakeup is needed.
He declined to identify those he believes should be fired, saying
he'd get into even more trouble with the party. In March, the
policy-making Central Committee began investigating whether his
views conflict with the party line.
   Yeltsin said the committee's action in April to retire 110
top-ranking party officials, including many elderly holdovers from
the Brezhnev days, was only a partial solution. A full-scale
Central Committee purge can be made only at the next Communist
Party Congress in 1991, and Yeltsin suggested there be an
extraordinary session to weed out more oldtimers.
   Yeltsin said the Central Committee is more conservative than the
parliament to which he was just elected and it has made the party
the rear-guard instead of the vanguard of society. The new
parliament will include such reformers as human rights campaigner
Andrei D. Sakharov, economist Nikolai P. Shmelev and historian Roy
A. Medvedev.
   In a 1987 speech that led to his ouster as Moscow party boss and
removal from the Politburo, Yeltsin said consumers were concerned
perestroika had given them nothing, and he blasted Ligachev for
impeding reform. He has railed against the privileges granted the
Soviet elite and demanded more radical economic reform.
   Gorbachev himself has pushed gradually for more radical reform,
and in an April 25 speech acknowledged that shortages of housing,
food and basic consumer goods are growing despite perestroika.
   In a sense, Gorbachev is beginning to sound more and more like
Yeltsin.
   Asked whether he had simply aired his complaints too soon,
Yeltsin responded: ``I think he (Gorbachev) is late, moreover he is
of the very same opinion (as I am), but something prevents him from
showing himself more decisively to solve these problems.''
   He said later that he meant ``somebody'' was holding Gorbachev
back, mentioning Ligachev but declining to identify others.
   Last year, Gorbachev said he had brought Yeltsin into the
leadership in 1985 because he was ``an experienced, energetic
person with a critical approach.'' But, Gorbachev said, Yeltsin
resorted to ``shouting and command methods'' and ``went off into
high-flown talk, statements and administrative fiat.'' He also
accused Yeltsin of ``self-admiration.''
   Yeltsin said he was hurt by the criticism and wants the Central
Committee to annul a resolution it passed in 1987 branding his
speech ``politically erroneous.''
   ``It can't be called politically erroneous,'' he said somberly.
The resolution ``hangs on me even now .... Probably I will have to
wait for 28th Party Congress to raise this question.''
   Yeltsin also is angry about an investigation the Central
Committee launched during his election campaign into charges he
opposed party policies. One charge was that he supported breaking
the party's monopoly on political power. Yeltsin contends he has
simply called for discussion of a multiparty system.
   Asked about the inquiry, he snapped back that no commission
representative has interviewed him or asked for copies of his
speeches.
   ``Any criminal has a right to defense,'' he said.
</TEXT>
