<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Pesticide-Poultry     05-09 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticide-Poultry,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search for Heptachlor in Arkansas May Spread to Other States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department official said
Tuesday that all federally inspected poultry and hog slaughtering
plants in Arkansas have been put under ``intensified suveillance''
for traces of the cancer-causing pesticide heptachlor.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food
Safety and Inspection Service, said the agency may ``expand testing
into surrounding states'' over the next few weeks. The intensified
surveillance program for heptachlor in Arkansas began on Monday, he
said.
   The USDA agency has been monitoring Arkansas slaughter plants
since January for traces of heptachlor after finding contaminated
poultry at Townsends of Arkansas in Batesville, he said.
   ``We also began suveillance testing in other poultry and
red-meat slaughtering plants in Arkansas to determine if the
heptachlor problem extended beyond Townsends,'' Crawford said.
``Regrettably, we found additional problems.''
   One hog tested positive for heptachlor at unacceptable levels,
and two others showed traces of the chemical. Meanwhile, he said,
the Food and Drug Administration reported unacceptable heptachlor
levels in non-commerial egg samples.
   Contaminated feed is the suspected cause, although the FDA has
not been able to determine the specific source. At least four feed
mills have been under investigation.
   Crawford said his agency will inform the FDA ``whenever actual
or potential violations are detected through our testing.''
Meanwhile, the FDA will attempt to determine who bought the
contaminated feed. After that, Crawford said his inspectors will
test animals from those producers.
   ``The problems occurring with heptachlor are disturbing,'' he
said. ``Heptachlor has been shown to induce tumors in mice. In
1978, the Environmental Protection Agency banned heptachlor for all
agricultural uses except as a seed treatment, but it is apparent
from the problems we're finding now that residues from treated seed
persist in food animals.''
   Crawford said the problem will not be resolved until the
practice of using chemically treated seed as animal feed is
stopped. ``We are very encouraged by the EPA announcement that they
will ban the future use of heptachlor on treated seed,'' he added.
</TEXT>
