<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleAstronaut     05-09 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Astronaut,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Astronauts Return To Work To Discuss Shuttle Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The astronauts who rode the space
shuttle Atlantis on a four-day mission returned to work Tuesday to
begin reviewing their flight, highlighted by the deployment of a
planetary probe to Venus.
   Their mission ended Monday when the 97-ton shuttle dropped out
of orbit and glided to an afternoon landing at Edwards Air Force
Base, Calif. Atlantis remained at Edwards and initial inspections
showed little damage to the thermal tiles that protect it from the
heat of re-entry.
   While the astronauts returned to work, the Magellan probe they
deployed in orbit, where its own rocket engine was fired,
maintained a nearly perfect course for Venus. It will travel 806
million miles and loop 1{ times around the sun before reaching
Venus in August 1990.
   NASA officials praised the five astronauts' efforts in deploying
Magellan, the nation's first planetary probe in 11 years and the
first ever to ride a shuttle into space.
   ``Obviously this mission was an outstanding success,'' NASA
science chief Lennard Fisk told reporters at Edwards.
   The astronauts _ commander David Walker, pilot Ronald Grabe, and
mission specialists Mary Cleave, Mark Lee and Norman Thagard _
returned home to Houston late Monday and were welcomed at Ellington
Field by about 200 people.
   ``It's really nice to have the mission finished and we couldn't
have done it without you,'' Ms. Cleave told the crowd.
   She said the astronauts had a great time and that it was good to
know that a spacecraft was en route to Venus and ``we were all a
part of it.''
   The astronauts went to work Tuesday at the Johnson Space Center
reviewing photographs taken during their 1.68-million-mile journey.
On Wednesday, they will undergo physicals and begin discussing the
mission in depth with NASA officials.
   The only problem reported during the Atlantis flight, the fourth
since shuttle flights resumed Sept. 29, 1988, was Sunday's failure
of one of four redundant computers that control the shuttle's
systems.
   The crew was able to restart the computer but ground controllers
decided not to trust it for re-entry. The crew abandoned other
tasks and spent 4{ hours replacing the faulty computer with a
spare, the first time that had been done in orbit.
   The shuttle could land with just one computer operating,
according to NASA.
   Before the computer failure, the astronauts worked on an
experiment involving crystallizing a metal sample in a small
furnace and photographed lightning and pollution on Earth. The
weight of Magellan and its booster rocket _ 45,000 pounds _ had
limited the number of experiments the orbiter could carry.
   Once Magellan reaches Venus, it will use its high resolution
radar to map up to 90 percent of the planet's surface. The
$550-million mission should help scientists learn more about how
Venus evolved so differently from the Earth.
   Images obtained by Magellan are expected to show features as
small as a football field; that would be 10 times cleared than
pictures acquired by earlier radar spacecraft.
</TEXT>
