<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Osprey     05-09 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Osprey,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Decision to Scuttle Osprey Stands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department said Tuesday it wanted
to see the V-22 Osprey aircraft project shut down ``in an orderly
manner'' but had no intention of providing any more federal funds
to the two contractors involved.
   Reiterating Friday's announcement that no more money would be
forthcoming for the project, the department said the political
outcry after Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's decision to terminate
the program was ``not unexpected.''
   ``I think that if we were dealing with a real turkey here, you'd
have a different situation,'' Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief
spokesman, said Tuesday. ``But the secretary acknowledged the fact
that this is a good program.
   ``The decision (to terminate) was based on the secretary's
judgment that the only way you can cut the budget is to cut the
budget. That means that something has to come out.''
   On Friday, the two contractors developing the plane for the
Marine Corps announced they were temporarily suspending their
threat to begin layoffs in order to pursue further negotiations
with military officials.
   The contractors _ Bell Helicopter Textron Inc. and the Boeing
Helicopter Co. _ have said they don't want to pour any more of
their money into the V-22 this year if the decision to cancel the
program in the next fiscal year stands.
   The issue of corporate money arises because the Pentagon already
has paid the two companies all the money they're due in fiscal 1989
and the contractors are facing overruns that total about $25
million a month.
   Howard repeated Tuesday that Cheney intends to kill the program
in fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1, but fully expects the
contractors to complete work required under the fiscal 1989
contract.
   The Pentagon spokesman said there had been some additional
discussions with company executives, but declined to elaborate.
   Terry Arnold, a Bell spokesman, declined comment except to say
the contractors were still discussing the situation with Pentagon
officials.
   ``In the meantime, our status hasn't changed,'' Arnold said.
``It's a day-by-day decision on continuing work and we're still
working right now.''
   The V-22 Osprey, described by the Marine Corps as its most
important weapons program, is a revolutionary aircraft designed to
take off like a helicopter and fly like an airplane. To do this, it
utilizes special propellers at the tip of each wing that can swivel
upward and back.
   The Marine Corps wants to use the planes to improve its ability
to conduct surprise, long-range amphibious assaults. The first of
the planes just recently began flight tests in Texas.
   Cheney, in fashioning a fiscal 1990 military budget to honor a
White House-Congress budget compromise, two weeks ago announced $10
billion in cuts to the original spending plan of the Reagan
administration.
   In making those cuts, Cheney ordered the Osprey program canceled
outright, saying that the Pentagon simply couldn't afford the plane
and that the Marine Corps could do just as well by ordering
additional _ and cheaper _ helicopters.
   The Pentagon had planned to spend $25.9 billion on 663 Ospreys,
including $1.3 billion in 1990. The department has already invested
$2 billion in the program over a nine-year period.
   Of all of Cheney's budget-cutting decisions, the cancelation of
the Osprey has attracted the most intense opposition on Capitol
Hill. The plane is built in the district of House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, and enjoys widespread support among Republicans.
   Howard said that if Bell and Boeing failed to complete the work
required in the fiscal 1989 contract, they could face government
legal proceedings to recover $200 million to $300 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceShooting     05-09 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Shooting,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Detail Incident That Left Two Officers, Man Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An argument between a man and his wife
apparently led to a shooting spree in which two policemen were
killed before the suspect was killed by his son.
   Officers Bill Patterson and Wayne Henebry were killed by shotgun
blasts Monday night, apparently when they tried to serve a warrant
on ex-convict Howard Polk Sr. of Columbia, authorities said.
   Polk, 51, died later about three blocks away after his
19-year-old son used his car to pin the shotgun-wielding older man
against a pickup and then emptied a pistol at him, said District
Attorney Richard Douglass. No charges were filed against the son.
   Douglass said the rampage apparently resulted from an argument
Polk had with his wife.
   ``Evidently, they had an altercation and she made out charges,''
Douglas said. ``I assume it was some kind of assault. When he found
out about it, he sent word through some means that he would get her
and the law officers that had the warrant.''
   Douglass said Henebry and Patterson had responded to a domestic
disturbance call at the home of Polk's wife, but Polk had left by
the time the officers arrived and they headed back to the
courthouse.
   The officers' bodies were later found outside their patrol cars
near the courthouse, where they had encountered Polk, Douglass said.
   Apparently, both officers shot at Polk when he got out of his
truck firing his shotgun.
   ``I believe they knew he was dangerous,'' Douglass said. ``They
weren't trying to gun him down. They were just trying to do their
job.''
   He said Henebry was shot in the back of his head and Patterson
was shot in the face and head.
   While officers were rushing to the site of the shootings, they
received reports of a nearby disturbance. ``He (Polk) came back ...
and went to the house where his wife's relatives live,'' Douglass
said.
   He said witnesses reported that Polk stopped his truck and got
out, brandishing a shotgun. ``At the time, a member of the family
rammed him with a car and pinned him against the truck,'' he said.
   Douglass said the family member was Polk's son, Howard Polk Jr.
   ``There were a number of bullet wounds in his (elder Polk's)
body,'' Douglass said. ``The boy said he fired all the bullets in
his gun.'' He said one bullet in the 9-shot .22-caliber pistol did
not fire.
   Douglass said Howard Polk Jr. was questioned and released.
   ``It does not look like there will be charges,'' he said. ``He
made the statement to his son, `I'm going to go take care of these
papers and then I'm going to take care of you.'''
   Polk had a record in Marion County dating to the 1960s, said
Marion County Circuit Clerk Joe Herring.
   He served a prison sentence in the 1970s after pleading guilty
to a charge of manslaughter, reduced from murder, in a 1971 killing
in neighboring Lamar County, said Chief Lamar County Deputy Yancey
Saucier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
