<FIRST>r a PM-PhillyFares     05-09 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philly Fares,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fare Increase Blocked In Philly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today barred the city transit agency
from raising fares on subways, buses and trolleys until a higher
court decides whether the poor got a fair chance to be heard.
   Common Pleas Judge Samuel Lehrer rejected a plea from the
Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority that the agency
would suffer irreparable financial harm if the increase didn't take
effect Thursday.
   Under the new fare schedule, the cost of tokens _ which riders
buy in bulk _would go from 85 cents to $1 for the agency's 1
million weekday rides. The basic cash fare, $1.25 since 1986, would
not change.
   SEPTA had wanted to raise fares April 9, but community groups
argued that the agency, during public hearings, did not adequately
take into consideration the effect on the poor. Lehrer agreed at
the time and blocked the increases.
   Today, SEPTA argued it had the right put the increases into
effect pending a hearing June 7 in Commonwealth Court, but Lehrer
disagreed.
   SEPTA attorney David Bruton had argued that the system is losing
$60,000 to $80,000 a day without the increase.
