<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Media     05-09 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Media,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Czechoslovakia Striding Toward Press Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia is striving for press freedom and
does not deserve to be called an East bloc ``bad guy,'' a
Czechoslovak diplomat said Tuesday at a meeting to improve
information between East and West.
   Ambassador Dusan Spacil, who is based in West Germany, said
Western countries that criticize his country's record on press
rights are biased and speak from ``pre-programmed thinking.''
   Canada and the United States have accused Czechoslovakia and
other East bloc participants of violating or ignoring an
international agreement on press and other freedoms signed by 35
nations in Vienna in January.
   The aim of the London forum, which ends this week, is to monitor
compliance with the agreement.
   ``Whatever problems do exist, don't exist only in socialist
countries, but also in Western countries,'' said Spacil, who is
heading the Czech delegation.
   ``What we do consider unjust, especially in the Western
information media and also during this conference, were one-sided,
biased views,'' he said.
   ``There is pre-programmed thinking. This includes the fiction
that there are good and bad socialist states according to how they
apply `perestroika' and `glasnost,' and if they don't apply it
according to the pre-programmed thinking, then they are the bad
guys,'' he said referring to the Soviet policies of economic and
political reforms and openness applied in varying degrees in the
East bloc.
   However Spacil, a former ambassador to the United States, said
he believed most delegates were cooperative and understanding.
   Earlier at the forum, Canadian Ambassador William Bauer compared
the propaganda techniques and state-controlled media of Romania,
Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and East Germany to Nazi Germany.
   Chief U.S. delegate Leonard H. Marks singled out the same four
nations for criticism, saying they had yet to fulfill the Vienna
agreement.
   Spacil said ``glasnost'' has permeated his country's media.
Newspapers carry articles criticizing official speeches, they
reprint foreign articles without commentary and are more widely
available, he said.
   But he said his government could not immediately hurry into
place all the changes needed to comply with the accord, which he
said maintains that ``national laws have to be respected.''
   ``We are in this process, adjusting our national laws to the
requirements of Vienna,'' Spacil said.
   He cited as an example that Czechoslovakia is changing its rules
to enable foreign journalists to obtain visas immediately,
beginning in the next two months.
</TEXT>
