<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     05-09 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Distributes Money to Bhopal Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government paid the first monthly
benefit Tuesday to the heirs of more than 2,000 adults who died in
the 1984 Bhopal gas disaster, as ordered by the Supreme Court.
   Government funds are being used pending resolution of legal
challenges to a $470 million settlement by Union Carbide Corp. of
Danbury, Conn. An Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide operated the
Bhopal plant.
   Bank accounts opened in the names of the heirs were credited
with the first monthly payments of 750 rupees ($50) each.
   Members of the Bhopal Gas Affected Women's Organization held a
silent demonstration outside a building where officials presented
the heirs with bank documents.
   Protesters carried placards and banners accusing the government
of trying to take credit for the compensation program.
   Abdul Jabbar Khan, organizer of the group, said: ``We want to
tell the victims that it is because of the Supreme Court and not
the munificence of the government that they are getting the money.
There was no need to hold such a function. This only shows the
government wants to use the occasion for electoral purposes.''
   At least 3,400 people were killed and more than 20,000 injured
when toxic gas leaked from the Bhopal pesticide plant on Dec. 2,
1984.
   Union Carbide was ordered in February to pay $470 million, under
a settlement supervised by the Supreme Court during the hearing of
a $3 billion damage suit filed by the government.
   Payment was delayed after several petitions challenged the
government's right to represent the victims.
   Another bench of the court ordered monthly payment of interim
relief pending a decision on the legal petitions. The amount paid
is to be deducted from the final compensation award.
</TEXT>
