<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-High-DefinitionTV     05-09 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High-Definition TV,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Seeks U.S. Aid; Mosbacher Says Uncle Sam No `Uncle Sugar'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. electronics industry on Tuesday
released a plan proposing more than $1.3 billion in government aid
to help America catch up in the global race to develop
high-definition television technology.
   But Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said U.S. manufacturers
shouldn't depend on Uncle Sam to be their ``Uncle Sugar'' in
bankrolling the effort.
   High-definition television, which offers the promise of sharper,
brighter and wider pictures, is expected to be in full operation in
Japan by the mid-1990s. The U.S. telecommunications industry has
barely begun testing the technology.
   Pat Hill Hubbard, vice president of the American Electronics
Association, told a Senate committee that if the United States
fails to catch up, ``the effects on our economy may be drastic''
and would adversely affect a range of industries, including
semiconductors, software and automated manufacturing equipment.
   ``We must gain an industry to retain many industries,'' she said.
   The association released a proposal developed by the Boston
Consulting Group that calls for $1 billion in loans and loan
guarantees for U.S. companies that join together to manufacture and
market the television technology.
   The plan also proposes $300 million over three years to promote
high-definition TV research at the Pentagon and $50 million more
for related work at the Commerce Department. The proposal calls for
matching investments and initiatives from interested businesses.
   Mosbacher, testifying earlier, said the Bush administration had
not yet decided on its role in fostering the new technology, but
said he had ``serious doubts about throwing money at the problem.''
   ``I think, frankly, the problem is that they are hoping ...
Uncle Sugar will fund it and I don't think they should depend on
that,'' Mosbacher said. ``It's got to be that the private sector
will still take the lead.''
   Mosbacher reiterated his previous statements that the
administration hopes to promote America's industrial
competitiveness by extending research and development tax credits
and reducing the capital gains tax rate.
   He also said the administration is considering easing antitrust
restrictions to allow U.S. companies to work together to develop
new technologies.
   IBM Corp. Vice Chairman J.D. Kuehler, said the core question
related to development of high-definition television is ``whether
or not this country wants to get into the development and the
manufacturing of consumer electronics,'' now largely the territory
of Japanese companies.
   ``HDTV has become the symbol of or the last bastion of or the
best opportunity ... to put this country into the role of a
provider of consumer electronics,'' Kuehler said.
   The committee chairman, Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., said he
was ``embarrassed'' for Mosbacher because of his lack of specific
recommendations for advancing HDTV and U.S. industrial
competitiveness.
   Hollings praised the HDTV proposal released by the electronics
association and said the suggested amounts of government assistance
included in the plan were ``in the ballpark,'' given the head start
that the Japanese have in HDTV technology.
</TEXT>
