<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Crops-Weather     05-09 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crops-Weather,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crops in Plains Hurt by Lack of Rain; Too Much Rain in Corn Belt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lack of rainfall continued to hurt crops in
major areas of the Great Plains while too much rain slowed spring
planting in the eastern Corn Belt and the Southeast, a government
report said Tuesday.
   Winter wheat was in mostly fair-to-poor condition nationally
during the week of May 1-7, although the Great Plains crop was
rated below that. In the Pacific Northwest, Corn Belt and
Southeast, winter wheat was said to be in ``mostly good to fair''
shape.
   The Joint Agricultural Weather Facility said 89 percent of the
winter wheat crop in Kansas was in very poor or poor condition
``and continued to deteriorate due to lack of moisture'' during the
week.
   Harvesting of the 1989 winter wheat crop has begun in southern
Texas and will gradually move north. The Agriculture Department
will issue its first official estimate of this year's production on
Thursday.
   Meanwhile, the report by the facility, which is operated jointly
by USDA and the Commerce Department, said corn planting nationally
was about 43 percent completed, eight percentage points behind
normal for this time.
   ``Lack of moisture has slowed germination and emergency (of
corn) in Kansas,'' the report said. ``Rain continued to slow
planting in the eastern Corn Belt and the Southeast.''
   Corn planting was 42 percentage points behind in Ohio and 25
points behind in Indiana, the report said. Planting trailed the
usual pace by 34 percentage points in North Carolina.
   Only about 5 percent of the soybean crop had been planted, four
percentage points behind the normal pace, although planting was
under way in all major soybean states except Minnesota and North
Carolina.
</TEXT>
