<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     05-09 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Dedicates Mass to Torture Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic archbishop of
Asuncion has urged Paraguayans to plant flowering trees beside the
graves of torture victims from the deposed regime of Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner.
   On Monday night, Archbishop Ismael Rolon stood before a
coffin-shaped box covered with a maroon shroud at Mass dedicated to
torture victims. Beside him was a small tree decorated with
multicolored tags bearing the names of 68 people believed to have
been killed by the deposed regime.
   ``Next to every one of the tombs discovered we must plant a ...
tree, which on flowering every year will renew our hopes and
refresh our spirit,'' Rolon told about 700 worshipers at the
National Cathedral.
   ``We must never again remain quiet,'' he said. ``Silence
provoked by fear helped these crimes to take place and granted
immunity.''
   Stroessner was ousted three months ago in a coup by Gen. Andres
Rodriguez, who was elected president May 1 by an overwhelming
margin. Rodriguez pledged to respect human rights and punish those
responsible for past abuses.
   In past weeks, a skull and bone shards of three alleged victims
of the past regime were unearthed in a rural area.
   Excavations at another site believed to be a mass grave for
peasants was suspended after water seeped into the cavity and
prevented further digging.
   Ignacio Duarte, a former political prisoner, has said there are
at least six graves in the garden of a police barracks on the
outskirts of Asuncion. But he has been prevented by police from
entering the barracks to point out the site.
</TEXT>
