<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0606 05-09 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shells &amp; Rockets Hit Hospitals, Apartments, Public Utilities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UDPATE casualties to 11 killed, 50 wounded.
Picks up 4th pvs, ``Sheik Sabah ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells hit hospitals, apartments, post
offices and communications facilities Tuesday in one of the most
destructive artillery duels of the 14-year-old civil war, killing
11 people and wounding 50.
   The savage bombardment by Syrian gunners and Christian army
units blanketed the Moslem and Christian sectors of Beirut, nearby
hills and a stretch of Christian coast north of the city.
   By police count, 327 people have been killed and 1,234 wounded
since March 8, when fighting began between the 20,000 Christian
soldiers commanded by Gen. Michel Aoun and a Moslem alliance of
Syrian troops and Druse militiamen. Most of the casualties have
been civilians.
   Sheik Sabah Ahmed, foreign minister of Kuwait and head of an
Arab League mediation panel, said plans to send Arab military
observers to Beirut had been suspended until another cease-fire
could be arranged. One called by the league April 28 was broken by
the latest battle.
   Beirut residents took refuge in underground shelters for a
fourth day. Syrian troops in Moslem west Beirut and on nearby
slopes blsted the 310-square-mile Christian enclave north and east
of the city, using multibarreled rocket launchers that fire up to
40 projectiles a minute.
   Aoun's Christian units pummeled the Moslem sector of Beirut and
Druse-held villages in the central mountains with howitzer and
mortar fire.
   A police spokesman said the dead included two men killed by
shells that hit Barbir Hospital, one of four major medical centers
in west Beirut.
   At least 12 howitzer and mortar rounds hit Barbir overnight,
said the spokesman, who added that Mohammed Mosallem, an
administrator, was killed ``while supervising the patients'
evacuation to the underground shelter.''
   Bilal Daher, a 25-year-old journalist, was killed while trying
to help evacuate his elder brother, Ouday, who had fractured his
hip in an auto accident. Free-lance cameraman Mehdi Mehdi was
wounded in the leg by a sniper while trying to photograph damage at
the hospital.
   Reporters saw cleaners sweeping broken glass and debris out of
Barbir during a morning lull in the shelling.
   Several shells hit St. Louis hospital in the Christian port of
Jounieh, 12 miles north of Beirut, but the staff and patients had
been evacuated and no casualties were reported.
   Police said 31,000 shells and rockets had fallen on Beirut since
the latest battle began Saturday evening. U.N. sources and Lebanese
economic experts estimated the damage since March 8 at more than
$300 million.
   Police said shells and rockets struck many apartment buildings,
starting fires, post offices were hit and damage to communications
facilities knocked out local and overseas telephone service.
   To help fill the gap, the leftist Voice of the People radio
broadcast messages from people in Beirut to relatives elsewhere in
Lebanon.
   Radio reports said Arab League envoy Lakhdar Ibrahimi, who had
planned to visit Syria and Lebanon in an attempt to revive the
collapsed truce, was stranded in Rome by a strike of airport
workers.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League and has become the country's main
power broker during the long civil war.
   Salim Hoss, who leads the Moslem cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, and Parliament speaker Hussein Husseini met in Damascus
with Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam of Syria and Farouk Sharaa,
the foreign minister. Gen. Aoun heads the competing Christian
government.
   Ibrahimi is an Algerian and represents Chedli Klibi, the Arab
League secretary-general.
   In Kuwait, Sheik Sabah said: ``It has become difficult in light
of the recent developments to send the Arab observer force to
Lebanon to expose their lives to danger either by assassination or
killing as a result of the indiscriminate shelling.''
   Warring factions had agreed to the Arab League truce, but Syria
and its allies continued shelling the coastal strip, claiming three
Iraqi ships in the Mediterranean intended to deliver weapons to the
Christians.
   Aoun held fire until Saturday, then ordered his men to retaliate.
</TEXT>
