<DOCNO> AP890509-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     05-09 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kadar Leadership Criticized in Letter Announcing His Removal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party Central Committee
accused ousted leader Janos Kadar of making wrong decisions that
hampered the nation's political and economic progress, official
media reported Tuesday.
   The official MTI news agency on Tuesday released the message
sent to Kadar by the Central Committee, which stripped him of his
last official posts on Monday.
   The message said history would be the best judge of Kadar's 32
years as party leader.
   Kadar, 76, was removed as Hungarian leader last year and
replaced by Karoly Grosz, who has allowed more personal freedoms
and political reforms.
   ``Today we cannot undertake to assess your 50-year historic
career, which is inseparably linked with the advancement _ not free
of contradictions _ of the Hungarian nation,'' MTI quoted the
message to Kadar as saying.
   ``In the final anaysis, only posterity can complete a balance
sheet of an era which is linked to the name of Janos Kadar.''
   Informing Kadar that he was being removed from the powerful
Central Committee and the honorary post of party president, the
party leadership said ``the objective difficulties of the past 15
years and our economic and political woes have been aggravated by
erroneous decisions, which were taken on more than one occasion.''
   In a clear break with the former leader, the Central Committee
stated: ``We cannot underestimate our (achievements) but we cannot
keep silent about our errors, either.''
   Foreign Minister-designate Gyula Horn also criticized Kadar, who
became party leader as Soviet troops and tanks crushed an
anti-Soviet revolt in 1956.
   ``We must not gloss over the fact that grave errors were also
committed during that period, the impact of which are felt today,''
Horn said on state-run TV. ``The so-called years of stagnation are
also linked to Kadar's name.''
   Kadar has come under increasing criticism in official media for
his role in postwar purges and allegedly in the arrest and
execution in 1958 of revolutionary premier Imre Nagy and several of
his associates.
   Kadar has also been indirectly blamed for the downward slide in
recent years of the national economy, once a model of prosperity in
the socialist world.
   Hungary is saddled with a $17 billion foreign debt, inflation
expected to top 16 percent this year and sharply declining living
standards.
   A party official who addressed a news conference said Kadar was
sent into retirement for health reasons.
   Party secretary Gyoergy Fejti told reporters, ``The Central
Committee noted with sadness that the health of chairman Kadar does
not allow him to fulfill his functions and, therefore, decided to
release him.''
   Fejti said the Central Committee letter expressed ``respect and
esteem'' for Kadar's contributions.
   ``We are sure that both history and public opinion will see this
period as a progressive one despite the shortcomings,'' said Fejti.
   He would not divulge details about Kadar's health.
   Budapest's Kossuth radio reported in a noon broadcast that Kadar
spoke incoherently during the last Central Committee meeting two
weeks ago.
   Fejti also discussed the ruling party's efforts to set up a
national round table to negotiate with newly formed opposition
groups on the transition to a multiparty system and methods of
reversing the economic crisis.
</TEXT>
