<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ImpostorAstronaut     05-09 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Impostor Astronaut,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Astronaut Impostor Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who police said posed as an astronaut,
fooling the mayor of Dublin, Ireland, and even his wife, pleaded
guilty to using a credit card fraudulently to pay for a $6,000
charter flight.
   Robert Hunt, 27, was released from jail and put on a year's
probation after his plea Monday. He had already served three months
and 12 days in jail following his arrest.
   Boston Municipal Court Judge Herbert Hershfang ordered Hunt to
undergo psychiatric treatment and to repay Eastern Air Charter of
Norwood for the airplane rental.
   Hunt was accused of posing in a variety of roles over several
years, including Marine captain, astronaut and jet pilot. He
scorched some kitchen tiles and told his wife, whom he married last
year, that they were from the space shuttle Challenger, police said.
   He also visited the lord mayor of Dublin while on a trip to
Ireland, posing as an astronaut, and, closer to home, gave a
well-received speech about his space experiences to an aviation
club in Bedford.
   But after he was arrested Jan. 28, police said Hunt had swindled
his unsuspecting new wife of up to $50,000 on her company-issued
credit card, including the cost of the charter flight to Montreal.
He told her that flight was free because of his astronaut
experience.
   Recalling the day he was unmasked, his wife, Ann Sweeney, said:
``I was shocked. It was almost like watching someone die. He just
dissolved, disappeared.''
   He was charged with using an American Express credit card issued
by Polaroid Corp. to Ms. Sweeney to rent a jet and flight crew to
fly him and her to Montreal. American Express refused to pay for
the flight because Hunt, not his wife, had signed to rent the plane.
</TEXT>
