<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Bomb     05-09 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Bomb,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Responsibility for Bomb That Injures Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-communist rebels claimed
responsibility Tuesday for a bomb in the Angolan capital of Luanda
that destroyed the offices of the Texaco oil company and two other
foreign firms, injuring two people.
   The 6.6-pound bomb exploded Monday night and destroyed the
Texaco office, as well as those of Japanese multinational Sumitomo
Corp. and France's Petromar.
   ``Angola is in a state of war,'' said Alcides Sakala, a
spokesman for the rebels known as UNITA, or the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola. ``If these companies weren't
operating out of Angola, and supporting the Luanda regime, they
wouldn't be targets.''
   A child in an apartment above the offices was hurt and a
Sumitomo director suffered minor head injuries in the blast, the
Portuguese news agency Lusa reported.
   Sakala said the attack was a response to provocation by forces
of Luanda's communist government.
   The blast, the fourth in Luanda since last year, wrecked cars
parked on the oceanside boulevard and shattered windows at the
nearby Hotel Presidente and the Congolese Embassy, Lusa said.
   The rebels have been fighting the government since shortly after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
