<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     05-09 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Demands U.S. Removes Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea called Tuesday for the
United States to remove nuclear weapons from the Korean peninsula,
saying they pose a threat of nuclear war.
   The United States dismissed the call as ``repetitious
propaganda.''
   Maj. Gen. Choe Ui Ung, a North Korean spokesman, urged the
creation of a nuclear-free zone at a meeting of the Military
Armistice Commission overseeing the cease-fire that ended the
bitter 1950-53 Korean War.
   ``In light of the international trend to remove the danger of
nuclear war, we have presented the issue of removing the nuclear
weapons at this meeting,'' he said.
   U.S. Navy Rear Adm. Larry G. Vogt welcomed North Korea's call
for the meeting, but said the nuclear charges were ``repetitious
propaganda'' to weaken South Korea and its allies. He was speaking
for the 16 nations that aided Seoul in the Korean War.
   Vogt did not respond directly to Choe's charges that the United
States is storing nuclear weapons in South Korea as part of war
preparations.
   Instead, the American suggested the commission discuss steps to
ease tension, such as the restoration of joint observer teams to
investigate alleged armistice violations, and the return of remains
of soldiers killed in the war.
   The creation of a nuclear-free zone was a ``political'' issue
out of the purview of the command, Vogt said.
   The United States declines to confirm or deny if it has nuclear
weapons in South Korea. Past reports indicate U.S. forces are
equipped with some tactical nuclear weapons.
   Choe said U.S. nuclear arms in South Korea include artillery
shells, warheads for missiles, mines, bombs and said two nuclear
airfields are under construction.
   ``It is not only a hypocrisy, but also a deception of the public
opinion that you talk about the nuclear disarmament while keeping
nuclear weapons in South Korea, the most dangerous hotbed of
nuclear war in the world,'' he said.
   South Korean officials said the meeting marked the first time in
recent memory that the Pyongyang government offered an agenda in
advance. They said it also was the first time North Korea focused
on one topic.
   North Korea, which invaded South Korea in 1950, repeatedly uses
the commission to call for the removal of U.S. forces from the
peninsula. South Korea says the 42,000 U.S. troops are vital to
prevent another communist attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
