<DOCNO> AP890509-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NursingShortage     05-09 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Shortage,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Greater Demand Triggered Nurse Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greater demand, not job burnout, is the major
cause of the nationwide nursing shortage, according to a two-year
study released Tuesday.
   ``Despite widespread beliefs to the contrary, it is simply not
true that large numbers of nurses are being driven out of nursing
by their working conditions, by a lack of respect from doctors, or
indeed by anything else,'' said the Commonwealth Fund, a foundation
whose goal is improving health care.
   The study said only 6 percent of the people holding nursing
licenses are working outside the profession.
   Instead, ``a key explanation for the shortage is the steady
growth in demand for nurses by hospitals, which employ about
two-thirds of all working nurses.''
   Demand has jumped because doctors now ``aggressively treat or
operate upon very ill patients whom a few years ago they would not
have subjected to such extensive intervention,'' it said.
   Forty percent of all hospital nurses work in intensive care
units, which need four to six times more nurses per bed than other
medical and surgical units.
   The number of working nurses jumped from 750,000 in 1970 to 1.62
million in 1988. Still, an average of 15.4 percent of all budgeted
nursing positions in hospitals are now vacant.
   ``Medicine today is not what medicine was 20 years ago _ that's
the crucial point,'' said Eli Ginzberg, a Columbia University
economics professor and health policy specialist who participated
in the study.
   While hospitals historically have shown a ``reluctance to
innovate,'' these surveyors ``sensed people believing that business
as usual wasn't going to do it any more,'' said Marc Roberts, a
professor at the Harvard School of Public Health.
   The survey questioned 15,000 nurses and 400 hospitals in New
York, Boston, Pittsburgh, Chicago, Houston and Los Angeles.
Entry-level nurse salaries ranged from $20,000 to $28,000 and
peaked between $30,000 and $40,000.
   Today's hospital nurses primarily are married women in their 30s
and 40s, with school-aged children.
   Asked what were very important among their concerns, 51 percent
of full-time nurses listed scheduling, 48 percent salary and 40
percent benefits.
   Nursing school enrollments have declined, partly due to a
shrinking work-age force and partly due to increased career options
for women. While some men are being recruited, 97 percent of all
nurses still are women.
   The study said state governments should help nursing schools
recruit recent college graduates, displaced workers, low-income
people and members of minority groups. Scholarships, loans and
work-study programs also were recommended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
