<FIRST>r w AM-WorldEnvironment     05-09 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Environment,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>People Around the World Fear Pollution, Say It's Getting Worse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. survey says people around the world, no
matter their economic standing or education, are acutely worried
about environmental problems and believe pollution will get worse
before it gets better.
   The survey was conducted by Louis Harris and Associates for the
United Nations Environment Program, the organization's lead agency
for dealing with environmental matters. It was released Tuesday in
Washington and in Nairobi, Kenya where the agency has its
headquarters.
   At a news conference, Louis Harris said the findings are
``nothing less than an alarm about the state of the environment''
and indicate environmental concerns will play an increasingly
important political role in the next decade.
   ``I think in the next five years governments will topple because
of the environmental issues,'' he said.
   According to the polls, more than 75 percent of the people in
each of the countries surveyed believed that stronger government
action was needed to protect against pollution. Governments
generally were given poor to mediocre grades on dealing with
environmental matters.
   In all but one of the countries _ Saudi Arabia _ most people
rated their environment as only fair or poor and in all of the
countries surveyed a majority said they would be willing to pay
higher taxes if they knew the money would be spent on environmental
protection.
   The survey in 14 countries was conducted last year and a shorter
version was conducted in the United States in April. Between 400
and 1,253 people were interviewed in each of the nations on
subjects ranging from their view of the environment to whether they
thought the government was doing enough to protect it.
   The foreign countries were Argentina, China, Hungary, India,
Jamaica, Japan, Kenya, Mexico, Nigeria, Norway, Saudi Arabia,
Senegal, West Germany, and Zimbabwe.
   Large majorities in each of the countries said they perceive a
direct link between environmental quality and public health.
   The surveys revealed broad concern about the quality of drinking
water, chemical pollution of the air as well as lakes and rivers,
loss of agricultural lands and forests, and disposal of toxic
wastes.
   ``Only tiny minorities in any nation surveyed believed their
environmental laws were too strict,'' said the United Nations
agency.
   In the United States, 64 percent of those interviewed gave the
environment a fair or poor rating. That was mild, however, compared
to the responses to a similar question posed in seven other
countries. More than 80 percent of the respondents in Hungary,
Senegal, Mexico, China, West Germany, India and Japan gave a
similar assessment.
   Water and air pollution most often were cited as posing the most
concern.
   People in countries that are still moving toward
industrialization often expressed the greatest concern about air
pollution, while only 23 percent of the Japanese surveyed held such
concerns despite that nation's enormous industrial concentration,
the survey said.
   In all of the countries there was fear that environmental
problems will likely become worse.
   Even in Saudi Arabia, the only country where today's environment
received a positive mark, 61 percent of those surveyed said the
environment will get worse. Nine out of 10 people in Argentina said
the environment will deteriorate, the most pessimistic view in all
of the nations in the survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0151 </DOCNO>
