<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     05-09 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Seeks Extra Anti-Drug Financing in Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House put itself on record on Tuesday as
favoring added muscle for the nation's anti-drug efforts and
opposing an increase in the tax on gasoline to help cut the federal
deficit.
   Lawmakers voted 397-10 to call on House-Senate negotiators to
alter the proposed fiscal 1990 budget by transfering $100 million
from the account that pays for congressional mailings to law
enforcement initiatives.
   Bargaining between the two chambers over a $1.2 trillion
spending plan for next year is set to begin Wednesday.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, ranking Republican on the House
Budget Committee, proposed the non-binding measure, saying that
fears that more money needed to be diverted to anti-drug programs
``seemed to plague'' many lawmakers.
   The section of the budget containing money for law enforcement,
and the portion covering general government expenses such as
congressional mailings, each contain about $10 billion for next
year.
   The House-passed measure also included language urging the
chamber's negotiators to oppose a boost in the 9.1-cent-per-gallon
federal tax on gasoline.
   On a voice vote, the Senate put itself on record last week as
being against such an increase. Administration officials have
reportedly considered consenting to such an increase for fiscal
1991, which begins Oct. 1, 1990, in exchange for a cut in the
capital gains tax.
   House and Senate budget writers are hoping their efforts to
agree to a compromise budget will last only a few days. The two
spending plans differ little, mainly because of a pact between
congressional leaders and the Bush administration that set overall
spending and taxing figures and laid out $28 billion in claimed
deficit reduction.
   On another front, leaders of the House Appropriations Committee
are still trying to rework the $4.7 billion domestic spending bill
for this year that the House defeated two weeks ago.
   Efforts to pare the bill down in size have run into objections
from Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, chairman of the Appropriations
justice subcommittee. He has continued to insist that much of the
$750 million for anti-drug initiatives in the original measure
should remain intact.
   Republicans and some Democrats have said the measure is too
expensive. The portion of the bill that members say is most
urgently needed is $340 million for veterans' health programs, an
account that could run out of money by Memorial Day.
</TEXT>
