<FIRST>r a AM-SpillResponse     05-09 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill Response,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three States, British Columbia React to Alaska's Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lesson of the runaway Exxon Valdez oil spill
is that getting people and equipment to the scene quickly is
crucial, an Alaska environmental official told colleagues from the
Pacific Northwest on Tuesday.
   ``One thing we learned, if the right equipment isn't brought to
bear quickly to contain the pill, you're going to be chasing it
forever,'' said Jeff Mach, a cleanup coordinator with Alaska's
Environmental Conservation Department.
   Mach addressed the first meeting of the Oil Spill Task Force
since the Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24 in Alaska's Prince
William Sound, spilling 10.1 million gallons of crude and fouling
more than 600 miles of wildlife-rich coast.
   Washington and British Columbia created the task force after a
barge spilled 270,000 gallons of fuel oil in the Pacific in
December, fouling the coast. Oregon and Alaska were invited to join
after the Exxon accident.
   Members of the group Tuesday set about the task of working more
closely to prevent spills and clean them up more effectively. They
outlined four areas:
   _Taking stock of what cleanup equipment is available and
developing a plan for dispatching it to the site of a spill.
   _Sharing information on procedures, laws and mechanisms to
recover costs from polluters.
   _Sharing technology.
   _Improving spill prevention, the adequacy of Coast Guard radar
coverage of shipping lanes, and guidelines for crew training.
   ``This is a case of forgetting about jurisdiction and dealing
with who's got what kind of capabilities. British Columbia's
resources are at risk and we'd like to have a look-see at how well
prepared everybody is,'' said Rick Wilson of the province's
Ministry of Environment.
   Christine Gregoire, head of Washington's Department of Ecology,
said the time was right for such an effort.
   ``The congressional delegation is interested, the Legislature is
interested and has oil-spill bills to deal with _ there's even a
citizens initiative in the works,'' she said.
   Gregoire said a variety of changes are needed to enhance the
safety of shipping products like oil. Foremost was increasing the
liability of shippers, she said.
   One of the immediate concerns of the task force is Exxon's plan
to move the crippled tanker to Portland, Ore., for repairs
   Richard Dalon, deputy minister of British Columbia's Ministry of
Environment, said a consultant for the province concluded the
tanker was structurally sound to make the trip if seas are
relatively calm. However, the consultant, Olaf Hatlen, reported
holes as large as 20 feet across in the bottom of the hull and a
crack that extends nearly halfway across the hull.
</TEXT>
