<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Housing     05-09 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Nation Facing Loss of Housing Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Housing Conference said Tuesday
that the nation faces the loss of hundreds of thousands of
federally assisted housing units and urged a $10 billion-a-year
program to preserve and produce housing for low- and
moderate-income families.
   The conference, a non-profit organization of civic leaders and
leaders of the housing industry, said the inventory of federally
assisted housing units is declining because of several factors and
that no federal program is in place to replace lost housing.
   John Simon, president of the group, said at a news conference
that the nation faces the ``imminent and long-term loss of between
200,000 and 1.2 million units'' of subsidized housing.
   In calling for new federal spending, he said Congress and the
administration have shown a willingness to spend massive amounts to
bail out the savings and loan industry and provide agricultural
subsidies, and should do the same for affordable housing.
   ``We think money can also be found and must be found to house
our people,'' he said.
   If the loss in housing occurs, Simon said there would be
``massive displacement of poor and low-income tenants, and the
working poor, and a dramatic increase in the number of homeless
families.''
   Simon and other conference leaders said the problem is being
created by the termination or expiration of federal subsidy
contracts for housing projects, the loss of assisted housing and
public housing due to deterioration and inadequate maintenance, and
the prepayment of mortgages on privately owned subsidized housing.
   The end of mortgages and subsidy contracts permit private owners
of federally assisted housing to convert the housing to market-rate
rental units or condominiums, he said.
   He said housing officials have stated such a wide estimate of
potential housing losses because they do not know how private
owners and developers will react when their subsidy contracts
expire.
   Simon said the organization was asking for $10 billion yearly
increases for several years in spending on housing programs.
   He said the money should be used to provide new incentives,
including tax benefits and subsidies, to induce owners to keep
projects in the assisted housing inventory. He said money should
also be spent to create new subsidized housing and to create a
trust fund to aid first-time home buyers.
   The National Housing Conference, which concluded a two-day
meeting, was created in 1931 and is the oldest national housing
organization.
</TEXT>
