<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-LaborParty     05-09 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Labor Party,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kinnock Wins Vote to Water Down Anti-Nuclear Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Party, battling to broaden its appeal
after a decade in opposition, on Tuesday dumped its vote-losing
doctrine of unilateral nuclear disarmament.
   Urged on by party leader Neil Kinnock, Labor's National
Executive voted 17-8 for a new policy of multilateralism, under
which a Labor-led government would scrap Britain's independent
nuclear arsenal only in a negotiated arms control deal.
   A 16-9 vote defeated a motion by the hard-line left to set a
deadline for scrapping Britain's submarine-based nuclear missiles
unilaterally.
   The National Executive adopted an unopposed amendment whereby a
Labor government would negotiate nuclear disarmament with the
Soviet Union if U.S.-Soviet negotiations stalled.
   But the executive also adopted unopposed a resolution saying
nuclear weapons are ``not a deterrent and of no practical use.''
The governing Conservative Party contended this is tantamount to
saying a Labor government would never use nuclear arms.
   Labor left-wingers accused their party of betraying its
principles and vowed to fight to reverse the new policy at the
party's annual convention in October, which must approve the policy
changes.
   The shift is part of a wide-ranging policy review designed to
draw Labor back to the political center and kill the public
perception of a party in thrall to doctrinaire left-wingers.
   Arguing passionately against unilateralism, Kinnock told his
colleagues he had tried out the doctrine on U.S., French and even
Soviet leaders and won no understanding for it.
   ``Unilateralism is not even comprehended by those who share our
objectives in other countries,'' he said.
   ``They were totally uncomprehending that we should want to get
rid of a nuclear system without getting elimination of nuclear
weapons on other sides too _ without getting anything for it in
return,'' he said.
   The 47-year-old Welshman, once an ardent unilateralist,
reiterated a theme that has resonated throughout the two-day
National Executive meeting _ that only by breaking with the past
can Labor win power.
   ``Out of power, we do not have the opportunities of unilateral
or any other sort of disarmament,'' he said. ``We only have the
chance to talk about it. In power we can act and make dramatic
progress.''
   Unilateralism was adopted by Labor in 1981 and has been cited as
a key reason for Labor's two subsequent defeats by the
Conservatives under Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who believes
nuclear deterrence alone can keep the world at peace.
   Answering questions in Parliament, Mrs. Thatcher said the new
policy was ``unilateralism in a different wrapping.''
   Her defense secretary, George Younger, said, ``To arm yourself
with a deterrent, which you then say you will not use, would be
about as effective as a feather duster.''
   Labor's foreign affairs chief, Gerald Kaufman, insisted the new
policy was in line with most of Britain's NATO partners.
   On Monday, the National Executive voted 23-4 to jettison
commitments to renationalize all state-owned industries sold to
private investors by the Thatcher government.
   On Tuesday it dealt the hard left more defeats. It threw out a
proposal to abolish the unelected House of Lords, voting instead to
establish an elected upper chamber. Calls to quit NATO and the
European Economic Community, and withdraw British troops from
Northern Ireland, all were heavily defeated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
