<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Health     05-09 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Health,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>His First Physical as President Will Be Wednesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0680 to fix day in summary line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will undergo a routine physical
examination at nearby Bethesda Naval Hospital on Wednesday, the
White House announced Tuesday.
   The examination, Bush's first as president, will include a chest
x-ray, hearing tests, an eye examination, an electrocardiagram,
allegery tests, a urinalysis and a dermatology examination, said a
White House statement.
   The statement, by presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater,
said that the examination would be under the direction of Bush's
personal physician, Dr. Burton Lee.
   Lee will conduct a ``complete history and personal
examination,'' the statement said. It said that Lee had taken
several blood samples earlier this week and that they ``will be
analyzed as part of the examination.''
   Bush, 64, was expected to fly by helicopter from the White House
to the hospital in Bethesda, Md., for the morning examination,
which is expected to take about four hours.
   ``Never felt better in my life,'' Bush said Tuesday when asked
about his health in an interview in the Oval Office with a group of
reporters.
   Although he suffered from ulcers 20 years ago, Bush has said he
is in excellent physical shape.
   He suffers from several physical ailments, however, including a
stronconductivity.
   The study said efforts by other countries to create alliances of
business, government and academia ``have the potential to weaken
the United States economically and militarily ... Observers have
suggested that the Sematech model _ federally sponsored
pre-competitive industry cooperation _ may be one answer to this
problem.''
   Sematech's aim is to achieve global leadership in semiconductor
manufacturing technology by 1993.
   The consortium was created because of fears a decline in the
U.S. semiconductor industry may undermine the competitive and
technological leadership of U.S. computer and communications
equipment makers. Also, there is the immediate issue of a growing
U.S. dependence on foreign sources for state-of-the-art weapons
components, the report said.
   It cautioned, however, that even if Sematech ``were a complete
success in its own terms, major issues now affecting the
competitiveness of U.S. chipmakers would remain _ limited marketing
opportunities and a range of tax, antitrust and trade policy
issues.''
   The study also said the United States would still trail the
Japanese and Europeans in developing technologies necessary for
leadership in semiconductors in the late 1990s, particularly in the
area of X-ray lithography.
   ``If the public investment in Sematech is not followed by an
increase in the competitive strength of U.S. chipmakers and their
suppliers, Sematech as a public policy will not have been
successful,'' the study said.
   Even as Sematech was gaining momentum in 1988, U.S. chipmakers
continued to lose ground commercially. U.S. semiconductor
manufacturers say their share of world market sales fall to 37
percent, 3 percentage points below 1987 levels, the study said.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said Tuesday he never doubted Sematech would succeed.
   ``But keeping up with the technology and successfully competing
for worldwide chip sales are two different things,'' said the Texas
Democrat. ``It's not just the technology.''
   The study's author, Jeffrey L. Mayer, deputy director of the
office of Economic Policy at Commerce, said Sematech, now in its
second year, has ``done a very good job of getting to the starting
line.
   ``They are now in a position to begin achieving their explicit
R&amp;D objectives. It remains to be seen how well they do that, and
No. 2, what the long-range impact of that will be,'' Mayer said.
   The study, a report by the Advisory Council on Federal
Participation in Sematech, recommends the Pentagon spend $100
million on Sematech in fiscal 1990, which would be matched by the
member corporations. Withdrawal of federal support now ``would
seriously limit Sematech's operations and prospects for success,''
it said.
</TEXT>
