<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Astronauts     05-09 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Astronauts,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Telephones Shuttle Astronauts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday telephoned the
astronauts of the space shuttle Atlantis to wish them well and
invite them to the White House.
   Bush chatted for three minutes with Capt. David M. Walker and
his four crew members, asking them about the accomplishments of
their mission and promising to do the best he could in the federal
budget for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   In what has come to be known as Bushspeak, the president queried
the astronauts about their deployment of a planetary probe for
Venus, asking: ``Look, how was the actual deployment thing. That
went smoothly as I recall.''
   He told the crew to visit him at the White House when they
return from their mission and see his dog Millie's new puppies.
   ``Unless you hurry up, the puppies are gone,'' he said. The
Bushes are giving the puppies away to family members.
   Atlantis' mission ended Monday when the 97-ton shuttle landed at
Edwards Air Force Base, Calif. after deploying Magellan, the
nation's first planetary probe in 11 years and the first ever to
ride a shuttle into space.
   ``I want you to come here, and it _ we're very proud of the job
you all did,'' Bush said.
   He added that, ``My only worries _ and they are worries that
affect absolutely everything that I want to do _ is budgetary
constraints. But we've got some, I think, reasonably good figures
in here now for NASA ... so we'll try to do our part from this
end.''
</TEXT>
