<FIRST>r a AM-Earthquakes     05-09 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earthquakes,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Evidence Points to Severe Earthquakes in Last 500 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Studies of hearths and discarded seashells
at old Indian sites suggest huge earthquakes struck the Northwest
in the last 300 to 400 years, far more recently than previously
believed, geologists said Tuesday.
   Rick Minor and Wendy Grant, geologists working along the Oregon
coast, presented papers to a Geological Society of America
convention correlating sudden, dramatic changes in land levels to
disruptions in Indian communities.
   The evidence suggests the last major quake was 300 to 400 years
ago, said Minor, who is with a consulting company in Eugene, Ore.,
and Grant, a U.S. Geological Survey scientist affiliated with the
University of Washington.
   ``A lot of people think these happened very long ago,'' said Ms.
Grant. ``But people were living here and were affected by these
erthquakes.''
   Previous evidence suggested the last major quake was 3,000 or
more years ago. The seismic events are believed to be caused by one
of the Earth's plates diving under another at fault line beneath
the Pacific Ocean.
   Chuck Steele of the Federal Emergency Management Administration
office in Bothell said the discovery of a quake so recent could
affect a Geological Survey study of the likelihood of an quake in
the region and how to deal with it.
   ``The sense of urgency is there,'' he said.
   The new information is significant because Oregon has been
regarded as one of the most seismically ``benign'' states in the
country, said Brian Atwater of the Geological Survey. Atwater
studied land levels in Washington and two years ago theorized that
the last major quake was 3,000 years ago.
   Grant said the research is the first to study the possible
effects of severe land movement on human populations.
   She said carbon dating of hearth sites and layers of shellfish
eaten by people living near the ocean show periods where habitation
abruptly ended.
   These periods can be correlated to evidence of dramatic drops in
land levels followed by a tsunami, a giant wave associated with
large earthquakes, Grant said.
   Scientists cautioned that carbon dating is imprecise and that
the evidence, while intriguing, is circumstantial.
   ``Clearly, much more work needs to be done on why people would
be forced to move, or change their subsistence patterns,''
cautioned Minor.
   ``The only explanation is that it was a large earthquake,'' said
Atwater. ``But to really nail it down, more research is needed.''
   He noted Indian folklore contains no such reference to what
would have been a significant event. But Minor speculated that
diseases introduced by European and American settlers may have
decimated the tribes, wiping out ancient oral traditions by the
time ethnographers began studying the tribes in the early 1900s.
   As many as 2,000 geologists from throughout the West are
expected to attend the convention, which runs through Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
