<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HospitalizedChildren Bjt   05-09 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospitalized Children, Bjt,0522</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Hospitalized Children Less Depressed Than Parents, Study Suggests
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospitalized child is less likely to get
depressed than his parents, but their reactions can affect his
level of distress, says a study released Tuesday.
   Researchers also were surprised to find children showed less
distress if they had more exposure to sometimes discomforting
medical procedures, said P. Alex Mabe, of the Medical College of
Georgia.
   Children may be able to become rapidly accustomed to such
experiences, Mabe said at a news conference at the annual meeting
of the American Psychiatric Association.
   Doctors have assumed for years that hospitalization caused
depression in children, but recent studies have questioned that,
Mabe said.
   His work, done with colleagues at his school, focused on 75
children, ages 6 to 15, who were admitted for treatment of a
variety of disorders. The children were assessed two to 10 days
after admission.
   Researchers found that seven of the children reported symptoms
that implied significant distress. But the measurements suggested
the hospitalized children experienced no greater distress than
children in the general population.
   In contrast, 24 percent of the parents reported moderate to
severe levels of depression.
   The reason for the difference was not clear, Mabe said. Parents
may be torn by competing responsibilities to the child and their
family at home. Or parents may be interpreting their feelings as an
emotional reaction, while the child simply considers his reactions
part of being physically sick, he said.
   Children who had depressive symptoms were more likely to have
mothers who were experiencing emotional distress, Mabe said.
   Perhaps the children use parents as an indicator to see how
depressing they should consider the hospitalization, he suggested.
Alternatively, a depressed parent may be less available to provide
support.
   In any case, the apparent link means helping the parents out of
depression may benefit both them and the child, he said.
   Mabe cautioned that the study results may be affected by the
fact that the work was done at a specialized hospital rather than a
primary-care institution, and that the children studied had
generally been hospitalized several times.
   Asked how parents can minimize the trauma of hospitalization for
a child, Mabe recommended taking an active role in the child's care.
   In another presentation at the news conference, Elizabeth Weller
of Ohio State University said many physicians do not know how to
diagnose depression in children and are giving anti-depressive
drugs when they may not be needed.
   A suspected case of child depression should be referred to an
expert for diagnosis, she said.
   Barbara Geller, of the University of South Carolina, said
anti-depressants have not yet been proven generally effective in
children.
   Some depressed children will probably turn out to be helped by
the drugs, she said, ``but at this point we can't select them out
as well as we would like to.''
   But a child who has not responded to psychological treatment may
still be a candidate for trying an anti-depressant, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
