<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignInvestment     05-09 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Investment,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say Foreign Investment in U.S. Cost American Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instead of being a boon to U.S. employment,
the surge of foreign investment in the United States during the
mid-1980s cost America more jobs than it created, two researchers
said Tuesday.
   The tripling of foreign investment during the 1980s came largely
from takeovers of existing companies rather than construction of
new plants and offices, said Norman Glickman, director of the
Center for Urban Policy Research and State of New Jersey Professor
of Planning at Rutgers University.
   ``It's primarily a shift in ownership from an American owner to
a foreign owner,'' Glickman said. ``This does not necessarily
create jobs and often it can in fact destroy jobs.''
   In a new book, ``The New Competitors,'' Glickman and Douglas
Woodward, assistant professor of economics at the University of
South Carolina, said they found that foreign investment rose to
$262 billion in 1987, triple the amount of direct investment at the
start of the decade.
   They discussed their findings at a news conference sponsored by
the Economic Policy Institute, a labor-backed think tank based in
Washington.
   The authors found that while foreign firms or their affiliates
employ about 3 million workers, most of those employees represent
``the transfer of old jobs from an American to a foreign boss.''
   From 1982 to 1986, foreign investors cut 56,000 more jobs
through layoffs than they created through new plants and expansion,
the researchers said.
   Even excluding the 1982-83 recession years, only about 15,000 to
20,000 jobs a year were created by foreign investment, ``a very
small number in a 100 million-job economy,'' Glickman said.
   Glickman said the Japanese have been the most likely to invest
in new plants and create jobs in the United States, but have been
``the greatest recipients of xenophobia in this country.''
   He said that even as foreign companies have created few new
jobs, they exert little control over the U.S. economy. While
foreign companies employ 3 percent of American workers and own 8
percent of the nation's assets, ``those are still relatively small
numbers,'' he said.
   ``They are growing fast and they are of considerable concern,''
Glickman said. ``But at present, that's an issue which we need to
watch but not be as fearful of.''
   Glickman said foreign investment in the United States has
worsened the nation's trade deficit because the companies' exports
are overshadowed by imports of intermediate goods used in
production.
   Foreign investors had a net trade deficit of about $8 billion in
1986 and the rate has increased since then, Glickman said.
   The authors called for the creation of a government agency to
analyze the economic impact of major foreign investments.
   Woodward said that because the addition of a new foreign-owned
plant can be a big boon to a particular region, local officials
have engaged in counterproductive ``global smokestack chasing,''
offering huge incentives to lure plants their way.
   ``Our mayors and governors are falling all over themselves,''
Woodward said. ``They're frequent fliers at the government's
expense, as if they've discovered this holy grail for economic
development.''
   Woodward said the incentives being offered in some cases cost
tens of thousands of dollars for each job created without holding
companies accountable for a specific contribution to the local
economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
