<DOCNO> AP890509-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WHO-PLO     05-09 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WHO-PLO,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>WHO Representatives Seek Compromise on PLO Bid for Membership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the World Health Organization's
annual assembly worked nervously Tuesday to head off a showdown
with the United States over a PLO request for full membership in
the U.N. body.
   Diplomatic sources said a proposal to put off the decision in
exchange for greater medical aid to Palestinians was gaining
support.
   In a move aggravating tensions, the Palestine Liberation
Organization submitted a separate request Tuesday to be recognized
as a full member by another U.N. agency, Paris-based UNESCO.
   Since the Palestine National Council, which acts as a
parliament-in-exile, proclaimed the state of Palestine last
November, the PLO has been seeking full membership as a state in
all U.N. agencies. It now holds non-voting observer status.
   The United States and its Western allies have not recognized the
new state, which controls no territory. Washington, which pays 25
percent of WHO's regular budget of $625 million for 1988-89, has
threatened to withdraw its money if Palestine is recognized as the
167th member of WHO.
   Diplomats at the WHO assembly, which began Monday, worked
tensely Tuesday in search of a compromise. A senior West European
diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there was a
general desire to reach a compromise, ``but it is like walking on
eggs.''
   Another source, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said
there was growing support for a proposal to combine a postponement
of a decision on PLO membership with increased medical assistance
to Palestinian residents of the Israeli-occupied territories.
   A report by a WHO committee, published Tuesday, said health
services there have remained the same or even deteriorated over the
past four years.
   The authors of the compromise proposal, in a bid to gain PLO
support, suggested that it also express the ``hope'' that ``the
people of Palestine'' would be fully represented in WHO at some
later time, the source said.
   He said most Western countries, the Soviet bloc, and some Third
World countries have indicated support for such language.
   However, sources at the assembly said the United States has
opposed that wording, arguing it implies recognition of Palestinian
statehood.
   Addressing the WHO session, Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, U.S.
Secretary of Health and Human Services, made no reference to
Washington's threat to withdraw funding. But he called on the more
than 1,000 delegates not to let themselves be ``diverted by
political issues.''
   WHO Director-General Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima, in a reference to the
U.S. warning, urged the meeting earlier ``to come to a decision
that will not jeopardize the survival of our organization.''
   In Paris, the PLO presented a letter to Federico Mayor, director
general of the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization, to ask for recognition as a member state.
   The PLO's UNESCO representative, Omar Massalha, said the request
would be put on the agenda of UNESCO's executive board. The body
begins a five-week meeting May 17.
   Final approval, however, must be given by a two-thirds majority
of the 158-nation UNESCO General Conference, which meets in
November.
   Massalha said a nation's vote in favor of the PLO request would
not amount to diplomatic recognization by that country.
   The United States withdrew from UNESCO in 1984, charging it was
too political and mismanaged.
</TEXT>
