<FIRST>r w AM-HHS-Abortion     05-09 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HHS-Abortion,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush To Propose Turning Family Planning Over To States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will soon propoose legislation
to transfer federal family planning programs _ which generate
continual controversy over abortion _ to state control, the
administration's top family planning official told a Senate panel
Tuesday.
   ``Making the states the sole family planning grantees will
enable them to exercise maximum flexibility in tailoring services
to best meet their citizens' needs,'' said Nabers Chambers, deputy
assistant secretary for population affairs at the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   In advocating the transfer, she did not specifically mention
differences over how far federally funded family planning clinics
can go in telling pregnant women about the availablity of abortion,
a matter now being fought over in three separate federal court
suits.
   But Ms. Chambers said giving states authority over how to parcel
out the federal money allocated to them for family planning would
allow them ``flexibility to operate clinics through county
agencies, private agencies, or hospitals as is most appropriate for
each particular state.''
   Congress consistently rejected similar efforts by President
Reagan to transfer the program to state control.
   Ms. Chambers, a holdover from the Reagan administration, headed
the department's Office of Population Affairs last year when
regulations were put in place designed to bar counselors in
federally funded family planning clinics from discussing abortion
with their clients.
   Two of three federal district judges who considered the case
quickly found the regulations in violation of the Public Health
Service Act and an appeals court in Boston recently upheld one of
those two rulings.
   Prior to the appeals court decision, the administration sought
to apply the regulations in parts of the nation not covered by a
court order against them. Ms. Chambers told the Senate committee it
is too soon to say if the administration will pursue that policy in
light of the appeals court decision.
   Faye Wattleton, president of Planned Parenthood Federation of
America, complained the program ``has been subjected to both
political harassment and administration confusion'' since 1981,
when Reagan took office.
   ``Thanks to the efforts of the program's congressional
supporters, and to the basic strength of the program itself, Title
X has largely withstood this array of assaults,'' she said. ``But
they have taken their toll, and the open attacks on Title X that
have been ongoing since 1981 must end.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., the committee chairman, opened
the hearing by stating his intention to have the panel approve a
three-year reauthorization of the family planning legislation on
Friday, observing that the issues are already well known to
committee members.
   Although the program has not been formally reauthorized since
1981, it has continued to operate with annual appropriations based
on the underlying 1981 law.
   Ms. Chambers said $138.3 million is being spent in federal money
this year to provide family planning services through 88 grant
receipients at 4,000 clinics to an estimated 4.3 million women _
about a third of them adolescents.
</TEXT>
