<FIRST>r w AM-IowaTrains     05-09 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Trains,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Board Blames Railroad, Federal Agency, Crew In Wreck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Failures by the Iowa Interstate Railroad and
the Federal Railroad Administration to enforce train operating
rules and a tired train crew's error caused the fiery collision of
two freight trains in Altoona, Iowa, last summer, federal safety
officials concluded Tuesday.
   The July 30 head-on crash killed two crewmen on a westbound
train en route from Newton, Iowa, to Des Moines when it collided
with a train bound from Council Bluffs, Iowa, to Chicago. The two
employees on the eastbound train jumped to safety.
   More than 2,000 people were evacuated from their homes in and
around Altoona as two tank cars containing 20,000 gallons of
denatured alcohol burned for more than two days.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said the eastbound
train, with 78 cars, departed Altoona before its permitted time.
Its crew had been on duty for nearly 10 hours after having only
four or five hours of sleep the night before, the board said.
   ``Contributing to the train crew's failure to comply with the
wait provisions was a combination of fatigue induced by irregular
work-rest schedules, preoccupation with completing their asisgnment
prior to exceeding duty time limits, inexperience, `mental set' or
expectations based on previously issued train orders, the work
activities which intervened since they recieved the train order,
and the failure of (the railroad) to properly train its crews,''
the board said in its finding of a probable cause.
   The board said Iowa Interstate, which operated both trains, had
no way of knowing that the westbound train had departed its initial
terminal because it did not maintain a record of train movements as
required by federal regulations.
   It said, however, the westbound train was being operated
properly and would have had time to clear the area if the eastbound
train had not pulled onto the track early.
   The board cited several deficiencies in the railroad's training
programs and proficiency testing of its employees.
   The Federal Railroad Administration, the board said, failed to
take action against the railroad for not complying with federal
rules. It recommended that the agency conduct a safety audit of
Iowa Interstate.
   The board also recommended that several steps be taken to
decrease the likelihood of tanker cars catching fire, including
improved design to ensure that closure fittings stay closed in
accidents that do not rupture the tank itself. The report said that
release of the alcohol from pressure release valves contributed to
the length of the emergency.
   The board said there was no evidence that any mechanical problem
with either train or track conditions contributed to the crash, or
that alcohol or drug use was a factor.
</TEXT>
