<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves James for HHS Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nomination of a former
right-to-life spokeswoman for top public affairs job at the
Department of Health and Human Services won approval of a Senate
committee on Tuesday despite opposition from Planned Parenthood.
   The pro-choice group, in a letter to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, charged Kay
James' appointment was ``part of the White House reparations
payment'' to satisfy abortion opponents upset by HHS Secretary
Louis Sullivan's early statements supporting a woman's right to
choose.
   ``Her appointment is nothing more than a gift from the Bush
White House to the anti-abortion movement,'' William W. Hamilton
Jr., director of Planned Parenthood Federation of America's
Washington office, said in the letter.
   James told the committee her personal views would not get in the
way of her duties to speak for the government.
   ``It's my job to articulate government policy,'' James said. ``I
have my personal views ... (but) my job isn't to represent my
views. My job is to represent the U.S. government.''
   On the issue of abortion, she said, representing the government
position would be easy since the president opposes abortion except
in cases of rape, incest and danger to the mother's life. Sullivan,
after his initial comments, said he shares Bush's view.
   ``I can serve them both well,'' James said.
   The committee approved Bush's nomination of James by a voice
vote.
