<HEAD>Eds: SUBS item on Boone to INSERT 2 grafs after 4th, `Bell Savings...'
to UPDATE with comment from Boone.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Pat Boone, who used his Lamb &amp;
Lion Records label to spread a Christian message through music, is
seeking reorganization of the label through the U.S. Bankruptcy
Court.
   Lamb &amp; Lion, whose most popular artist is Boone's daughter
Debby, has piled up $355,689 in debts with $62,416 in assets,
according to court papers quoted in Tuesday's editions of the Los
Angeles Times.
   The record label filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of
the federal bankrupty law last September, the newspaper said.
   Bell Savings of San Mateo sued the label in late 1987,
contending that Boone and a former Lamb &amp; Lion executive created
``a fraudulent plan'' to divert $200,000 owed to the savings and
loan to themselves.
   ``The record company is very precious to me and my family,''
Boone said Tuesday. ``We had to restructure,'' he added.
   ``We had to hold Bell Savings off,'' Boone said. ``They wanted
full payment of a loan and we weren't prepared to do that. We have
worked out an amicable settlement with Bell now.''
   Boone's attorney, Richard Green, denied Bell's accusations,
saying a settlement is being worked out.
   Boone, 54, founded the label in 1983. Daughter Debby, best known
for her 1977 hit ``You Light Up My Life,'' recorded albums that
sold more than 100,000 copies each. But the label had no performers
in the million-selling category.
   ``There's nothing complicated to it. Not enough people were
buying their product,'' said Joseph A. Eisenberg, a Lamb &amp; Lion
bankruptcy lawyer.
