<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Noriega     05-09 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Noriega,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Officials Challenge Judge Ruling Over Noriega Documents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs authorities on Tuesday challenged a court
ruling preventing them from handing over to U.S. drug enforcement
agencies documents belonging to Panama's de facto ruler, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Customs agents seeking evidence in a drugs-related,
money-laundering case said they found Noriega family accounts by
chance after raiding a bank in London last October.
   Customs lawyer Andrew Collins said the investigation was not
aimed at Noriega, who was indicted in Florida last year on U.S.
drug trafficking charges. Noriega denied the charges.
   Commissioners of the Customs and Excise Department argued that a
judge's ban on U.S. authorities seeing details of the Noriega
family accounts was unreasonable and interfered with the battle
against global drug dealing.
   Collins told the Court of Appeal the early-morning bank raid
coincided with swoops by drug trade investigators in the United
States.
   Individuals in 10 U.S. cities and Paris and London were accused
of taking part in a ring that laundered profits from the Colombian
cocaine trade through the Luxembourg-based Bank of Credit and
Commerce International, or BCCI Holdings.
   BCCI, two subsidiaries and nine bank officials were charged with
laundering $14 million in drug profits collected from seven U.S.
cities.
   Collins said agents obtained a warrant to enter the bank's
London office and then discovered the office of one suspect was in
an adjoining building.
   He said agents quickly obtained an additional warrant to enter
that building and found a locked cabinet containing files and
accounts belonging to Noriega, his wife Felicidad, daughters Lorena
and Sandra and son-in-law Jean Rene de Beauchamp.
   Collins said the Customs officer believed the files would be
important in investigating Noriega's alleged involvement in drug
trafficking and possibly would help in the BCCI investigation.
   The officer could not remove the documents under the warrant, so
he applied to Southwark Crown Court Judge Valerie Pearlman for an
order requiring the bank to produce the documents for inspection
and the judge so ordered, Collins said.
   The bank challenged the order. The judge upheld the order but
only on condition that U.S. drug enforcement agencies were not
given the documents.
   Collins said the judge was concerned about `an alleged risk to
the bank and its employees in Panama if material was passed on to
the U.S.''
   He asked the Court of Appeal to quash the ruling, saying the law
``makes it perfectly clear that what should concern the court ...
is not only drug trafficking in this country but drug trafficking
in any other country in the world.''
   The hearing is expected to take at least two days.
</TEXT>
