<DOCNO> AP890509-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearPower     05-09 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Power,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Official Says Public Fears Could Doom Nuclear Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States could lose nuclear power as
an energy source unless public confidence in its safety is
restored, a senior Energy Department official said Tuesday.
   ``Without restoration of public understanding of the efficacy
and safety of nuclear power ... there may never well be another
nuclear power plant ordered in the United States,'' John C. Tuck,
the undersecretary of energy, told a nuclear industry group.
   Tuck, in his first major public address since being confirmed
last month as the No. 3 official in the Energy Department, said the
department strongly supported nuclear power and would do everything
possible to help the industry expand.
   ``Rest assured that the Department of Energy will at every
opportunity advocate vigorously on behalf of nuclear energy,'' Tuck
told the Nuclear Power Assembly, the industry's annual meeting.
   ``We will make the case for nuclear power before the American
people, and we will be forceful advocates,'' Tuck said. He
reiterated the department's recent vow to try to prevent New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo from tearing down the Shoreham nuclear plant on
Long Island.
   Shoreham got its operating license from the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission last month, but Cuomo and the plant's owner have agreed
to dismantle it. State and local officials say Long Island could
not be evacuated in the event of a severe accident.
   Lando W. Zech Jr., chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, told the nuclear assembly he was concerned by the fact
that no nuclear plant had been ordered since 1978 and that none
currently was planned. He said the commission's recent decision to
streamline the licensing process could help the industry rebound.
   Zech called the licensing decision ``perhaps the most important
change ever made to the NRC's power reactor licensing process,''
and said it would lead to safer reactor designs.
   In another development, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., introduced a
bill Tuesday to abolish the NRC and replace it with a Nuclear
Safety Agency headed by a single administrator. He said the
five-member commission and its staff had undermined public
confidence in nuclear power by becoming too cozy with the industry.
   A similar bill passed the Senate last year but died in the House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
