<DOCNO> AP890509-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Giuliani     05-09 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Giuliani,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prosecutor Poised for Leap into Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolph W. Giuliani prepared Tuesday to dive
into the race for mayor, counting on his appeal as a crime-fighting
prosecutor to overcome his Republican affiliation in this
overwhelmingly Democratic city.
   Giuliani, who gained fame with a string of high-profile
prosecutions as U.S. attorney in Manhattan, hopes to fashion a
fusion candidacy in the mold of John V. Lindsay in 1965, the last
Republican to win City Hall.
   Giuliani's formal announcement was scheduled Wednesday, ending a
year and a half of speculation about his political future that
continued even as he was putting mobsters, Wall Street cheats and
corrupt politicians in jail.
   ``The city is in very, very bad shape, and the mayor is
responsible for it,'' Giuliani, 44, said in February, while still
considering his prospects. ``The city is in a grave crisis and I
think it's time for new leadership.''
   His decision to offer himself for mayor was bolstered by polls
that have consistently shown him defeating incumbent Mayor Edward
I. Koch or any other likely Democratic nominee in a hypothetical
matchup.
   Giuliani has said for months that he would run only if he
appeared to have enough support to win. But in a city where
Democrats outnumber Republicans 5-1, his victory is by no means
assured.
   He started with a bold, potentially risky stroke last month,
winning the endorsement of the city's tiny Liberal Party and
assuring himself a place on the November ballot. Lindsay did the
same thing.
   Giuliani's next must tackle the Republican primary. He faces a
well-financed challenge from cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder, who's
running as a conservative more in tune with New York's GOP
stalwarts.
   ``The Republican Party has an obligation to choose a candidate
that represents its principles,'' said Nelson Warfield, Lauder's
spokesman. ``We think that Ronald Lauder is that candidate. Rudy
Giuliani, with the Liberal Party endorsement, can't ride two horses
at one time.''
   Giuliani has not ruled out tax increases, Warfield said; Lauder
has.
   Next on the Giuliani-bashing line was Koch, who has been
charging recently that Giuliani can't be counted on to continue
city support of abortions for poor women because Giuliani
personally opposes abortion.
   Giuliani campaign spokesman Charles Perkins said Tuesday that as
mayor Giuliani would continue to fund abortions at current levels.
   Perkins added that Giuliani preferred to focus on ``the issues
the mayor has some ability to confront and resolve, like crime and
drugs and the health care system and the infrastructure.''
   Giuliani also promised to make an issue of integrity. Corruption
scandals have rocked city government, but not touched Koch, since
1986. Giuliani prosecuted the most prominent of those cases,
winning a racketeering conviction of Bronx Democratic boss Stanley
Friedman.
   Following that case, Giuliani was mentioned last year as a
challenger to Democratic U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
Giuliani flirted with the notion, dropped it, then left the
prosecutor's office in January after 5{ years to explore the
mayoral race.
   Koch, his popularity lagging, could lose the Democratic
nomination. Challenger David Dinkins, the Manhattan borough
president, leads in polls. And Giuliani leads in polls pitting him
against Dinkins.
   But it is four months before the primaries, six months before
the general election, and Giuliani, who never has held elective
office, is untried as a campaigner in New York's barefisted
political ring.
   Asked for comment about Giuliani's candidacy, Koch spokesman Lee
Jones said, ``We just think in November he'll regret it.''
</TEXT>
