<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Panama     05-09 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Panama,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Asked to Nullify Canal Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., introduced
legislation Tuesday calling on the Bush administration to nullify
the Panama Canal treaties in light of reports of election fraud in
Panama's presidential elections.
   Mack said the move is justified because it is clear the
country's military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, ``is
stealing the presidential election from the Panamanian people.''
   But White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters the
president has ``no plan to abrogate the canal treaties.''
   Mack acted after examining the conduct of Sunday's election in
Panama as a member of a White House observer team.
   The Panama Canal treaties, ratified in 1977, provide for Panama
to take control of the canal at the end of 1999.
   ``If we were facing this same situation in 1999 rather than
1989, Congress would be falling all over itself looking for a way
to keep control of the canal,'' Mack said. ``Let's work now to
address our concerns with the canal so we're not forced to confront
the issue later,'' Mack said.
   It was not clear whether Mack would be able to muster majority
support for his legislation.
   But apparent fraud in the elections in Panama stirred widespread
condemnation on Capitol Hill.
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., said members of the observer delegation
had told the president ``that we saw such widespread irregularities
and actual fraud that we didn't see any way that it could be a free
and fair election.''
   ``Friends of freedom everywhere share a growing sense of outrage
over the flagrant fraud being committed by Gen. Noriega in his
desperate effort to steal the election and stay in power,'' said
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   ``Gen. Noriega is a disgrace to democracy,'' Kennedy said. ``No
amount of fraud can conceal his overwhelming repudiation by the
citizens of his country.''
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., another member of the observer team,
urged Bush to withdraw U.S. military dependents and U.S. civilians
from Panama while increasing the number of combatants among the
10,000 U.S. troops stationed there to protect the canal.
   But Rep. Larry Smith, D-Fla., said the actual use of military
force was ``the last option you would consider.''
   ``I don't believe the first thing we are going to see is some
sort of war-room exercise of people deciding when they are going to
the mat with Noriega militarily,'' Smith said. ``It's just not
happening.''
</TEXT>
