<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-North 1stLd-Writethru a0693 05-09 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-North, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Wanted to See North Exonerated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To make story stand as Bush roundup, adds comments on missiles,
Noriega, health, subbing 9 grafs for 4th graf pvs, North is</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in his first public comment on
the Oliver North verdict, said Tuesday he had ``wanted all along to
see him exonerated.''
   Asked if he thought North, who was found guilty last Thursday on
three of 12 felony counts, was innocent, the president said: ``I'm
not going to argue with the courts. The process is being appealed.
He's entitled to the right of appeal without a lot of editorial
comment from me, although I've already given you some.''
   Bush was asked about North at the end of an interview with a
group of reporters in the Oval Office.
   On another subject, Bush brushed aside a dispute with West
Germany over short-range nuclear missiles, an issue which threatens
the harmony of a NATO summit May 29-30.
   ``I have a good feeling that there's been a lot of smoke out
there and we'll have a smooth summit,'' Bush said. Asked if that
meant he was willing to compromise, Bush replied, ``It might mean
people are willing to do it our way _ with the United States.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has called for East-West
negotiations soon to reduce short-range weapons in Europe, but the
Bush administration has argued that they are needed to compensate
for an overwhelming superiority in conventional forces by the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Bush also discussed the issue in private with a Dutch delegation
led by Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers.
   The president summoned reporters to his office to declare that
Panama's presidential election on Sunday was marred by fraud and to
call on Manuel Antonio Noriega to ``heed the call of the people''
and relinquish power.
   ``And I call on all foreign leaders to urge General Noriega to
honor the clear results of the election,'' Bush said.
   On a personal matter, Bush will undergo a routine physical
examination, his first as president, at Bethesda Naval Hospital on
Wednesday.
   Bush, 64, told reporters, ``Never felt better in my life.''
   As for North, the former White House aide is awaiting sentencing
on his convictions of illegally destroying and altering government
documents, accepting an illegal gratuity and aiding and abetting in
obstruction of Congress' investigation of the Iran-Contra affair.
   White House officials have said Bush has not discussed the
possibility of a pardon for North.
   Bush, when asked his reaction to the verdict, said, ``As you
know, I wanted all along to see him exonerated. The matter is now
under appeal, and thus I'll have nothing more to say about it while
it is.''
   As the interview broke up, he was asked, ``You don't believe in
shredding documents, do you?''
   ``I believe in taking them with me,'' he joked.
   Bush said several times during the 1988 presidential campaign
that he believed North would be aquitted of charges stemming from
his role in the Reagan administration's efforts to help the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   He has also called North a hero, saying he was referring to the
retired Marine lieutenant colonel's record in Vietnam.
   A government-approved document introduced during North's trial
said Bush met early in 1985 in Honduras with then-president Roberto
Suazo. It said Bush informed Suazo of then-President Reagan's
decision to speed U.S. military and economic aid to the country _
expedited aid that the document said had been approved as part of a
deal to gain Honduran support for the Contras.
   The document did not say Bush was part of any such deal, and he
said emphatically last week that despite what the document said
there was no deal, ``no quid pro quo.''
</TEXT>
