<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Ozone-IndustryReax     05-09 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone-Industry Reax,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers May Not Meet Vermont Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ozone-Cars, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Big Three automakers said Tuesday
they're working as fast as they can to eliminate from car air
conditioners a chemical that attacks the Earth's ozone layer, but
it may not be fast enough.
   The Vermont Legislature has passed and the governor is expected
to sign a bill that after 1993 would outlaw the registration of
vehicles whose air conditioners contain CFC-12.
   CFC-12 is a type of chlorofluorocarbon, or CFC, a class of
chemicals best known under the trade name Freon. Most other CFC
applications, such as refrigerators, use different types of CFC.
   Chlorofluorocarbons that rise into the upper atmosphere attack
the protective ozone layer. Scientists say that lets in extra
ultraviolet radiation that increases the number of cases of skin
cancer and eye disease and that damages plants and animals crucial
to the food chain.
   Researchers at General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp. and their suppliers have been looking for ways to eliminate
CFC-12 from their cars' air conditioning systems.
   Most of the research is going into a substance called 134-A,
which contains no chlorofluorocarbons.
   ``Work is continuing as if it is the substance of choice,'' said
Douglas Mark, an emission engineer for GM.
   But there are problems.
   ``There is no (compatible) lubricant and the toxicological
testing is not finished,'' said Norm Nielsen, supervisor of
government regulatory programs at Chrysler. ``Officially, it will
take three or four years to finish.''
   Mark noted that long-term health tests of 134-A are expected to
go through 1992, when the 1993 model-year vehicles mentioned in the
Vermont law will be in production.
   The automobile industry has learned to live with California
regulations governing exhaust emissions that are stiffer than other
states. Cars made for sale in California have different exhaust
emission control systems than for general sale.
   But officials of the Big Three automakers say there are more
problems switching from CFC-12 to something else than in switching
equipment to meet California air quality standards.
   ``The whole system has to be changed,'' Mark said. ``There's got
to be compressor and evaporator changes. Materials have to be
re-evaluated for seals and hoses.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
