<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Carter     05-09 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Carter,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Carter Stormed Out Of Election HQ to Denounce Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Panama, Bjt ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter walked
into Panama's vote tabulation center with an open mind but stormed
out after he found election officials were cheating, according to
his aide Bob Pastor.
   ``He took every step in the process at face value,'' Pastor said
of Carter on Monday. ``And when he got to the final step and they
were cheating, he said `Stop.'''
   He said that inside the center on Monday, Carter found officials
tabulating counterfeit vote tally sheets to give government
candidate Carlos Duque a victory in Sunday's election.
   Election Tribunal spokesman Boris Moreno said Carter told the
election officials they should resign rather than participate in a
fraud, and the head of the tabulation commission then told Carter
he was a guest and could not pass judgment.
   Carter walked out.
   The Panamanians refused to let him use the official press center
so he held a news conference across the street in a crowded, narrow
lobby at the Marriott Hotel.
   Carter angrily denounced Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, head of
the Panamanian Defense Forces, as a dictator who was stealing an
election from his own people.
   Carter, who had been granted a visit with Noriega on Saturday,
said he thought the general had fooled himself and sincerely
believed that Duque, his hand-picked candidate, would win in a fair
election.
   He said he would not meet Noriega again unless the general
declared he was prepared to honor the vote.
   Carter didn't expect that and he left Tuesday morning from the
U.S. Southern Command's Howard Air Force Base on a flight to
Washington where he met with President Bush.
   Carter was not in the official U.S. delegation sent by Bush to
Panama to observe the elections but was an observer from the
unofficial Council of Freely Elected Heads of Government. Carter is
the head of the council.
</TEXT>
