<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-09 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Produce More Severe Weather In Texas And Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms returned to the South on Tuesday with hail as big
as golf balls and damaging wind, and thunderstorms spread over
parts of the East.
   Thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front produced large
hail and high wind in northeastern Texas and northwestern Louisiana
during the late morning.
   Hail 2 inches in diameter fell near Atlanta, Texas, and hail as
big as golf balls fell at Mira and Benton, La., the National
Weather Service said. Winds gusting to 62 mph accompanied the hail
at Mira.
   By afternoon, the storms extended into northwestern Mississippi.
   Showers and scattered thunderstorms developing ahead of a warm
front extended from the Carolinas to the Ohio Valley during the
afternoon. Flood watches were posted through the night for western
Maryland, West Virginia's Eastern Panhandle, and central Virginia.
   In the West, a cold front crossing the Pacific Coast produced
showers in western Oregon and northwestern California. Showers and
thundershowers were widely scattered over southern and central
California and southern Nevada.
   Drizzle fell in the middle Mississippi Valley and the central
high Plains.
   An apparent tornado tore through the Moseley area of
northeastern Oklahoma near the Arkansas border late Monday, ripping
up country homes, barns, trees and power lines in a four-mile path,
West Siloam Springs police dispatcher Becky Stockton said Tuesday.
No deaths or serious injuries were reported.
   ``One home rolled over on its top and the girl inside was in it
when it rolled, but she came out with just a scratch on her arm,''
said Oklahoma Highway Patrol Capt. Leroy Hendren.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 50
degrees at Oscoda and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 100 at Gila Bend,
Ariz. Tuesday's low for the 48 contiguous states was 25 at
Phillips, Wis.
   Wednesday's forecast called for numerous showers and
thunderstorms in the Carolinas and widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms in most of the rest of the Southeast; showers from
Virginia and eastern Kentucky to the northern Atlantic Coast
states; and scattered showers and thunderstorms across much of the
West, with widely scattered showers and thunderstorms over south
central Texas and the southern High Plains.
   Highs only in the 50s were predicted in the Great Lakes region,
the upper Ohio Valley and the Northeast; in the 50s and 60s from
the Tennessee Valley to the upper Mississippi Valley and the middle
and northern Atlantic Coast states; in the 60s across the Pacific
Northwest and along the California coast; in the 80s from Florida
and southern Georgia, across much of Texas and the northern High
Plains; and in the 80s and 90s in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
