<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Netherlands     05-09 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Netherlands,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Dutch Leaders Discuss European Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch leaders met twice with President Bush on
Tuesday in an effort to find a solution to NATO differences over
short-range nuclear missiles.
   Bush told reporters he set aside an additional hour to discuss
the issue with the delegation led by Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers
and that he expected the differences with the West German
government to be cleared up by the time of the NATO summit in three
weeks.
   ``I have a good feeling that there's been a lot of smoke out
there and that we'll have a smooth summit,'' Bush said.
   But, he added, ``I don't believe in deadlines.''
   Bush was asked whether he had had any more telephone
conversations with West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on the
problem. Kohl opposes modernizing U.S. short-range missiles
stationed in Europe and wants to negotiate with the Soviet Union
for elimination of the weapons.
   ``Oh, I never discuss these _ all these talks I've had,'' Bush
said.
   Kohl was reported to have been irritated that the White House
disclosed that he and Bush discussed their differences in a phone
call on Friday.
   The Bush administration has argued that short-range missiles are
needed in Europe to compensate for an overwhelming superiority in
conventional forces by the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Bush said Lubbers was ``a friend of long standing'' and that
they would be able to discuss the issue ``very, very frankly.''
   ``But this alliance is not going to fall apart,'' said Bush.
``It is going to stay together and be strong. And we'll work it
out.''
   Asked whether the United States was willing to compromise, Bush
said, ``It might mean people are willing to do it our way. We're
the United States.''
   Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek said his country had
presented a compromise solution at meetings going on in Brussels at
the headquarters of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. But he declined to say what the Dutch text contained.
   Van den Broek said a possible solution to the rift, which
threatens to disrupt a NATO summit scheduled for May 29, would be
for the allies to ask for unilateral cuts in the Soviet short-range
missile arsenal.
   A West German official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said, however, that Bonn has grave reservations about unilateral
cutbacks because they might not be verifiable and that an agreement
including verification procedures would be preferable.
</TEXT>
