<HEAD>Armed Robbery Charge Dropped Against `Diff'rent Strokes' Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charge of armed robbery against
``Diff'rent Strokes'' star Todd Bridges was dropped Tuesday after
prosecutors said they had new information on the case, which they
declined to describe.
   Bridges, 23, still faces attempted murder charges for a Feb. 2
shooting at a reputed drug den in south-central Los Angeles in
which the victim survived and later identified his attackers.
Another man also is charged in that case.
   Bridges for eight years played the character Willis Jackson on
``Diff'rent Strokes'' opposite costars Gary Coleman and Conrad Bain.
   In the armed robbery charge, investigators said Bridges took his
BMW from a repair shop at gunpoint Jan. 23 instead of paying a $500
repair bill. The shooting also stemmed from a dispute over the same
car, investigators have said.
   But when Bridges' preliminary hearing was about to begin
Tuesday, Deputy District Attorney Robert Gosney moved to dismiss
the charges.
   ``Some new information came in that cast a serious doubt (on)
whether we had the right man,'' Gosney said.
   He declined to describe the information, and said the robbery
charge may be refiled against Bridges if the new evidence fails to
stand.
   Authorities have said Bridges was one of two men who had taken
the car in for repairs.
