<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-09 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Chief To Resign On May 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reformer Stipe Suvar will step aside
as Communist Party chief next week, but he will join the
government's influential nine-member presidency, news reports said
Tuesday.
   He would have been forced to give up his party post next month
anyway, because the party leadership rotates annually. Beginning in
June, the leadership transfers to a party official from the
republic of Macedonia.
   Suvar recently was elected to represent the republic of Croatia
in the nine-man state presidency. News reports said he will be
inaugurated as a member of the presidency on May 15 and resign as
party chief on May 17.
   The seat on the presidency assures Suvar a continued role on the
national political stage, where he is battling his Serbian
political rival, Slobodan Milosevic.
   He is a more authoritarian, orthodox Communist than Suvar,
although both men have backed market-oriented reforms.
   Milosevic was proclaimed Monday as president of the republic of
Serbia, which gives him largely a figurehead role in the largest of
Yugoslavia's six republics. In addition, Milosevic will have to
give up his seat on the national party's ruling Politburo.
   The dispute between Suvar and Milosevic reflects ethnic divides
between the Serbs, the dominant ethnic group in Yugoslavia's
patchwork of nationalities, and the rival Croats and other northern
people.
   Milosevic has bolstered Serbian authority in the province of
Kosovo, where the ethnic Albanian majority rioted over his policies
in March. The clashes in the province on the Albanian border left
at least 24 dead.
   Media reports on Tuesday quoted Suvar as saying that ``because
of the political quarrels within the party, tomorrow we could have
brutal clashes'' because of mounting economic and political strife.
   Yugoslavia suffers an annual inflation rate of about 500
percent, which has helped fuel ethnic tensions.
   Serbia's security chief, Dragutin Mitrovic, told Yugoslav
journalists Tuesday that police have stepped up security in Kosovo
after intercepting reports that ethnic Albanians plan sabotage and
assassination attempts on senior Communist officials there and in
neighboring Serbia.
   Mitrovic said ``there exists a latent danger'' of further unrest
by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo ``primarily in the form of acts of
sabotage and assassinations.''
   He said targets of ``hostile Albanian emigres'' include
``leading personalities in Serbia and Kosovo'' but gave no details.
He also did not elaborate on the new security measures.
   Many security forces have already been deployed in Kosovo, and a
state of emergency imposed during the unrest remains in place.
   In a related development, the state Tanjug news agency said 12
people, including eight policeman, were arrested in the republic of
Montenegro and accused of selling stolen firearms to Albanians in
Kosovo.
   The eight policeman reportedly had served in Kosovo.
   The weapons included pistols, semi-automatic rifles and a
machine gun, Tanjug said.
</TEXT>
