<FIRST>r i AM-China-Teachers     05-09 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Teachers,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Rampant Teacher Bashing in Henan Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers all over China grumble about their
miserable pay, but those in Henan province also are subjected to
physical violence.
   The Guangming Daily, the national newspaper for intellectuals,
reported about the violence against in a front-page article Tuesday
with the headline ``The Disgrace of the Cradle of Civilization.''
   ``A section of cadres and the masses look down on learning, and
their concept of despising education has not fundamentally
changed,'' it said.
   Intellectuals, once considered the elite in China, have had low
social status since the Communists came to power 40 years ago.
During the Cultural Revolution of 1966-76, they were called ``the
stinking ninth class.''
   From the beginning of 1988 through April 1989, there were 156
incidents of teachers being beaten or otherwise injured or
humiliated in Henan, the paper reported. It said three of the
teachers died and 13 suffered serious injuries.
   Among those attacked was Zhang Xipei, a high school principal
who tried in February 1988 to expel a girl who insisted on carrying
a dagger to school, it said.
   Her uncle went to Zhang's house with a group of men and egged
them on with with shouts of ``Ruthlessly attack _ 500 yuan for
breaking a leg, 1,000 yuan for gouging out an eye!'' the Guangming
Daily reported. The top reward of 1,000 yuan is about $270.
   Zhang and his daughter were seriously injured.
   Although the government says it is committed to improving the
living standard of teachers, their pay typically is only half that
of factory workers.
   Violence is nothing new to teachers in Henan. In 1987, the China
Education Newspaper reported more than 200 cases of teachers being
beaten.
</TEXT>
