<FIRST>r w AM-Medicare-Catastrophic     05-09 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare-Catastrophic,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Confirms Deficit in Medicare Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report delivered to Congress on
Tuesday confirms earlier projections the prescription drug program
under the new Medicare catastrophic care program will run about $3
billion short by 1993.
   The report by the Department of Health and Human Services
projects that over the first four years of the program, benefit
payments will exceed premium revenues by nearly $1 billion, or $3
billion, including administrative costs.
   New benefits under the program will expand coverage of
prescription drugs received outside of the hospital beginning Jan.
1, 1991. The program includes a schedule of co-payments by
beneficiaries.
   The drug benefits will be financed partly by an increase in the
monthly flat-rate premium paid by those eligible for Medicare,
which rose to $4 this year and is scheduled to go up to $4.90 in
1990 and $7.40 in 1991.
   Money for the benefits also come from a surtax on income taxes
of on Medicare beneficiaries. The maximum surtax on any person is
$800 this year, or $1,600 for a couple if both spouses are eligible.
   A Congressional Budget Office report recently estimated that
these revenues would bring $4.9 billion more than is needed to fund
the catastrophic illness benefits and build up a reserve.
   The report prompted Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, to suggest that
premiums for the new program could be cut. President Bush, however,
opposed the idea, saying the surplus might be needed because of
projections that the expanded drug benefits are underfunded.
</TEXT>
