<FIRST>r w AM-SEC-CrashStudy     05-09 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Crash Study,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Study Says Computer Traders Had Effect Before October Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study Tuesday by a Securities and
Exchange Commission economist found that computerized trading
strategies influenced stock prices in the days leading up to the
Oct. 19, 1987, crash but not on the day of the crash.
   The study, prepared by SEC economist Dean Furbush and by custom
not adopted as a formal position by the commission, is the latest
contribution to what has been a hotly debated point.
   Those who advocate combining the regulation of stock and stock
index futures markets under one agency have maintained that
lightening-fast trading of huge quantities of stocks and futures
contracts contributed to the record 508-point plunge in the Dow
Jones average of industrial stocks.
   Although separate federal agencies continue to regulate stock
and futures markets, the exchanges have agreed among themselves to
suspend trading across markets when prices plunge in one of the
markets.
   A presidential task force headed by Nicholas F. Brady, now
Treasury secretary, found last year that just a few institutional
investors using a computer-trading strategy known as portfolio
insurance ``played a dominant role'' during the stock crash.
   The SEC in an earlier study said program trading, while not
causing the crash, made it faster and worse than it would have been.
   However, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which fought
a successful turf war to maintain its power over the trading of
stock futures contracts, found in its study that program trading
``does not appear to have played a major role in the crash.''
   Furbush, who examined the relationship of stock and futures
trading at five-minute intervals from Oct. 14 to Oct. 20, partly
backs that view, finding ``greater price declines were not found to
occur systematically during times of more intensive program
trading'' on Oct. 19.
   However, he said, ``the volume of ... program trading (was)
related to (stock price) changes ... on Oct. 14, 15 and 16.''
   Furbush said by Oct. 19 the relationship between the stock and
futures markets was breaking down and on Oct. 20, when the New York
Stock Exchange had suspended use of its computerized trading
system, the volume of program trading declined dramatically.
</TEXT>
