<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-09 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Claims Vietnamese Still Fighting Near Thai Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese troops have not withdrawn
from areas near the Cambodian-Thai border and are still shelling
refugee camps there, according to the Khmer Rouge guerrillas.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach, during a recent
visit to Bangkok, said Vietnam had pulled its troops back to points
at least 19 miles from the border. Vietnam has said it began the
withdrawal from the border zone in late 1987 as a peace gesture to
Thailand.
   The Khmer Rouge, the largest Cambodian guerrilla force, said in
a broadcast that the Vietnamese statements were false.
   A text of Sunday's broadcast was obtained in Bangkok on Tuesday.
It said:
   ``When Nguyen Co Thach released that statement, the Cambodian
resistance forces and the Vietnamese aggressor troops were fighting
vigorously and fiercely along the border.
   ``The Hanoi troops stationed along the border fired thousands of
artillery shells into Cambodian refugee camps in Thailand, killing
and wounding a number of residents.
   ``At times Vietnamese soldiers even intruded into Thai
territory, such as in the Pailin area.'' There was no independent
confirmation of the Khmer Rouge claims.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the radical
Khmer Rouge that had ruled the country since the spring of 1975 and
set up another communist government.
   The Khmer Rouge came to power by defeating the U.S.-backed
Cambodian government. During its brief rule up to 2 million
Cambodians were killed in purges or died of starvation.
   After the Vietnamese action the Khmer Rouge reverted to
guerrilla warfare and subsequently formed a fractious resistance
coalition with supporters of Prince Norodom Sihanounk and
anti-communist forces of former Premier Son Sann.
   Another Khmer Rouge broadcast Sunday repeated the rejection of
recent peace proposals and a cease-fire.
   The broadcast said, ``What the Vietnamese have done is only to
change their appearance with the aim of fooling international
opinion, but their administrative and military networks remain the
same from top to bottom in Cambodia.''
   At a meeting last week in Indonesia, Sihanouk and Cambodian
Premier Hun Sen agreed to a Thai proposal that the Cambodian
factions observe a cease-fire before the complete withdrawal of the
Vietnamese from Cambodia.
   Vietnam, with up to 70,000 soldiers in Cambodia, has pledged to
remove all of its military forces by Sept. 30.
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan said Monday a cease-fire could
only be part of an overall solution.
   ``We cannot accept a cease-fire that keeps in place a puppet
regime,'' he said of the Hun Sen government.
   Hun Sen has ruled out Khmer Rouge participation in any
provisional government.
</TEXT>
