<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HurricaneFlights     05-09 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Flights,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force To Continue Hurricane Hunters For Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force agreed Tuesday to maintain its
fleet of ``hurricane hunters'' for the next two years, reversing
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's plans to scrap weather
reconnaissance flights in the midst of the hurricane season,
lawmakers said.
   ``It's a good resolution of the problem,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, said late Tuesday after a group of coastal states
lawmakers met with acting Air Force Secretary Jack Welch and other
officials of the Pentagon and National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   NOAA and the Air Force will attempt to work out an agreement
over the next two years on which agency would eventually man the
planes that fly into the eye of a hurricane, lawmakers said.
   It has been suggested the hurricane hunters become the
responsibility of NOAA, but Bentsen and others contend the agency
would be unable to take over the program on such quick notice.
   Cheney said the flights, used to predict the intensity and
position of an approaching hurricane, were not a defense mission
and sought to save at least $14 million annually by slashing the
program.
   But lawmakers complained that phasing it out this summer would
leave hurricane-prone regions dangerously exposed.
   Rep. Greg Laughlin, D-Texas, said keeping the hurricane hunters
``is to the American citizens' benefit so they know whether the
hurricane has the intensity to require an evacuation.''
   The Pentagon officials told the group the Air Force decided to
eliminate the program because ``they thought they had an agreement
with NOAA'' for it to assume responsibility for the hurricane
hunters, ``and there was no agreement,'' Laughlin said after the
closed-door session.
   Rep. Tom Lewis, R-Fla., said ``we feel there's no way peacetime
dollars can be better spent.''
   Cheney had recommended the Air Force halt the reconnaissance
flights by Oct. 1, when the new fiscal year begins.
   In testimony before a House committee last week, National
Hurricane Center Director Robert C. Sheets said the aircraft ``are
the only means of making direct measurements of location, strength
and windfield distributions critical to the hurricane forecast and
warning process.''
</TEXT>
