<DOCNO> AP890509-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Fusion     05-09 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Fusion Researchers Concede Measurement Errors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two chemists went before 1,800 colleagues to
bolster their claim of achieving nuclear fusion at room
temperature, but failed to sway doubters and admitted problems
plague some of their measurements.
   ``I think they're clearly on the ropes at this point,''
physicist Steven Koonin of the California Institute of Technology
in Pasadena said Tuesday after the presentation by Martin
Fleischmann and B. Stanley Pons.
   However, Koonin said the possible achievement of
room-temperature fusion in an experiment by Pons and Fleischmann's
scientific rival, Steven Jones of Brigham Young University, ``is
looking pretty good and there may be some real physics there.''
   There is growing evidence indicating that experiments conducted
by Jones may have created room-temperature fusion, ``but not enough
to heat anything,'' Koonin said.
   Pons, of the University of Utah, and Fleischmann, of England's
Southampton University, announced March 23 that they had created
nuclear fusion in a flask.
   Such an accomplishment, if confirmed, could lead to a cheap,
virtually inexhaustible source of energy.
   However, Pons and Fleischmann are facing a growing number of
critics who have attacked their experimental measurements and
conclusions.
   Their appearance Monday night at the Electrochemical Society
Inc.'s meeting at the Westin Bonaventure Hotel had been billed as
the pair's opportunity to present new evidence to substantiate
their claims.
   Instead, Pons and Fleischmann acknowledged they may have made
errors in their measurements of neutrons and gamma radiation during
their experiments at the University of Utah.
   ``We are well aware those measurements are deficient,''
Fleischmann said.
   He and Pons also said their most recent experiments yielded 10
to 50 times more energy than was consumed to operate their fusion
device. In their March announcement, they said they had produced
four times more energy.
   Unlike fission, which generates energy by splitting the atom,
fusion generates tremendous energy by fusing two atoms together. It
is the process occurring in the sun and hydrogen bombs.
   Most efforts to achieve fusion have focused on forcing atoms
together by brute force, using multimillion-dollar machines
operating at extremely high temperature and pressure.
   But Pons and Fleischmann claimed they created fusion by finesse,
using relatively simple laboratory equipment to coax hydrogen atoms
to fuse in a low-level electric field.
   Their apparatus sent an electrical current through an electrode
made of palladium and wrapped with platinum while immersed in heavy
water, which is made with a form of hydrogen called deuterium.
   Koonin said that while Jones' experiments measured atoms fusing
at a rate of about one per second, the heat described by Pons and
Fleischmann would require a fusion rate of about one-hundred
trillion fusions per second.
   Experimental findings presented at the meeting, particularly by
researchers at Texas A&amp;M University, tend to ``confirm Jones, but
they wouldn't confirm Pons and Fleischmann,'' Koonin said.
   ``Something real is happening here,'' said Robert Huggins of
Stanford University, noting that he got 40 percent more heat from
his experiment than he put into it.
   Several other scientists at the meeting said they successfully
produced excess heat or other signs of fusion, such as neutrons,
but stopped short of saying their studies proved fusion had
happened.
   Many major laboratories have been unable to duplicate Pons and
Fleischmann's results.
   ``There is no fusion,'' one of their most vocal critics, Caltech
chemist Nathan Lewis, said at Monday's meeting.
   He disputed claims by Pons and Fleischmann that their device
produced excess heat, or that it yielded byproducts of fusion,
including helium, tritium, neutrons and gamma rays.
   Fleischmann and Pons disputed Lewis and other critics who
accused them of sloppiness in their measurements, and Pons said
scientists unable to duplicate their experiments failed to use
large enough palladium electrodes.
   But, Fleischmann added, ``I have always been ready to
acknowledge the fact our experiments could be faulty. If we turn
out to be wrong, I'll be the first to admit it.''
   He acknowledged that evidence of gamma radiation was the ``least
satisfactory'' part of their research. ``We are doing a complete
new set of measurements with improved techniques,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, they maintained their experiments generated excess
heat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
