<DATELINE>OAKHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of an aerobics class got to
exercise their political clout when they happened on a town meeting
in need of voters.
   The three selectmen, the town moderator, the town clerk and the
administrative assistant all gathered in the Oakham Center School
gym in this central Massachusetts city Monday evening.
   But no residents showed up because it had been previously
announced that the annual session would be postponed until late
June, when state aid figures are expected to be available.
   The problem was that residents had to vote to postpone the
meeting.
   The dilemma was solved when a group of women in leotards walked
in for their class. Town Clerk Abby Dolson polled them and found a
sufficient number of registered voters.
   The postponement was unanimously approved and the voters got on
with their exercises.
