<FIRST>r w AM-VocationalEducation     05-09 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vocational Education,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Education Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted easy approval Tuesday of a
bill bankrolling vocational education programs, but only after
adding an amendment permitting voluntary prayer in the schools.
   The bill, passed 402-3, provides $1.4 billion for combined
academic and vocational education.
   It provides money to states and to local school districts based
on a complicated formula which gives advantages to disadvantaged
and handicapped students.
   Before passing the bill, the House voted 269-135 approval of an
amendment by Rep. William E. Dannemeyer, R-Calif., denying any
money to programs which have ``a policy of denying or which
effectively prevents participation in prayer in public schools by
individuals on a voluntary basis'' would be denied funds. That
amendment passed by a 269-135 vote, with 31 members not voting.
   ``It was just an opportunity. It was a last-minute thing. It
caught everybody by surprise,'' said Paul Mero, a spokesman for
Dannemeyer.
   Mero said the amendment is a prelude to a proposed
constitutional amendment for voluntary school prayer which he said
Dannemeyer will soon offer.
   The bill makes some changes in the way the money would be
administered. For example, it eliminates most of the specific
categories, known as set-asides.
   A compromise ``hold harmless'' amendment addressed concerns
expressed by some members that no school district be drastically
cut or get an unexpected windfall in the new funding formula.
   That formula provides an increase from the current 32 percent to
80 percent of federal money is passed through from the state level
to local school districts, community colleges and area schools.
   The amendment, offered by Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., would
phase in the new formula over three years with no school district
being allocated less than 80 percent of what it received in the
preceding fiscal year.
   The Senate also has passed legislation reauthorizing federal
funding for vocational education.
   Both measures now go to a conference committee where one
education committee staffer predicted the voluntary prayer
provision would be dropped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
