<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Echandia     05-09 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Echandia,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Colombian Vice President Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Dario Echandia
Olaya, a senior statesman who served as president four times, has
died. He was 91.
   Echandia died Sunday at Tolima Hospital in Ibague, the capital
of Tolima state in central Colombia, the hospital announced. He had
suffered for nearly two years from heart and lung problems, it said.
   In 1938, Echandia was defeated in a presidential election by
Eduardo Santos.
   He was never elected president by popular vote. However, he
served as vice president and four times took over briefly as a
caretaker president.
   On one of those occasions, Echandia served as president from
October 1943 to May 1944 while President Alfonso Lopez Pumarejo
traveled abroad in search of a cure for his ailing wife.
   During his career, Echandia also served as president of the
congress, president of the supreme court, as well as minister of
foreign affairs, the interior, justice, and education.
   He was also president of the Liberal Party, the country's
leading party.
   Echandia was buried Monday in Ibague. No information was
available on his survivors.
</TEXT>
