<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia     05-09 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government's Presidential Candidate Gains Congressional Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party's presidential
candidate gained a firm lead Tuesday in congressional support and
was favored to be elected by Congress in August.
   None of the nine presidential candidates received a majority in
Sunday's national elections. Under the electoral law, the new
Congress will convene Aug. 4 and elect the winner from the three
top vote-getters.
   They are Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada of the governing
Revolutionary Nationalist Movement; former military dictator Gen.
Hugo Banzer of the center-right Nationalist Democratic Action; and
Jaime Paz Zamora, candidate of the Social Democratic Movement of
the Revolutionary Left.
   Congressional elections also were held Sunday for all 27 Senate
and 130 House of Deputies seats, which will be divided among the
parties according to the number of votes they received in each
province.
   Unofficial results with 70 percent of the ballots counted gave
Sanchez de Lozada's conservative party 11 Senate seats and 38 House
of Deputies seats for a total of 49, Banzer 7 and 37 for 44 and Paz
Zamora 7 and 32 for 39.
   Most of the ballots still to be tabulated are from remote areas
where Sanchez de Lozada's party was reported running about 6
percent ahead of Banzer's. The election commission will issue its
official final results May 28.
   Both Banzer and Sanchez de Lozada, who were also running
neck-and-neck in the popular vote for president, claimed victory.
   The president selected by Congress will take office for a
four-year term, and the three contenders now must try to strike
political bargains to win.
   In the first round in Congress, any one of the three could be
elected president. In the second round, Congress will decide
between the two who won the most votes in the first round.
   Political observers said Sanchez de Lozada is in a position to
negotiate with either Banzer or Paz Zamora for their support. They
said Banzer might try to form an alliance with Paz Zamora to beat
Sanchez de Lozada, but such an alliance is unlikely.
   They noted many left-wing members of Paz Zamora's party were
jailed, killed or exiled while Banzer was president from 1971-78.
</TEXT>
