<FIRST>u a AM-GreenwoodShooting     05-09 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenwood Shooting,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Sentenced to the Electric Chair for School Rampage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman who went on a rampage at an
elementary school last fall, killing two children and wounding nine
other people, was sentenced Tuesday to the electric chair.
   James W. Wilson, 20, showed no emotion during the sentencing by
Circuit Judge James Moore. Asked earlier if he had a statement to
make, Wilson replied, ``I have nothing to say.''
   Wilson pleaded guilty but mentally ill last month to two counts
of murder and other charges stemming from the Sept. 26 shooting at
the Oakland Elementary School.
   Wilson walked into the northwestern South Carolina school and
sprayed the cafeteria and a classroom with gunfire, killing
classmates Shequila Bradley and Tequila Thomas, both 8, and
wounding seven students and two teachers.
   The sentence brought sighs of relief from relatives of the
victims.
   ``I'm happy. I'm satisfied,'' said a tearful Linda Davis, whose
8-year-old son, Joseph, was among the wounded.
   Wilson's father, James, said he was disappointed in the
sentence, noting that his son has suffered from mental illness
since he was 14.
   Psychiatrists who examined Wilson testified during his
competency hearing last month that he had a borderline personality
disorder, an illness bordering on schizophrenia.
   Defense attorneys had asked for a life sentence with psychiatric
treatment for their client. Prosecutors sought the death penalty.
   State Chief Deputy Attorney General Donald Zelenka said the
judge clearly found that Wilson knew what he was doing at the time
of the rampage.
   Moore also sentenced Wilson to 175 years in prison on nine
counts of assault and battery and one count of carrying a gun into
a school.
   All death penalty cases in South Carolina are automatically
appealed.
</TEXT>
