<FIRST>u p AM-HiltonHeadGrowth 1stLd-Writethru a0706 05-09 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hilton Head Growth, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islanders Vote Not to Limit Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with residents refusing to limit growth,
quotes, editing to conform; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this burgeoning
golf-and-tennis resort refused Tuesday to clamp down on growth by
tying construction to how long motorists have to wait at lights.
   The referendum for limited development received 9,364 negative
votes, or 68 percent, to 2,995, or 32 percent, in favor, said Town
Clerk Tommy Malone.
   ``As far as we know, this kills this particular issue,'' Ms.
Malone said. ``We were really surprised at the outcome. We expected
it to be very close.''
   However, the measure's author, former Town Councilman Don Hook,
said he had not ruled out the possibility of future referendums.
   Ms. Malone said earlier that she expected a turnout of 50
percent to 60 percent of the island's 14,500 registered voters.
   The measure would have frozen building permits if traffic, as
measured at any of several specified locations, slowed such that
drivers must wait more than two turns of a traffic light during the
peak of the tourist season in June.
   The moratorium would have been lifted once steps to alleviate
the congestion were undertaken.
   Proponents said it would put some teeth into a planning
ordinance approved by residents three years ago. Opponents say the
ordinance already is strong and that a moratorium would cost jobs
and hurt the local economy.
   The population on this 12- by 5-mile seaside resort has grown
from 6,500 year-round residents in 1975 to an estimated 20,000
today. About 1.1 million tourists visit the island each year,
according to the Chamber of Commerce.
   The state Attorney General's Office indicated the measure was
probably unconstitutional because it could deprive property owners
of the use of their property without compensation.
   The measure was placed on the ballot after author Hook and 11
other islanders mounted a petition drive to take the issue to the
voters.
   Last month, the Council approved 6-1 a resolution urging
islanders to reject the measure.
   A telephone survey by The Island Packet newspaper in February
indicated that some 38 percent of those polled were undecided about
the issue.
</TEXT>
