<HEAD>One Killed, 20 Arrested in Anti-Government Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour general
strike over food prices and inflation paralyzed Santo Domingo and
about 20 other cities Tuesday. A youth was killed and 20 people
were arrested in clashes with police.
   Schools, stores and public transportation shut down throughout
most of this West Indies nation of more than 6.5 million people as
thousands of Dominicans obeyed a call by workers' unions to strike
over food prices and for higher pay. Police said a Secret Service
officer accidentally shot a 17-year-old youth in the head and
killed him during a confrontation in Santo Domingo. No other
casualties were reported.
   Police said youths set up flaming tire barricades in several
areas.
   Hardly any buses ran in this capital city of 2 million people.
   Strike organizers demanded that President Joaquin Balaguer's
government take immediate measures against inflation, now running
at about 30 percent.
   They also demanded improved public services. The power sector
has been plagued by blackouts and water shortages.
   Organizers threatened to extend the walkout unless the
government acted.
