<SECOND>AM-Stubborn Silos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dynamite Charge Makes Stubborn Silos Topple in Fort Worth</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE five more silos fell after Tuesday's
blasting; picks up 3rd graf, ```We were ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 10 dynamite explosions in as many
days, a grain elevator has finally yielded a large section to
demolition crews.
   Attempts began more than a week ago to topple the 110-foot
concrete elevator, built around the turn of the century. But when
the dust settled each time, it still stood _ until Monday, when
five of the 19 silos fell. On Tuesday, five more silos came down
after still more blasting.
   Now, blasters are confident that days are numbered for the rest
of the building, too.
   ``It's going like clockwork now,'' said Teri O'Donoghue, a
spokeswoman for the land developer that owns the property.
   ``We were hoping it would fall today but we weren't positive,''
Jerry Vann, who is heading the demolition project, said Monday.
Vann is president of Blasting Specialists Inc., a Chicago-based
company.
   As the first silos collapsed, nearby buildings shook and clouds
of white dust puffed over the remaining concrete towers.
   ``This is a beautiful sight,'' said Vann.
   He had planned to spend only 10 days on the job. Instead, Vann
has spent 30 days drilling and placing dynamite in the silos and
nine days blasting at the elevator's base.
   He said he expects to topple the remaining columns by this
weekend ``unless we get thunderstorms or bad weather.''
   The McCurdy Peanut Elevator is built of concrete up to two feet
thick, reinforced with heavy steel rods, to withstand the force of
a grain dust explosion, officials said. The peanut company bought
the elevator from a grain company.
   Vann said he could have destroyed the silos sooner but city
safety officials limited the amount of dynamite he could detonate
at any one time.
   ``We are working at this slow and steady so we don't endanger
anything around here,'' he said. ``I would rather shoot four or
five times, just to make sure no one gets hurt.''
   A land developer intends to transform the grain elevator's
28-acre site into a hotel and office development.
</TEXT>
