<HEAD>Murder Convict Resigns as Honorary Student President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of murdering a police officer
resigned Tuesday as honorary president of the student union at the
London School of Economics because of the uproar over his election.
   Winston Silcott, who is serving a 30-year minimum prison
sentence for the killing, said in a statement released by his
attorney that he was giving up the honor to spare his student
supporters grief.
   He thanked them but added, ``I have no wish for them to be made
scapegoats as I have been.''
   Administrators at the famous college, members of the governing
Conservative Party, and government officials had attacked the
students' election of Silcott. Education Secretary Kenneth Baker
described it as a ``shameful and despicable'' action of the ``loony
left.''
   However, school officials said they did not have the authority
to reverse it.
   The campus chapter of the National Union of Students accepted
Silcott's resignation.
   Indraprasad Patel, college director, said there would be a
review of the relationship between the college and the student
union to ensure such a thing never happens again. He said the
college had been ``gravely embarrassed'' by a small minority of
students who gathered April 27 to pick Silcott for the one-year
ceremonial term.
   The students voted for him to express sympathy for his claims
that he is innocent.
   The 29-year-old black and two other people were convicted of
murdering a white police officer with machetes during a riot at a
predominantly black housing project in north London in 1985.
Silcott was out on bail for another murder at the time.
