<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 4thLd-Writethru a0767 05-09 0941</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0767,0972</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Denounces Observers; Opposition Suggests Talks With Military</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead, SUB grafs 14-16, `Venezuelan government...' with
5 grafs UPDATING with Duque criticism, CLARIFYING Ritter remarks time element.
Picks up 17th graf, `The government...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government under Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega denounced international observers who said he stole
the presidential election, and it declared Tuesday that its own
candidate was ahead by almost two to one.
   In Washington, President Bush demanded that Noriega ``heed the
call of the people'' and abandon power. Bush said reports by U.S.
observers ``demonstrate clearly that despite massive irregularities
at the polls the opposition has won a clear-cut, overwhelming
victory'' in Sunday's election.
   The opposition claims a 3-1 victory. It said it was paying no
attention to official results and offered to negotiate.
   ``We are ready to enter a dialogue between civilians and the
military to find a solution to the nation's crisis,'' Ricardo Arias
Calderon, the opposition candidate for first vice president, told a
news conference Monday.
   Government foes staged no further demonstrations, and truckloads
of troops coursed through the streets.
   Police broke up a brief confrontation between pro- and
anti-government supporters at the home of Archbishop Marcos
McGrath, the country's Roman Catholic leader, who was meeting with
the opposition leadership.
   Walls, telephone poles and palm trees still bore campaign
posters, but stores that were boarded up in anticipation of
violence were reopening.
   The government said Noriega's candidate, Carlos Duque, was
leading opposition candidate Guillermo Endara by 51,752 to 26,878
with 12 of 40 districts reported.
   The opposition released figures from its own pollwatchers saying
it was leading by 236,097 to 79,260 with 35.8 percent of the vote
counted.
   Retiree Carlos Halphen summed up an opinion expressed by many
when asked what would happen next.
   ``We want the United States to do something. The U.S. got us
into this mess, it should get us out,'' he said.
   U.S. observers discussed with Bush in Washington options for
putting more pressure on Noriega to step down.
   The United States has imposed damaging economic sanctions on the
government but has been unable to oust Noriega as commander of the
15,000-strong Defense Forces and as de facto ruler.
   ``This election was a terrible fraud on the Panamanian people,''
said Rep. Larry Smith, R-Fla., a member of an uninvited observer
delegation sent by Bush. ``Polls opened late, peoples' names were
not on lists, dead peoples' names were on lists after years of not
appearing on lists.''
   Duque denounced ``obvious American intervention in affairs that
concern only Panama'' and said claims of stolen tallies were ``the
stuff of a soap opera plot.''
   Venezuelan government spokesman Pastor Heydra said in Caracas
that Latin American foreign ministers will meet in Lima, Peru _
possibly on Wednesday _ to consider ousting Panama from the
regional Group of Eight organization because of the electoral fraud
allegations. The organization suspended Panama after Noriega
engineered Eric Delvalle's ouster as Panamanian president in
February 1988.
   Venezuela, Colombia, Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, Peru, and
Mexico belong to the Group of Eight, which promotes political and
economic integration in Latin America.
   Panama's foreign minister, Jorge Ritter, accused Washington late
Monday of ``creating a climate for military intervention.'' His
comments were broadcast on news reports Tuesday.
   The government frequently has accused the United States of
plotting with the opposition to abrogate treaties under which
Panama would gain control of the Panama Canal at the end of the
century.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, who signed the treaties, said
Monday that Noriega's soldiers seized legitimate election returns
and that the results being tallied were counterfeit.
   He said he believed an exit poll conducted by the Catholic
church, which had the opposition leading 3-1, was an accurate
reflection of the true count.
   Carter left Panama on Tuesday morning after denouncing Noriega
as a dictator who was stealing the election from the Panamanian
people.
   Election Tribunal spokesman Boris Moreno said tabulation board
president Diomedes Rosas had told Carter he was an invited guest
and could not pass judgment, give advice or issue conclusions.
Carter stalked out, Moreno said.
   ``Noriega thought he was going to legitimize his regime.
Instead, it has been delegitimized,'' said a U.S. Embassy official.
   Noriega himself kept silent on the results and met with
government officials and acting President Manuel Solis Palma, who
is to step down Sept. 1.
   The vote counting center was surrounded Tuesday by a large
detachment of troops and truck-mounted machine guns.
   Moreno said troops were brought in because the government feared
rioting when more official results are announced.
   On Monday, a protest march by more than 15,000 people was broken
up with gunfire and three people were wounded, one seriously.
   Tuesday afternoon, Arias Calderon, Endara and second vice
presidential candidate Guillermo Ford visited McGrath.
   A few dozen armed paramilitary Noriega supporters surrounded the
house and dozens of Endara supporters gathered, but police
scattered the crowd by firing shots in the air.
   Endara said the candidates told McGrath of their desire for a
peaceful solution.
   Ritter said the international press was painting a distorted
picture of Panama and complained about U.S. Southern Command
television station broadcasts.
   The Southern Command station, the only uncensored station left
in Panama, was watched eagerly by many Panamanians, although it
broadcasts only in English.
   U.S.-Panama relations have been hostile since Noriega
orchestrated Delvalle's ouster last year. The CIA reportedly
contributed $10 million to the opposition campaign.
   Delvalle tried to fire the general after he was indicted in
Florida on drug-smuggling and money-laundering charges. Noriega
claims the U.S. charges are a smokescreen to keep the canal.
</TEXT>
