<FIRST>u p AM-JerseyCityMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0699 05-09 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jersey City Mayoral, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bitterly Fought Mayoral Races In Jersey City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with unofficial final results;
INSERTS one graf after 4th graf, `Jersey City, ...' to UPDATE with percentage
of registered voters who cast ballots; picks up 5th graf, `The candidates
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Gerald McCann and City
Council President Glenn Cunningham survived a mayoral free-for-all
with a record 10 candidates Tuesday, and will meet in a runoff.
   Incumbent Mayor Anthony Cucci lost a bid for a second, four-year
term, after placing fourth in the non-partisan race.
   With all of the votes counted, unofficial returns showed McCann
with 13,196 votes and Cunningham with 9,292 votes.
   ``I don't think there's even a comparison between us. I think
I'm by far the best candidate,'' McCann said after winning his spot
in the runoff June 13.
   ``Today was a rejection of old style politics. Councilman
Cunningham and I ran a clean, positive campaign,'' he said. ``The
people of Jersey City said that that's the style of politics they
want in the future.''
   Cunningham would become the city's first black mayor.
   The other candidates and their vote totals were: former Mayor
Thomas F.X. Smith, 6,482; Cucci, 6,342; Councilman Thomas
Fricchione, 6,260; banker Peter Murphy, 4,138; Councilman Thomas
Hart, 2,180; attorney Michael Bell, 1,324; police officer Richard
Boggiano, 1,077; and former City Council President Bobby Jackson,
826.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jersey City, across the Hudson River from New York City's lower
Manhattan, has about 95,000 registered voters, a decline of about
10 percent since the last mayoral election.
   Only 52 percent of the registered voters cast ballots, officials
said.
   The candidates battered each other with scurrilous attacks
during the long campaign in the state's second-largest city, where
politics has a reputation for decisions made in smoke-filled
backrooms.
   Some candidates resorted to putting fangs on unflattering
cartoons and caricatures of their opponents in some advertisements,
fairly typical of election day here.
   Smith served as mayor from 1977 until 1981, and McCann was mayor
from 1981 to 1985.
   All together, there were 102 candidates for the mayor's post and
nine council seats.
</TEXT>
