<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Sitcoms Adv11   05-09 1055</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Sitcoms, Adv 11,1085</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, May 11 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Researcher Became Couch Potato For Sitcom Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has seen them all _ television
situation comedies, that is _ says there was nobody like Lucy.
   Comedian Lucille Ball, who died April 26 of a ruptured aorta at
the age of 77, became a legend because of TV's ``I Love Lucy,''
which defined the sitcom genre when it first aired in 1951, and was
the model for a host of shows that followed.
   ```I Love Lucy' was so successful _ three years as the No. 1
show _ that virtually every (sitcom) that came after it was an
`actcom' until 1957,'' said Richard Taflinger, a professor of
communications at Washington State University.
   He said 90 percent of sitcoms are action comedies or
``actcoms.'' They start with a disruption of the status quo and
then follow the central character's actions as he or she tries to
restore things to normal. The character invariably causes further,
more humorous disruptions.
   Characters in actcoms are one-dimensional, unchanging and
unthinking. But the special ones such as Lucy Ricardo are
hilariously entertaining, Taflinger said.
   ``The penultimate actcom is, of course, `I Love Lucy,''' he said.
   The redheaded actress and her first husband, the late Desi
Arnaz, not only set the standard for comedy, Taflinger said, they
revolutionized television production by using three cameras in
their California studio to film the show in sequence before a live
audience.
   ``They totally changed television forever,'' he said.
   Sitcom episodes fill a sizable chunk of Taflinger's memory
banks, since he spent two years watching them seven hours a day.
Few couch potatoes could match such viewing habits, but Taflinger
was doing research for his book, ``Sitcom: What It Is and How It
Works.''
   ``I've watched at least one episode of every sitcom that's been
on the air since 1950, about 500 or so,'' he said.
   Taflinger has watched all 140 ``I Love Lucy'' episodes, all 160
of ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' and all 200 of ``M-A-S-H.'' He's also
analyzed obscure, short-lived programs that few television viewers
ever saw, such as ``Shirley's World,'' which starred Shirley
MacLaine for all of three episodes.
   But Taflinger said the series that had the briefest run was a
Tim Conway vehicle called ``Time Out.'' Cloned from the popular
``Laugh-In,'' ``Time Out'' drew such a flood of complaints during
its first 10 minutes on the air that the plug was pulled on the
program halfway through its hour-long premiere.
   Sitcoms, like jokes, must meet specific criteria to be funny,
Taflinger explained. The formula says effective humor must:
   _ Appeal to the intellect rather than the emotions.
   _ Be inherently human.
   _ Have its basis in a familiar set of societal norms.
   _ Involve actions or dialogue inconsistent with those norms or
unsuitable to the surroundings.
   _ Be perceived as harmless or painless to the participants.
   The second type of sitcom was the domestic comedy, which
Taflinger said began exploring character development, with children
becoming central to the plots. ``Father Knows Best'' was the first
in 1957, and later successes included ``My Three Sons,'' ``The
Brady Bunch,'' ``The Courtship of Eddie's Father,'' ``Family
Affair'' and ``Family Ties.''
   The top-rated show of recent seasons has been ``The Cosby
Show,'' but Taflinger said it isn't really a domestic comedy
anymore.
   ``I'm not entirely sure what it is,'' he said. ``It's great fun
to watch Bill Cosby do stand-up comedy, but nothing happens; they
have no problems.
   ``They simply live, which is why it's starting to slip in the
ratings, I think.''
   A number of sitcoms in between ``I Love Lucy'' and ``Cosby''
that were built around other established stars have not enjoyed the
huge popularity of those two series. Taflinger said the flops _
including Shirley MacLaine's show, ``The Jimmy Stewart Show'' and
``The Smith Family'' starring Henry Fonda _ lacked good scripts and
other necessary elements for a successful sitcom.
   The same principle applied to recent ill-fated attempts at
resurrecting TV veterans Dick Van Dyke and Mary Tyler Moore, whose
long-running original series concluded with final episodes.
   The very popular ``Mork and Mindy,'' a spinoff of ``Happy
Days,'' faded quickly after it began relying too much on Robin
Williams' antics to carry the show, Taflinger said.
   Not even Lucille Ball, whose return to series television in 1962
with ``The Lucy Show'' (later changed to ``Here's Lucy'') lasted 13
years, was immune from a flop. Her 1986 ``Life With Lucy'' sitcom
drew low ratings and was canceled within two months.
   Her last sitcom ``really wasn't a very good show; it depended
more on the fact that it was Lucy than on good writing and
producing a good, quality show,'' Taflinger said. He also noted
that at 75, she was unable to do the physical, slapstick comedy
with which Lucy Ricardo delighted audiences in the '50s.
   ``Plus, in today's network market a show must succeed almost
instantly or it's canceled,'' he said, noting that the original Van
Dyke show was nearly canceled after a few episodes but built an
audience by the end of its first 13-week season.
   The rarest variety of sitcom is the dramatic comedy, which must
have well-rounded characters who are humorous but also think, cry,
lose and sometimes die, Taflinger said. There have only been a
handful of ``dramedies'' _ ``All in the Family,'' ``M.A.S.H.,''
``Barney Miller,'' ``Maude'' _ but all enjoyed successful runs and
also ended with a final episode rather than cancellation.
   Taflinger expects the only drama-comedy (``dramedy'') currently
airing, ``Night Court,'' to last until its producers decide to end
it with a final episode.
   Taflinger's sitcom research began in 1972, and his two years of
seven-hours-a-day viewing spanned 1978-80, when he was writing his
dissertation at Washington State. He continued his research and
expanded it into his sitcom manuscript. He has about 3,000 sitcom
soundtracks recorded on cassette tapes. He listens to them while
driving, watching reruns of favorite episodes in his mind's eye.
   He remains an avid television viewer, and said ``Cheers,''
``Night Court'' and ``The Wonder Years'' are shows that can still
evoke laughs from him, but he doesn't see any of the current crop
of sitcoms with any staying power.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, May 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv12   05-09 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 12 ,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, May 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Catholic Church Tackles Cohabitation, Interreligious Marriages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church is taking a harder line toward
cohabiting couples seeking traditional church weddings, but is
making it easier than ever before for Catholics to wed people of
other faiths.
   A new handbook on marriage preparationdrawn up by a committee of
U.S. bishops states priests are taking an increasingly
confrontational approach toward cohabiting couples who ``create an
occasion of scandal for others by weakening the sanctity of
marriage itself.''
   ``You have to face the issue. We can't ignore it,'' said Bishop
Phillip F. Straling of San Bernardino, Calif., chairman of an
ad-hoc committee that drafted the handbook titled ``Faithful to
Each Other Forever.'' ``Marriage is not just a convenience, but a
sacred gift.''
   While the document, published May 8, strives to take what its
authors call a ``countercultural'' approach toward sexual ethics,
the bishops take an ecumenical approach toward another social trend
_ interreligious marriages.
   The handbook establishes guidelines encouraging cooperative
relations with non-Catholic clergy involved with the wedding and
mandating religious freedom for both spouses, stating the wedding
should never be the cause of any conversion.
   Valerie Dillon, president of the National Association of
Catholic Diocesan Family Life Ministers and a consultant to the
report, said interreligious marriages ``are really serving as
models of ecumenical growth, and they are the wave of the future.''
   The 400-page handbook was drawn up by the Bishops' Committee for
Pastoral Research and Practices in response to a 1983 Vatican
directive for national episcopal conferences to issue norms for
priests and others involved in marriage preparation in the 53
million-member denomination.
   The handbook also was approved by the Administrative Committee
of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   The Denver City Council last week abolished a ``living-in-sin''
law as outmoded, but with the number of Americans living together
before marriage tripling to 2 million in the period from 1970-84,
priests have been losing their inhibitions about confronting
cohabiting Catholics with traditional church teaching, Monsignor
Joseph M. Champlin, the chief author of the marriage handbook, said
in an interview.
   ``Twenty to 25 years ago, priests generally tended to overlook
the fact they were living together,'' Champlin said. ``It's like
parents; sometimes it's better not to know what the kids are
doing.''
   The new handbook states that while priests remain concerned
about alienating Catholics seeking the sacrament of marriage,
church leaders and clergy have increasingly adopted a more
challenging, confrontational approach to cohabiting couples.
   ``The negative statistics and harmful effects of cohabitation
... certainly contributed to that new development, as well as the
question of scandal to others and the potential injury to the
sanctity of marriage.''
   Since 1984, the dioceses of St. Cloud, Minn., and Cleveland have
established policies encouraging cohabiting couples to separate and
generally allowing only small, nuptial masses for couples who
refuse to live apart.
   Champlin said such dioceses have decided that ``to have a big
ceremony with a great dramatization is like making a mockery of
marriage itself.''
   While the handbook emphasizes traditional church teaching
forbidding premarital sex, the decision for handling individual
couples is left to priests.
   ``We don't condone what they have been doing, but we try to
straighten things out,'' Straling said.
   Mrs. Dillon said the church needs to confront couples living
together ``not to be punitive,'' but to ensure they're marrying for
sacramental reasons as opposed to pressure from their families or
other reasons.
   ``The church says marriage for any reason other than a free
desire to commit to each other for life is not an acceptable reason
for marriage within the church,'' she said.
   In the area of interreligious marriages, the church has moved
from confrontation to conciliation in the last generation.
   ``There's just been a tremendous growth in the kind of
collaborative approach,'' said Monsignor Champlin, also the author
of ``Together for Life,'' a book of prayers for the wedding liturgy
that has been used by two-thirds of the couples married by Catholic
priests over the last 20 years.
   In his own family, he recalled, his mother was married to a
non-Catholic in a rectory and his brother was married outside of
the communion railing. Today, he said, Catholics are able to get
married with the church's blessing at a Protestant church even if a
priest is not present.
   With 40 percent of American Catholics entering into
interreligious marriages, the bishops state in the marriage
handbook that the trend is ``a reality to which we must respond in
as positive a way as possible.''
   The handbook encourages the Catholic and non-Catholic spouse to
become familiar with the teachings of each other's religion and
mandates that both spouses enjoy ``total freedom'' with regard to
their own beliefs.
   ``An interreligious marriage may be the occasion, but must never
be the cause of any conversion,'' the handbook said.
   While same-faith marriages have some advantages, Straling said
the bishops wanted to stress in the document: ``Interreligious
marriages can work and do work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
