<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv12   05-09 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 12,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, May 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The moderate candidate for the Southern
Baptist Convention presidency, the Rev. Daniel Vestal of Atlanta,
says he will try to dilute the power of the office if he is elected.
   Fundamentalists have won the presidency over the last 10 years
and used the presidential appointive power to name trustees
controlling the denomination's agencies.
   ``For the last 10 years it has been winner take all,'' Vestal
told a meeting of moderates, saying he hopes to change that pattern
to ``winner shares all.''
   He is to oppose the fundamentalist-backed incumbent president,
the Rev. Jerry Vines of Jacksonville, Fla., when the Southern
Baptists meet in Las Vegas June 13-15.
   Moderates say they have been excluded from key appointments _
particularly to a powerful committee which names trustees governing
denominational agencies _in the decade in which the denomination
has come under fundamentalist control.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reform synagogues last weekend marked the 100th
anniversary of the organization of Reform rabbis in this country _
the Central Conference of American Rabbis.
   Founded in 1889 under leadership of Rabbi Isaac Mayer Wise, it
now includes 1,500 rabbis serving about 800 congregations in the
United States with a membership totalling 1.5 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Historic theological agreements reached
among different churches in recent years will come to naught if
churches don't go beyond talk to action in reuniting Christianity,
a major ecumenical conference was told.
   The Rev. Michael Kinnamon, dean of Lexington (Ky.) Theological
Seminary said the new accords must be followed up with ``decisive,
imaginative leadership if we are to break through from one stage of
the ecumenical movement to the next.''
   Failure to do so will lead to cynicism, frustration and
abandonment of the cause, he told a gathering about 500 Roman
Catholic, Protestant, Episcopal and Eastern Orthodox
representatives.
   ``We have a library of acknowledged `common convictions,' but .
.. we have not sufficiently acknowledged the pressure they should
exert on us for living and acting together.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two independent, evangelical organizations in
the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) have banded together into a new
broad-based organization called ``Presbyterians for Renewal.''
   A conference here of nearly 1,000 Presbyterian evangelicals
formed the new group from the former Presbyterians for Biblical
Concerns and Covenant Fellowship of Presbyterians.
   They also issued a call for ``promoting biblical, theological
and spiritual renewal,'' focusing on ``making disciples among all
peoples'' and ``working for righteousness.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHEVY CHASE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders from South Korea and
communist North Korea worshipped, discussed and sang together in a
rare gathering here contemplating reunion of their divided country.
   In the first visit to the United States since Korea was divided
in 1945 at the end of World War II, four North Korean Christains
met with South Korean church representatives, along with about 100
U.S. church leaders.
   The Rev. Dwain Epps, international affairs officer of the
National Council of Churches which sponsored the conference, said:
   ``We don't have the power in our hands to make peace or reunify
Korea. But we have the opportunity to respond to the call of the
Christians of the South and North to assist them to find a
reunified future.''
   The council launched an ecumenical campaign to educate U.S.
church members about continuing human costs of a divided Korea,
including separation of families and a devastating war in which 4
million died.
</TEXT>
