<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv11   05-09 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 11,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, May 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pesticide May Stop Formosan `Super' Termite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new slow-acting pesticide
approved for indoor use against cockroaches and ants also may stop
the Formasan ``super'' termite that is spreading throughout the
South, a researcher says.
   ``The Formosan termite is so aggressive that it's pushing out
our native subterranean termites,'' said entomologist Nan-Yao Su,
with the University of Florida Institute of Food and Agricultural
Sciences. ``If we don't stop this pest, it's possible the Formosan
termite could eventually replace our native species in the southern
part of the United States.''
   The pest has been found in Florida, Alabama, Louisiana,
Mississippi, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas. One colony may
contain 7 million termites and weigh 60 pounds, Su said. ``You
could say one of these termite colonies is like a 60-pound animal
eating about three pounds of wood every day.
   ``When you consider how aggressively this pest searches for
wood, cardboard and paper, it's easy to see why it's so
destructive.''
   With the beginning of swarming season, as many as 68,000 winged
termites may emerge from one nest at night in search of places
where they can mate and begin new colonies. Flights range as far as
1,500 feet from the nest.
   Worse yet, Su said, the pests are attracted by lights _
especially fluorescent lights. Warm, moist cracks or crevices in
buildings are ideal entry points, and the Formosan termite can
infest buildings from the top floor downward without the ground
connection needed by domestic termites.
   The key to controlling the pest is to destroy the underground
colonies, he said. Large quantities of pesticide beneath buildings
may keep the pest out, but won't destroy nests that could be as far
as 600 feet away.
   Termites are very sensitive to chemicals and seal off their
colonies to avoid them. The new chemical, sulfluramid, is effective
at concentrations so low termites don't detect it, Su said. A few
grams of the compound produced by Griffin Corp. of Valdosta, Ga.,
should be enough to destroy an entire colony.
   Field tests are set for this summer, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Experimental Grass Gets By With Little Irrigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FX 33 may sound like a new jet fighter,
but its use is strictly on the ground. It's a type of grass that
needs so little water that a plot last sprinkled in January is
still lush and green.
   ``It offers a significant advantage in drought resistance,''
said Phil Busey, a University of Florida researcher, ``but we're
still not sure how it will do with very cold weather, shade and
some types of disease.''
   FX 33 looks much like Floratam, developed by the university 14
years ago, Busey said. ``We've had both of them in Fort Lauderdale
test plots for 14 months now without irrigation, and the Floratam
has all but died out.''
   It's not that FX 33 doesn't need water _ it's the ability to use
water efficiently that counts. FX 33 has roots extending up to five
feet into the soil, enough to tap into the shallow aquifer beneath
much of central Florida.
   Spring droughts have forced bans on water usage during most of
the daylight hours in central and southern Florida.
   However, Busey suspects FX 33 has no tolerance for temperatures
much below 20 degrees, and might be susceptible to a disease called
gray leaf spot. It's also still unclear how the grass does in
prolonged shade.
   Homeowners need not line up at the garden store just yet, since
more tests will preclude commercial production until perhaps the
summer of 1991.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 11</NOTE>
