<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ogilvy Bjt   05-09 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ogilvy, Bjt,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>WPP Raises Offer For Ogilvy; Stock Price Goes Above Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover speculators are betting that WPP Group
PLC's new $50-a-share purchase offer for Ogilvy Group Inc. will not
be enough to capture the American advertising company.
   The WPP offer puts a value of roughly $750 million on Ogilvy,
the world's fifth-largest advertising concern based on 1988
billings. WPP, owner of the U.S. agency J. Walter Thompson, ranks
third.
   Together the companies would roughly tie Britain's Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi for honors as the world's biggest advertising group.
   WPP said Monday it was stepping up from its initial offer of $45
a share ``in order to avoid unnecessary and potentially unsettling
delay in the negotiation of a friendly transaction.''
   Arbitragers bid Ogilvy's stock up $2.12{ a share in
over-the-counter trading on Monday to $52 a share, higher than the
offer made public by Britain's WPP.
   The speculators apparently believed WPP would raise its offer
again or that a debt-financed group, possibly led by management,
would buy the company from shareholders at more than $50 a share,
analysts said.
   It is less likely that another advertising company will emerge
as a bidder, because the price already is more than 50 percent
above what the market considered Ogilvy worth before the bidding
began, said James D. Dougherty, an analyst at County NatWest USA.
   Ogilvy traded as low as $24 a share late last year. It rose to
the low $30s, partly on takeover speculation, before the initial
WPP offer, which was confirmed May 1.
   ``I frankly have a lot of problem finding economic sense at this
price. At $45, maybe,'' Dougherty said.
   Ogilvy says it can serve its clients better by remaining
independent.
   A spokeswoman, Joelle Frank, said Monday Ogilvy had received
many other expressions of interest but would not say if it had
negotiated with anyone.
   She also declined to confirm a report in The Sunday Times of
London that two American investment firms, Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&amp; Co. and Wesray Capital Corp., had approached Ogilvy with offers
higher than WPP's initial bid.
   A spokesman for Kohlberg declined to comment on the report,
while a spokesman for Wesray did not immediately return a phone
call.
   Although WPP wants a friendly deal, the London-based company has
not ruled out taking its offer directly to Ogilvy shareholders with
a hostile tender offer or proxy fight.
   A hostile takeover would not necessarily cripple Ogilvy by
prompting mass defections, as has happened in certain other
takeovers, Dougherty said.
   ``My suspicion is that there would be a few defections at the
very top, but the worker bees who actually would get the work out
for the clients would stay,'' he said.
   In addition to J. Walter Thompson, WPP owns the Hill &amp; Knowlton
public relations agency. Other Ogilvy's properties include Ogilvy &amp;
Mather Worldwide advertising and Scali, McCable, Sloves advertising.
   Based on Ogilvy's 14.7 million shares outstanding, a $50-a-share
buyout would total $735 million. Another 1.3 million shares could
be issued through the exercise of stock options, but those would
cost less than $50 apiece for an acquirer because the owner would
have to put up the exercise price.
   Ogilvy also has about $40 million in long-term debt that a buyer
would have to assume.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe Bjt   05-09 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Traders Under Scrutiny Were Fined in 1985</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two central figures in criminal and civil
investigations of New York's commodity markets paid $135,000 in
1985 to settle charges of collaborating in illegal trades,
officials said.
   Meanwhile, federal officials declined to comment Monday on
published reports that criminal subpoenas had been issued to
traders in connection with a raid last week on the markets.
   The investigations are said to focus on Preston H. Semel, who
runs a brokerage trading in gold, silver and other commodities, and
Mark B. Fisher, an independent trader who runs an oil futures trade
processing firm.
   Federal agents last Thursday executed criminal search warrants
at Fisher's exchange offices, while officials from the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission subpoenaed four exchanges and about 26
individual traders for information.
   The investigations reportedly focus on allegations of a variety
of trading practices violations, including pre-arranged trades,
using advanced knowledge of customer trades to trade for personal
accounts and conducting trades in order to skirt tax obligations.
   Fisher and Semel were linked in a 1985 settlement of charges
brought by the Commodity Exchange, or Comex, of alleged trading
abuses committed in 1983, Comex spokesman Robert McGrath said.
   The two were charged with scheming along with a third trader to
conduct pre-arranged trading and improper dual trading, in which
trades are made for both customer and personal accounts.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Fisher paid the exchange a
$60,000 fine, Semel paid $75,000 and was suspended two months, and
Sergio Cardello, a partner of Semel's, paid $125,000 and lost his
Comex membership seat, according to exchange records.
   A market source said Monday that Semel, 39, currently is the
subject of an internal Comex investigation for irregular trading
that involves other individuals.
   Semel in 1985 also paid a $5,000 civil penalty to settle charges
of conducting so-called ``wash sales'' in which contracts are
bought in identical amounts to create bogus losses for tax purposes
or to affect the price of a commodity, a CFTC spokeswoman said.
   That violation was included in charges against several other
firms and traders and involved gold and silver futures on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   A person answering the phone at Semel &amp; Co. said neither Semel
nor his attorney would be available for comment.
   An attorney for Fisher said the trader had not received a
criminal subpoena or been notified by the government that he is a
target. U.S. Postal Service inspectors executing criminal search
warrants seized documents from Fisher's World Trade Center offices
Thursday.
   Fisher has received a civil subpoena as part of the CFTC probe,
sources said.
   A subpoena is a formal request for information. It does not
carry any charge or imply guilt.
   Fisher and two other traders who have been subpoenaed in the
civil case attended the University of Pennsylvania in the early
1980s and were known to be personally acquainted.
   Mark B. Dickstein, a 1980 Penn graduate who has his own trading
firm, issued a statement Monday that he had received a CFTC
subpoena seeking documents dealing with two months of transactions
but was not under investigation, ``and neither I nor my counsel
believe that I am a target of any CFTC investigation.''
   A spokesman for Dickstein said the trader had not received a
criminal subpoena.
   Craig W. Effron, a 1981 Penn graduate and gold trader who also
has received a civil subpoena, declined to comment Monday.
   Dickstein and Effron both have been disciplined by Comex in the
past. Dickstein paid $40,000 to settle charges of a variety of
trading abuses in November 1986; Effron paid $7,000 in September
1986 and $9,000 in August 1988 to settle trading misconduct charges.
   In addition to Comex, subpoenaed exchanges were the New York
Mercantile Exchange; the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange; and the
Cotton Exchange.
   A separate Justice Department investigation of Chicago's
commodities markets, the nation's largest, came to light in January
but is not connected to the New York probe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
