<SECOND>BC-Consolidated Gold,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulatory Panel Grants Limited Extension to Minorco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it would grant South
African-controlled Minorco SA a limited extension in its hostile
$5.8 billion bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   The Panel on Takeovers and Mergers also ordered Gold Fields to
discontinue its court proceedings against Minorco unless its
shareholders approve such actions at a May 30 meeting.
   The acquisition of the British gold mining group would be
Britain's largest takeover ever.
   The takeover panel said it favored extending the timetable for
the bid because of ongoing litigation in the United States.
   Under the panel's ruling, the $25.30-a-share offer is to expire
June 7. It would have technically expired April 26.
   Minorco, which already held a 29.9 percent stake in Gold Fields,
announced April 26 that enough shareholders had accepted its offer
to give it a stake of nearly 55 percent in Gold Fields. But U.S.
litigation arising from antitrust claims has prevented Minorco from
actually taking its stake in Gold Fields above 30 percent.
   U.S.-based Newmont Mining Corp. is 49 percent owned by Gold
Fields and is a party to the litigation against Minorco.
   Graham Williams, a spokesman for Gold Fields, said the company
had no immediate comment on the panel's ruling Tuesday.
   Luxembourg-based Minorco is 60 percent controlled by Anglo
American Corp. and De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., the gold and
diamond mining interests of the South African Oppenheimer family.
   Minorco's bid was unveiled in September and twice sweetened. It
currently includes half a Minorco share and $19.62 in cash for each
Gold Fields share.
</TEXT>
