<FIRST>r f PM-Fruehauf-Varity     05-09 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fruehauf-Varity,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Varity Agrees to Buy Fruehauf's Last Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Varity Corp., which has tried to buy Fruehauf
Corp. three times since last fall, finally succeeded with an offer
worth an estimated $650 million in cash, stock and notes.
   Fruehauf and Toronto-based Varity said Monday they signed an
agreement under which Varity will pay $66 million in cash and $430
million in notes and issue new stock for the Kelsey-Hayes
automotive products division of Fruehauf.
   Kelsey-Hayes supplies wheels and anti-lock brakes and is the
last of Fruehauf's 75-year-old corporate empire. Fruehauf put
itself up for sale last autumn and has since sold off its
tractor-trailer and marine operations.
   Varity, formerly Massey-Ferguson, has pursued the profitable
Kelsey-Hayes unit for the last eight months. If the sale goes
through, Fruehauf said it would liquidate its assets, although the
nameplate will continue to appear on its trailers.
   Under terms of the deal, each share of Fruehauf common stock
would be converted into one share of newly issued Varity stock. At
Monday's prices, the new stock would be worth about $145 million.
   The 6,700 Kelsey-Hayes workers worldwide would not be affected
immediately, Varity spokesman Jack Nowling said. He said Varity
will delay any moves until the sale is completed in four or five
months, pending approval of Fruehauf shareholders and bondholders.
   Wilbur Ross, a spokesman for the creditors, said even though
creditors will be paid only 89 cents for each dollar, the deal is
good because Fruehauf's shaky status had meant the debt was worth
only 70 cents per dollar on the open market.
   Financial problems at Fruehauf, builder of half of all trailers
on the highways in the 1950s, date to the 1970s, when deregulation
forced truckers to slash their rates.
   The company's financial difficulties were compounded in 1986
when its managers borrowed $1.5 billion to buy the company and fend
off a takeover. Despite cost-cutting measures, it never recovered
from the debt burden and began putting divisions up for sale.
   In March, Fruehauf sold its unprofitable truck division for $232
million to Terex Corp., based in Green Bay, Wis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
