<FIRST>r f BC-MCorpBids     05-09 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-MCorp Bids,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Regional Holding Companies Consider Bank Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two regional banking companies have
joined a list of firms that are considering submitting bids to buy
the 20 former MCorp banks now controlled by federal regulators, a
newspaper reported.
   Sources quoted by the Fort Worth Star-Telegram in Tuesday
editions said Barnett Banks Inc. and Banc One Corp. are working
independently on possible bids and are examining the MCorp banks'
financial records.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. seized 20 of the 25 banks
owned by MCorp in March, one of the biggest federal takeovers of a
troubled banking company. The action came after three MCorp
bondholders sought to have MCorp's assets sold in an involuntary
bankruptcy liquidation to pay off debts.
   The 20 banks, operated under the umbrella of Deposit Insurance
Bridge Bank, were put up for sale recently by the regulators.
   Barnett Banks, based in Jacksonville, Fla., had total assets of
$25.7 billion on Dec. 31 and reported net income of $226 million in
1988, a 20-percent rise from its 1987 performance.
   Barnett has 546 banking offices in Florida and Georgia.
Columbus, Ohio-based Banc One, with total year-end assets of $25.3
billion, reported net income of $340 million last year and has 566
banking offices in Ohio, Kentucky, Michigan, Indiana and Wisconsin.
   Officials of Deposit Insurance Bridge Bank confirmed Monday that
as many as three prospective bidders were reviewing its books and
records and meeting with selected bank executives.
   ``The bank has arranged separate areas to accommodate
simultaneous due diligence reviews by up to three prospective
bidders,'' the bridge bank said in a statement.
   But the institution would not say whether Barnett and Banc One
were among firms conducting the on-site examination.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., a New York investment firm that
specializes in buying other companies with borrowed money, began
its second on-site audit last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
