<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting improved growing conditions in some major U.S.
crop-producing areas.
   The soybean market opened higher amid indications of Soviet
buying on the cash market but prices quickly turned lower in
reaction to overnight showers in the Midwest.
   The improved soil moisture in eastern Iowa and northwestern
Illinois also pressured corn prices.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued after
Monday's close called for normal precipitation early next week in
the Midwest and the Great Plains, which added to the bearish
sentiment in all the grain and soybean markets.
   Wheat traders are growing more cautious as they establish
positions ahead of the Agriculture Department's winter wheat crop
estimate on Thursday.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.32 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2 cents lower with May at $2.77} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 3
cents lower wiith May at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 2} cents to
6{ cents lower with May at $7.58 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .50 cent higher wiith June at 72.65
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .40 cent higher with
May at 77.05 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent to .18 cent
higher wiith June at 47.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.38 cent to 1 cent higher with May at 32.75 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Monday while pork futures
advanced.
