<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv11   05-09 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 11,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Thursday, May 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Does Anyone Know The Price Anymore?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Does anyone know the price anymore _ of an
automobile, a fast-food meal, an airplane ticket, a bag of lawn
fertilizer or a dozen other products that might come to mind?
   Pricing no longer is simple and straightforward. It is tricky,
confusing, surprising, exasperating and inexplicable, to mention a
few characteristics. Someone with imagination could make a list
that would gird the globe.
   Retailer discounts, manufacturer discounts, discount-option
packages, sales, rebates, below-cost financing, fees, specials,
exceptions and exemptions produce a challenge to which few buyers
are equal.
   The time of day on which you make your phone calls can mean full
price or a 65 percent discount, but that isn't the only thing that
complicates your phone bill. Do you own your phone or do you rent?
Do you own or rent the jacks?
   The day of the week on which you travel by air can mean paying
half-price or regular price. But the discount might be available
only if you fly through a certain city on the way to your
destination...if there is room on the flight.
   Do you know how interest is assessed on your credit card or
whether you pay an annual service fee? Do you know the rate _ or
how much it has changed in the past few months? Bluntly speaking,
do you know what your card costs?
   The difficulty in pricing was illustrated in recent weeks when
General Motors and Ford raised prices on options, but not the basic
prices of all cars. The effect is to further complicate attempts to
assess prices.
   GM, for example, increased by $10 each the prices of power
windows, power door locks and cruise control. It raised air
conditioning $20 and automatic transmissions $25. The result:
Higher car costs no matter what they say.
   Ford increased prices of power door locks, power windows, power
mirrors and cruise control by $8, but it retained discount-option
packages, in which option items have a lower total price when
purchased together rather than separately.
   Partly as a consequence of such complicated pricing, it becomes
nearly impossible to estimate the price of an automobile from the
prices advertised, which often are for bare-bones vehicles. Price
tags become come-ons.
   It happens in fast-food restaurants too. The big sign advertises
a juicy hamburger with lettuce and tomato for $1.99, but when the
bill comes it adds up to more than $4. The cheese costs 75 cents,
the side salad about the same. The small cola, tea or coffee costs
70 cents and sometimes more than $1.
   Over at the local lending institution, meanwhile, they're
pushing low-cost mortgages, but are points included? At the real
estate office they offer help in getting a mortgage, but do they
mention they might take a fee for doing so?
   So you buy the house and get to work on the lawn. At the garden
store they're having their spring sale, and that means fertilizer
rebates. Let's see: There's the regular price, the retailer
discount and the manufacturer's rebate, which you claim by mail
with proof of purchase and a sales ticket. Many forget to do so.
   You don't go overboard on landscaping because you know that real
estate taxes soon will be due. You thought you knew the exact tax
down to the penny _ until they reassessed the town. They raised
assessments 9.3 percent but lowered the mill rate 6.2 percent, so
that leaves you owing _ an indeterminate sum.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Thursday, May 11.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890509-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PanAm-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Mulling Offer for NWA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 12 grafs details, background, stock price of both airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. announced today it is considering
making an offer for NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines,
which is the target of several takeover suitors.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett made the surprise announcement
to shareholders at the financially troubled airline's annual
meeting in Washington.
   He said Pan Am's move is in response to NWA's general request
for such proposals. NWA already has received a $2.7 billion
takeover offer from investor Marvin Davis, and the airline's unions
have said they also are interested in possibly buying the carrier.
   A marriage of Pan Am and Northwest would create one of the most
far-reaching airlines, with routes worldwide, and further
consolidate the landscape of the deregulated U.S. airline industry.
   NWA didn't specifically approach Pan Am to make an offer, Pan Am
spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon said.
   Plaskett said Pan Am has retained Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. and Airlie Group LP as financial advisers but did not disclose
any possible details of a bid for NWA.
   Prudential-Bache is considering providing ``very significant''
new equity for Pan Am to acquire NWA and anticipates arranging the
remaining financing if Pan Am actually makes a bid, he said.
   Plaskett told airline analysts several months ago that Pan Am
probably would have difficulty ensuring its financial survival
without merging with another carrier.
   ``The linkage of two airlines with virtually no overlapping
routes into a single global carrier would create a formidable U.S.
challenger to the rapidly expanding foreign mega-carriers,''
Plaskett told the shareholders.
   ``The combination would be especially significant given the
heritage and reservoir of international experience which the
employees of the two carriers contribute.
   ``The recent developments at NWA have created a unique
opportunity to pursue an idea that makes good business sense and
one that will position Pan Am and Northwest to grow together into a
world leader in international aviation.
   ``Pan Am and its financial advisors believe that the business
economics of the combined entities could easily support a fully
financed cash offer at an attractive price. There are still a
number of complex issues to examine, including transitional labor
agreements and the specific terms of an offer, before we will
proceed with a bid.''
   Northwest's Pacific routes to the Orient and Europe would
dovetail with Pan Am's large international operations that are
strong in Atlantic routes and to Latin America.
   Trading in shares of both companies was halted shortly before
the announcement. After it resumed Pan Am rose 25 cents a share to
$5.00 on the New York Stock Exchange, and NWA rose 62{ cents a
share to $105.12{.
   Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest airline, generally is
considered one of the most profitable. Pan Am, on the other hand,
has been racked by losses for several years and has asked its
unions to take pay cuts.
   Pan Am, the eighth-largest, recently reported that its
first-quarter loss widened to $151.1 million from $83.3 million a
year earlier, due in part to a decline in business after the
bombing of its Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December.
   Pan Am reported $733.5 million in revenue for the first three
months of 1989, down from $763.9 million a year earlier.
   NWA, by contrast, reported its largest first-quarter profit of
the decade.
   First-quarter earnings were $12.6 million, or 43 cents a share,
compared with a net loss of $43.5 million in the first quarter of
1988.
   NWA's revenue in the quarter jumped 19.3 percent to $1.48
billion from $1.24 billion a year earlier.
   Kurt Rivard, an airline analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. in
Minneapolis, said a merger of the two carriers is plausible.
   ``They do make a very interesting fit,'' he said. ``There is not
much overlap in the domestic routes and while Northwest is strong
in the Pacific, Pan Am is fairly significant elsewhere in the world.
   ``An acquisition or a merger for Northwest from a company point
of view makes a lot of sense,'' he said. ``They're very
compatible.''
   Rivard said there may be some accounting benefits in Pan Am, the
smaller of the two, acquiring Northwest. He said there could be tax
losses at Pan Am that could be carried forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
