<FIRST>u f PM-AutoChangeovers 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Changeovers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monthlong Shutdowns at GM Scheduled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS June 13 to July 13 in graf 6, picks up 7th graf, She
called...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said today it planned to
shut down some of its assembly plants for a month or longer during
the summer to help reduce inventories and provide time for plant
retooling.
   There has been speculation that GM, Ford Motor Co. and Chyrsler
Corp. would have longer-than-normal changeover times because of
slow sales and ambitious production during the first three months
of the year.
   That combination boosted inventories and prompted automakers to
expand incentive programs as the second quarter of the year got
under way.
   Automakers typically shut down production in the late summer to
accommodate vacation periods and retool assembly lines for the
coming model year.
   The shutdown time varies, depending on the extent of the
changeover, but is usually at least two weeks.
   GM spokeswoman Marcia McGee said today the company's carmaking
plant in Flint would be closed between July 13 and Aug. 7, and
plants in Wentzville, Mo., and Orion Township in Oakland County
would be closed for about a month each during June and July.
   She called the shutdown time normal.
   ``We do a lot of retooling, line rearrangement,'' she said.
``Even though there is not a significant new product, there are a
lot of (manufacturing) changes for future product that is not
apparent.''
   She said production at the company's plant in Ypsilanti would be
shut down from May 19 until early next year for changes linked to a
new full-size, rear-wheel-drive model.
   Ward's Automotive Reports said GM planned to stop production at
assembly plants in Doraville, Ga.; Fairfax, Kan.; and Wilmington,
Del., and Hamtramck, Mich.; from a month to six weeks during the
summer.
   GM corporate spokesmen had no comment on general shutdown plans.
Calls to GM's major carmaking groups were referred to each of GM's
five carmaking divisions.
   There are no plans for extended shutdowns at Ford assembly
plants this summer, spokesman Joel Pitcoff said.
   However, he said there are discussions going on about whether to
tack one week on to the normal two-week summer vactation-retooling
period at plants in Chicago; Atlanta; St. Thomas, Ontario; and
Wixom, Mich., as the company installs driver-side air bags in
models that lacked them previously.
   Chrysler spokesman Doug Nicoll said plant closing schedules for
model changeover time have not been announced. Traditionally, he
said, the company staggers the closings in June, July and August.
   ``I'm not aware of any longer-than-normal times for
changeovers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
