   Declining issues barely edged out advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 694 issues down, 620 up and 583 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 100.31 million shares.
   Analysts said the market remained cautious in anticipation of
Friday's government report on producer prices, which will provide
additional information about the economy's growth.
   ``There's nothing going on. The main reason is this is a market
that is totally enthralled by the next economic report,'' said
Alfred E. Goldman, vice president of the investment firm A.G.
Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
   Analysts said last week's unemployment report provided mixed
signals and confused the market.
   Unemployment rose 0.3 percentage point to 5.3 percent in April,
indicating a slowdown in economic growth. But the market focused on
the part of the report showing hourly earnings rose seven cents,
suggesting inflation might still be a problem.
   Traders also said today's market could benefit if the three-part
Treasury borrowing produces favorable results. Bond prices were
weaker in early trading ahead of the sale. The government's $28.75
billion refunding auction starts today.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.06 to 171.20.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.28 to 345.57.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Pan Am was up | to 5
and NWA was down ] to 104] after Pan Am announced this morning that
it is considering making an offer for Northwest Airlines.
   Meanwhile, AT&amp;T was down [ to 34[, Upjohn had lost ] to 31{ and
Avon was off | to 36[.
