<HEAD>Wheat Futures Slip On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices fell moderately Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade on perceptions that growing conditions
are gradually improving.
   ``I think you saw some profit-taking and I think some people
looked at the weather forecast,'' said Katharina Zimmer,
grain-market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. in New
York.
   Soybean futures ended mostly higher on persistent rumors of
Soviet buying interest, while corn futures ended narrowly mixed.
   Monday's six-to-10-day forecast from the National Weather
Service predicted normal rainfall and normal temperatures early
next week in most major U.S. crop areas.
   Rain would bring little relief to winter-wheat farmers in
Kansas, because it's too late to revive the sizable portion of that
crop damaged by lack of moisture and extreme temperatures.
   But showers would improve the prospects for getting the spring
wheat crop off to a good start in the northern Plains, analysts
said.
   The contract for May delivery of wheat plunged 10 cents a
bushel, but analysts attributed the drop to factors surrounding the
contract's upcoming expiration rather than supply-and-demand
fundamentals.
   At the close, wheat settled 3{ cents to 10 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.26 a bushel; corn was 2 cents
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.77{ a bushel; oats were 2}
cents to 4 cents lower with May at $1.88{ a bushel; soybeans were \
cent lower to 5{ cents higher with May at $7.66 a bushel.
</TEXT>
