<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1616EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-09 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0300</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined in relatively low
volume today, pressured by jitters in the bond market and ongoing
inflation worries.
   The market opened on an up-note, then drifted lower as economic
uncertainty set in.
   Early in the day, many buyers withdrew from the market to await
the start of the Treasury's three-day auction of notes and bonds.
Investors also were reluctant to make commitments ahead of Friday's
wholesale price data, market observers said.
   The bond market took a nosedive late in the day after the first
round of the government auction. Stocks followed, with program
selling dominating the action.
   Analysts said that the bond market had anticipated a more
enthusiastic response from foreign investors to the Treasury's
$9.75 billion sale of three-year notes.
   ``Apparently the auction didn't go so well,'' said Michael Metz,
vice president of Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Before the sale observers had predicted that stock prices would
follow the bond market's reaction.
   Analysts said the stock market also remained cautious in
anticipation of Friday's government report on producer prices,
which will provide additional information about the economy's
growth.
   The producer price index has particular significance for the
market after last week's unemployment report, which provided mixed
signals, traders said.
   The report showed unemployment rose 0.3 percentage point to 5.3
percent in April, indicating a slowdown in economic growth. But the
market focused on the part of the report showing hourly earnings
rose seven cents, suggesting inflation might still be a problem.
   ``So the concern is shifting to stagflation,'' said Alfred E.
Goldman, vice president of the investment firm A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons
Inc. Stagflation refers to a condition of stagnant economic growth
coupled with inflation.
</TEXT>
