<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-09 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil future prices recovered some recent losses
Tuesday, although analysts said internal market influences were
largely responsible for the rebound.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, settled
32 cents higher at $19.76 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract had
declined 58 cents Monday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for June delivery rose 0.54 cent to
65.52 cents a gallon, after losing 2.52 cents Monday.
   June heating oil, which declined 2.12 cents the previous
session, settled at 46.99 cents a gallon, up 0.30 cent.
   William Byers, an energy analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.,
attributed Tuesday's price increase primarily to internal forces of
supply and demand in the market, in the absence of any fundamental
changes.
   ``There was a feeling that the market was oversold,'' Byers said.
   He said the market remained concerned about an oil glut among
OPEC producers.
   Monday's selloff was triggered by a report that showed members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries had boosted
their daily production last month to 20.9 million barrels.
   OPEC's self-imposed quota is 18.5 million barrels a day.
</TEXT>
