<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-LoebAwards     05-09 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Loeb Awards,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>UCLA Business Writing Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philadelphia Inquirer article on tax reform
led the list of winners of the Gerald Loeb Awards, presented by the
University of California, Los Angeles, for outstanding business and
financial journalism.
   The winners:
   _ For large newspapers, The Inquirer's Donald L. Barlett and
James B. Steele for ``The Great Tax Giveaway,'' on the revised
federal tax code.
   _ Medium-sized papers, S. Lynne Walker of The San Diego Union
for ``Invisible Work Force,'' about San Diego County's illegal
immigrant farm workers.
   _ Small Papers, Howard Gold of the Miami Review for ``Towering
Ambition,'' a series about Centrust Savings Bank and its
controversial chairman, David Paul.
   _ National magazines, shared by Eric Schurenberg and Lani
Luciano of Money for ``The Empire Called AARP,'' about the American
Association of Retired People; and Fortune's Carol J. Loomis for
``Buyout Kings,'' about the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
&amp; Co.
   _ Commentary, David Warsh of the Boston Globe for selected
columns.
   _ Beat or deadline writing, The Wall Street Journal's John
Helyar and Bryan Burrough for their coverage of the RJR Nabisco
buyout. Honorable mention to the Journal's Paulette Thomas and
Thomas Petzinger Jr. for coverage of Texas Air Corp.
   Winners get $1,000; honorable mention gets $500.
   Winners were selected from 250 entries by several panels of
judges, with final judging by J. Clayburn La Force, dean of UCLA's
graduate school of management; Shelby Coffey, editor and executive
vice president of the Los Angeles Times; John Dierdorff, managing
editor of Business Week; Mary Anne Dolan, syndicated columnist,
Robin Chandler Duke, national co-chairwoman of the Population
Crisis Committee, Draper Fund; John Lawrence, contributing editor
to Fortune; Lawrence Minard, deputy managing editor of Forbes; and
Paul Steiger, deputy managing editor of The Wall Street Journal.
   The late Gerald Loeb, an author and vice chairman of E.F.
Hutton, established the award in 1957 for writers who make
significant contributions to public understanding of business and
financial issues.
   Winners and finalists will be honored June 21 at a dinner at the
University Club in New York.
</TEXT>
