<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bank-MoneyLaundering     05-09 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank-Money Laundering,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Charges Brought Against Bank Linked to Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have brought more
money-laundering charges against a Luxembourg banking group, adding
two employees as defendants and implicating the bank's Colombian
branch office.
   The charges were contained in a new indictment against the Bank
of Credit and Commerce International Holdings S.A., which U.S.
Senate testimony has linked to money laundering by Panama's
military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noreiga.
   The new indictment was returned by a grand jury in Tampa last
week and made public Monday.
   In what was called a landmark case against an international
financial institution, the bank was charged in October with
laundering $14 million in cocaine profits collected in seven U.S.
cities.
   Some of the new charges apparently were based on testimony from
convicted smuggler-turned-informant Steven Michael Kalish. Kalish
won a sentence reduction from 14 to 10 years last week because of
his cooperation with federal authorities.
   The new indictment also combines the bank case and a related
money-laundering indictment against Gonzalo Mora Jr., a Colombian
businessman.
   Larry Barcella, one of the bank's Washington attorneys, said the
government was merely trying to shore up its case. The revised
charges are ``a simple transparent attempt'' by prosecutors to
resolve challenges the bank has raised in court filings seeking to
dismiss the indictment, he said.
   Mora's attorney, George Tragos, said his client was being
penalized by having his case merged with the bank's case.
   ``Mr. Mora can't possibly defend himself in a case that is so
large,'' said Tragos. ``He doesn't have the resources to match an
international bank or the government.''
   The bank indictment was one of three formal charges returned
here after a two-year U.S. Customs Service sting in which agents
laundered $32 million in drug proceeds for Colombian cocaine
cartels. The sting led to the indictment of 82 people in six cities.
   The new indictment includes allegations that Kalish laundered
millions of his smuggling ring's profits through the bank's
Panamanian and Colombian branches.
   Kalish linked the bank and Noriega, to his Tampa-based smuggling
ring during U.S. Senate testimony in January 1988.
   Prosecutors have said that his testimony was the key to
Noriega's indictment in February 1988 on drug charges here and in
Miami.
   Kalish was sentenced in February 1988 as the marshal of a ring
that smuggled 500,000 pounds of marijuana and 2,000 pounds of
cocaine from Colombia.
