<FIRST>r f AM-OPECSecretary     05-09 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC Secretary,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subroto: OPEC to Strive for Price Stability</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto, one-word name, is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of OPEC said Tuesday the cartel
will strive toward price stability and review its petroleum
production at a summer meeting.
   Subroto, secretary general of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, made the remarks upon arriving on a flight
from Frankfurt to Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
   Subroto, accompanied by his personal secretary, said he would
meet Wednesday morning with Texas Railroad Commissioner Kent Hance
at a breakfast session. Hance's commission regulates the Texas oil
industry and he has been an active observer of OPEC meetinggs in
the past.
   ``The message is that the member countries are striving toward
price stability'' at about $18 per barrel, Subroto said.
   It was Subroto's first American appearance since taking the OPEC
job last July. He was scheduled to address a Thursday luncheon
sponsored by Southern Methodist University's Institute for the
Study of Earth and Man in his only planned U.S. talk this year.
   Subroto's presentation, ``Long-term Prospects for Oil
Stability,'' at the Fairmont Hotel in Dallas was expected to
attract an estimated 1,000 oil and gas industry representatives and
others from the Southwest.
   Formerly Indonesia's minister of mines and energy, Subroto was
credited with developing a production agreement signed by OPEC
members. The pact has prompted an increase in oil prices since last
November.
   Subroto said he believed the performance of OPEC member
countries based on that agreement was ``pretty satisfactory.''
   Based in Vienna, Austria, OPEC's 13 member countries have been
instrumental in setting and maintaining worldwide oil prices.
   The organization has been watched closely by other petroleum
producing countries in anticipation of OPEC's June 5 meeting in
Vienna. Oil analysts have expressed concern following a 50 percent
price increase in past months and production levels that appear to
be rising.
   Strong demand has caused oil price rallies, with the latest
coming last week after reports of a delay in repairing the North
Sea's Cormorant Alpha platform, hit by an April 18 explosion.
</TEXT>
