<DOCNO> AP890509-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-09 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Weaker in U.S. Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar retreated slightly in choppy U.S.
trading Tuesday as dealers turned cautious about buying the
American currency.
   Gold prices rose in the United States, after weakening in
dealings abroad. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a troy
ounce of gold bullion at $378 as of 4 p.m. EDT, $2.60 higher than
the late bid Monday.
   Ross Taylor, a senior vice president at Kemper Currency Inc.,
said U.S. market participants became leery of having their currency
portfolios heavily weighted in favor of the dollar despite comments
from West German and Swiss authorities indicating that they were
not worried by current dollar levels.
   Some participants may be unwilling to add to their dollar
positions ahead of inflation statistics due later this week, he
said. The Labor Department is to issue the April producer price
index on Friday.
   Also discouraging buyers was a feeling in the U.S. market that
the dollar had gone up far enough after hitting a nine-month high
against the West German mark Monday.
   Earlier, the dollar advanced on European markets to its highest
level against the mark since last August, lifted by perceptions
that the U.S. economy continues to grow strongly enough to keep
interest rates aloft.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Europe said there had been no sign
of concerted intervention by central banks to sell dollars in order
to hold down the exchange rate, although the Bank of Japan and Bank
of England apparently did so on their own. U.S. dealers didn't
detect any interventions during U.S. trading.
   Central bank dollar sales in the past few weeks has not diluted
the currency's value and has been considered a largely symbolic
attempt to remind the markets that authorities are monitoring
exchange rates.
   In Europe, the dollar reached 1.9158 West German marks, up from
1.8975 on Monday and its highest level since Aug. 22 last year,
when it stood at 1.9190. Dealers said they expect the dollar to
test the 1.92 marks level this week.
   In U.S. trading, the dollar ended at 1.9094 marks, down slightly
from 1.9097 on Monday, the highest point since August 1988.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6605 late Tuesday, cheaper
for buyers than Monday's late $1.6710. Sterling stood at $1.6665
compared to $1.6646 on Monday.
   The dollar closed at 135.00 Japanese yen in Tokyo, up from
134.52 late Monday. In later London trading, the dollar traded
lower at 134.80 and in New York it ended at 134.525, down from
Monday's closing rate of 134.89.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Monday, included: 1.6955 Swiss francs, down from 1.7025; 6.4455
French francs, up from 6.4405; 1,391.50 Italian lire, down from
1,392.75; and, 1.18695 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1846.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday: 1.7035 Swiss francs, up from 1.6945; 6.4645 French francs,
up from 6.4025; 2.1610 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1400; 1,397.125
Italian lire, up from 1,385.00; 1.1869 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1850.
   Gold and silver prices had mixed showings on world precious
metals markets.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
settled at $378.80 a troy ounce, up from $376.90 Monday.
   The late bid gold price in London, the major market, was $376.50
a troy ounce, down from $377.50. In Zurich, the late bid price was
$376.40, down from $377.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $376.15, down from $377.25.
   Silver bullion for current delivery closed on New York's Comex
at $5.667 a troy ounce, up from Monday's settlement of $5.588.
Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.63 a troy ounce, down
from $5.64.
</TEXT>
