<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AgingAircraft     05-09 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aging Aircraft,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Modifications Might Not Be Enough, Congressional Staffers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airline industry officials hope plans to
extensively repair and modify 1,300 older Boeing jets will help
answer demands to ensure the safety of older passenger aircraft,
but some congressional staff members say it won't be enough.
   In the 13 months since the top ripped off an Aloha Airlines 737
over Hawaii, killing a flight attendant, Boeing Co., airlines and
the Federal Aviation Administration have hustled to reassure the
public that older commercial jetliners are safe.
   The National Transportation Safety Board is expected to issue
its report on the accident this month.
   Also expected soon are proposed FAA rules ordering 161
structural repairs and modifications for 1,300 older Boeing 727s,
737s and 747s. The estimated $600,000 worth of repairs per plane
will include replacing skin, rivets and other parts that get worn
as a plane ages.
   After the orders dealing with Boeing planes are issued,
aging-jet task forces will deal with planes made by McDonnell
Douglas Corp., Lockheed Corp., Europe's Airbus Industrie, Convair,
Fokker and British Aircraft Corp.
   According to aviation consultant Avmark Inc., 832, or almost 29
percent, of the nation's commercial jetliners were at least 20
years old as of last July. More than 15 percent, or 422, of the
jets were between 15 and 19 years old.
   Bill Becker, a Seattle aviation consultant, said the rules
should subdue what he calls the ``congressional dragon.''
   ``He'll continue to snort and vibrate, but he will be
appeased,'' Becker said.
   Maybe not. James Berard, a spokesman for Minnesota Democratic
Rep. James Oberstar, who heads the House subcomittee on aviation,
said the modifications don't go far enough.
   ``(These fixes) are still far short of what Congressman Oberstar
had in mind,'' Berard said. ``There will be further investigation
into the question to determine if additional legislation is
needed.''
   FAA spokesman David Duff in Seattle declined to discuss the
rules until they are formally released. But the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer on Monday cited industry sources as saying they
are expected to involve the following:
   _Seventy-four repairs to about 800 Boeing 727s with 60,000 or
more takeoff and landing cycles or 60,000 hours of flight.
   _Fifty-six repairs to about 300 Boeing 737s with 75,000 or more
cycles or 60,000 flight hours.
   _Thirty-one repairs to about 200 Boeing 747s with at least
20,000 flight cycles or 60,000 hours in flight.
   The proposals are expected to be filed in the Federal Register
next week and interested parties will have time to comment before
they become law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
