<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-09 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Up Strongly For Second Day On Supply Worries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices climbed aggressively for the second
straight day Tuesday, reflecting worries about the tight
availability of high-quality arabica coffee beans.
   On other markets, pork futures were up strongly while cattle
prices were mixed; energy futures rose; precious metals were
higher; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Coffee settled .81 cent lower to 2.75 cents higher on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, with the contract for delivery in
May up 2.75 cents at $1.4125 a pound.
   The sharp runup in the May delivery price followed an exchange
report showing the amount of warehoused coffee available for
delivery against the May contract at a 5-year low of less than
160,000 bags. Each bag contains 132 pounds of green, unroasted
coffee beans.
   With so little coffee available for delivery against the May
contract, which expires on May 19, fear of a so-called ``squeeze''
is building in the market, in which the physical availability of a
commodity is less than the amount required to satisfy all contracts.
   ``There just isn't enough product around,'' said Bert Ruiz, a
vice president with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in New York. One reason
for the supply tightness, he said, was an 18-day dockworkers strike
earlier this month in the Brazilian port of Santos, the world's
busiest coffee port.
   Frozen pork-belly futures soared the permitted 2-cents-a-pound
limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Analysts said the rally
was supported by strong cash markets but was mainly due to
technical factors.
   Hog futures also rallied but cattle futures were mixed with
strong cash markets offset by expectations of seasonal price
weakness in the coming weeks.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .27 cent higher with June
at 72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .18 cent
higher with May at 76.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent to
.35 cent higher with June at 48.17 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.98 cents to 2 cents higher with May at 34 cents a
pound.
   Petroleum futures prices rebounded from Monday's steep losses on
the New York Mercantile Exchange but the American Petroleum
Institute's weekly stockpile figures, which were released after the
close, were expected to prompt new selling on Wednesday.
   The API reported that U.S. gasoline stocks increased by 808,000
barrels last week while crude oil stocks rose by 9.316 million
barrels. Distillates were down 495,000 barrels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents lower to 32
cents higher with June at $19.76 a barrel; heating oil was .07 cent
to .30 cent higher with June at 46.99 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .11 cent lower to .54 cent higher with June at 65.52
cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures rose moderately on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar weakened.
   Gold settled $1.70 to $1.90 higher with June at $380.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 7.8 cents to 9 cents higher with July at $5.755 a
troy ounce.
   Wheat futures prices fell on the Chicago Board of Trade on a
combination of weakening chart signals and perceptions that growing
conditions are gradually improving.
   Soybean futures ended mostly higher on persistent rumors of
Soviet buying interest, while corn futures finished mostly lower.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 10 cents lower with May at $4.26 a
bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.77{
a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 4 cents lower with May at $1.88{ a
bushel; soybeans were \ cent lower to 5} cents higher with May at
$7.66\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
