<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Apple-Software     05-09 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Apple-Software,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Giant In Try To Remain User-Friendly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. is improving its system
software to hang on to the appeal of its Macintosh, the company
reported on Tuesday.
   The expanded software will extend memory capabilities to allow
programs to work together more efficiently, starring a feature
called ``virtual memory.''
   Virtual memory will extend the user's available memory by
treating the hard disk as if it were part of internal memory.
   Apple is planning to offer the new System 7.0 to software
developers by the end of the year, the company said.
   Other features include a new print architecture connected to
different printers and other devices made by companies other than
Apple _ an apparent move away from Apple's past efforts to maintain
the proprietary nature of its technology.
   ``That must have been a tough decision,'' said Nick Arnett, an
analyst with Creative Strategies Research International, a Silicon
Valley market research company. ``It may hurt their priinter
business, but it will strengthen the Macintosh by giving it many
more options.''
</TEXT>
