<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 1959EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AlaskaOil 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Oil, 1st Ld-Writethru,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Senate Pulls Reversal, Passes Oil-Tax Hike</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 16th graf to CORRECT tax increase to $45 million sted $35
million; picks up 17th graf pvs bg'ng, BP Exploration ...; Johne is cq
in 7th graf; Also moved on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Steve Cowper signed into law a bill
raising oil taxes by $235 million after the oil-industry-dominated
state Senate reversed itself in the wake of constituents' anger
over the Exxon Valdez spill.
   Cowper, saying big oil does not run Alaska, signed the bill
three hours after Monday's 11-9 vote, thwarting a last-ditch move
in the Senate to rescind the vote.
   ``There's no doubt about the fact that the spill made the
political atmosphere different from what it was before,'' the
governor said. ``It became a matter of competing credibility: the
credibility of the state vs. the credibility of the industry.''
   Oil industry officials argued that changing the tax formula
ultimately will cost the state jobs and oil revenue.
   The bill, which eliminates a tax break for the nation's two
largest oil fields, will add $235 million to the state treasury
next year and more than $2 billion over the next two decades, based
on current oil prices. Already, about 85 percent of the state's
$2.2 billion budget comes from oil and gas revenues.
   On Sunday, the state Senate, which had never before let the bill
even reach the floor, rejected the bill in a 9-11 vote.
   But Democratic Sen. Mike Szymanski, whose district includes
oil-stained Prince William Sound, and Republican Johne Binkley
reversed their initial ``no'' votes, providing the needed support
Monday for passage.
   The March 24 oil spill polluted the sound with more than 10
million gallons of North Slope crude. Binkley and Szymanski said
they did not change their vote to punish the industry, but both
said calls from constituents had influenced them.
   ``I think the oil companies, by and large, have been good
corporate citizens in the state of Alaska,'' Binkley said.
   But he said he received dozens of phone calls in the hours
following the first vote, most urging him to change his mind. A
brief private talk with Cowper, who had lobbied heavily for the
tax, also helped change his vote, he said.
   Szymanski, who said Sunday night that he could not approve a tax
increase, said Monday that he concluded the increase was needed to
ensure that Alaska gets its fair share of oil revenue.
   ``I would certainly hope that some of the additional money that
is made available by the (tax) would be made available to support
the local communities that were directly impacted by the oil
spill,'' he said.
   Szymanski said his phone rang constantly Monday. ``I had a lot
of pressure on me from the constituency,'' he said.
   The new law revises an oil-tax break known as the Economic Limit
Factor, or ELF. Cowper and other proponents of the bill said the
tax break should not apply to the productive Prudhoe Bay and
Kuparuk oil fields on Alaska's North Slope.
   It took three years for an ELF bill to make it to a vote on the
floor of the Republican-led Senate, long a stronghold of oil
industry support. The Democrat-controlled House approved an ELF
bill twice, in 1987 and this year.
   Exxon, which has a relatively small share of those two oil
fields, will pay only about 15 percent of the tax increase. At 15
percent, the company's share for the first year of the tax increase
would amount to about $45 million.
   BP Exploration (Alaska) Inc., a subsidiary of British Petroleum,
will pay about half of the additional taxes.
   ``We're disappointed,'' company spokesman Paul A. Laird said.
``We think it's not in the best interests of the state in the long
term economicially.''
   State officials said $150 million of the first year's revenue
from the tax hike will go into the state's oil-wealth savings
account, which was created to ensure that the state benefits from
the oil after it is gone.
   Nearly half of each year's earnings from the account are
distributed to residents. Last year, each qualified resident got
$826 from the fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
