<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IndianInvestigation 2ndLd-Writethru   05-09 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Implicated in Theft of Indians' Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: `In Wichita,' to UPDATE with Koch comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators implicated a Kansas-based oil
company Tuesday in testimony before a Senate panel that is checking
allegations of millions of dollars in oil and royalties being
stolen from Indians.
   The investigators told a special unit of the Senate Select
Committee on Indian Affairs that Koch Industries, which does a
large amount of business on Indian oilfields, over the past three
years consistently took hundreds of thousands more barrels of crude
oil than it paid for.
   But Donald L. Cordes, Koch Industries vice president for legal
and corporate affairs, said the Senate panel didn't reveal that the
so-called overages were a very small percentage of the total oil
the company buys and resells. He said the committee also has
information that Koch crude oil purchases were measured short the
first two months of 1989.
   For 1988, the Koch Industries overage was .0023 of the total
volume of crude oil handled and measured by the company, he said.
   ``This percentage is well within the range of overage
percentages reflected in the reports of the states which compile
that data,'' Cordes said.
   There isn't any basis for concluding Koch engages in illicit
measuring practices, he said.
   A spokesman for the Senate panel said that depositions were
taken with officials of Koch, though the officials were not called
to testify Tuesday.
   A certain amount of mismeasuring is normal in the industry, but
not to the degree shown in documents subpoenaed from Koch, said
witnesses.
   The documents indicated that Koch ended 1986 with 803,874 more
barrels of oil than it paid for; 1987 with 671,144 more barrels and
1988 with 474,281 more barrels. The value of the extra oil for the
three years was estimated at $12.2 million, $11.9 million and $7.1
million.
   ``Most companies try to be as accurate as possible,'' testified
Chris Tucker, an independent oil expert who investigated Koch. ``If
there are large overages, the company should figure out why this is
happening.''
   Tucker had been hired to investigate the company by a brother of
the owner, Charles Koch, said a Senate panel spokesman who
indicated the two brothers had quarreled.
   Tucker said that companies normally compensate for overages by
shorting themselves later and that the figures from Koch indicate
an intent by the company to take more than it pays for.
   ``It's very easy to steal from Indian lands,'' said Tucker.
``There are no checks and balances.''
   He and other witnesses said the fields are in remote areas and
are not generally watched.
   Tucker showed the committee a videotape he said he secretly made
of a Koch employee taking oil from a tank on Northern Ute Indian
land in Utah. The employee failed to perform all of the measuring
functions required under American Petroleum Institute standards,
Tucker testified.
   Chuck Norman, an investigator for the committee, said other oil
firms also were being probed. He said information about them would
be turned over to authorities.
   Before the hearings began, Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said
findings would be given to the Justice Department which could seek
indictments.
   ``We are not a grand jury,'' DeConcini, who chairs the special
committee, said during the hearing. ``We are attempting to zero in
on the problem and how it happens.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the purpose of the investigation
was to determine whether there was mismanagement by the federal
government and, if so, what steps Congress should take.
   Norman said there was confusion among the three federal agencies
that are charged with protecting Indian oil rights _ the Bureau of
Land Management, the Bureau of Indian Affairs and the Minerals
Management Service _ about who should be policing the fields.
   ``Usually nothing is done'' about theft, he said.
   The special committee will be investigating oil and oil royalty
theft on Indian land throughout the week.
   The hearings make up the second series since the panel began its
probe. Testimony in February alleged corruption in contracting and
gaming operations on Indian reservations and child sex abuse in
Bureau of Indian Affairs schools.
   DeConcini said he hopes to have a report by October that will
lead to changes in the government's approach to the Indians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
