<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru   05-09 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Vessel To Depart Aleanup Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Soviet ship to Vaidogubsky, sted Vaydaghubsky,
throughout; SUBS 9th graf, `In another ...,' with 4 grafs UPDATE with Robbins
inspecting islands; picks up 10th graf, `They don't ...' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ship helping clean up the Alaskan
oil spill is being sent home Wednesday because the high-tech
skimmer had trouble siphoning thick goo, frustrated U.S. officials
said Tuesday.
   ``We shouldn't blame the Russians,'' said Bill Rainey, Exxon's
operations manager. ``It was just not the type of oil she was good
in.''
   The 425-foot Vaidogubsky's pumps and machinery jammed often
while siphoning ``mousse,'' the thick goo that hardens as it's
tossed by winds and chilly currents, off the water, said officials
directing the cleanup.
   But they said the ship was unmatched in skimming the softer,
liquid crude that was in the water immediately after the spill
nearly seven weeks ago in Prince William Sound.
   ``If that ship had been available to us in the sound when the
spill first occurred, it would have made a helluva difference,''
said Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, who supervises cleanup work in the
spill zone.
   ``To this point, she hasn't collected a lot of oil,'' he added.
Robbins said officials decided late Monday night to send the ship,
which has been operating out of Seward, home on Wednesday.
   The vessel has been skimming mostly outside the sound, where the
tanker Exxon Valdez slammed into Bligh Reef on March 24 and spewed
more than 10 million gallons of oil into the water.
   The oil has killed hundreds of birds and fish and has fouled
beaches about 450 miles southwest of the spill site, including the
coast of Katmai National Park.
   Robbins inspected Big Smith, Little Smith, Applegate and Seal
islands in Prince William Sound on Tuesday.
   ``I'm encouraged with the progress on this island,'' he said on
Applegate as spots of oil glistened in the afternoon sun. ``It's a
heck of a lot better than when I last visited. ''
   The cleanup crew has been on Applegate for 13 days, hampered by
lack of equipment and frustrated by seeing the rocks re-oiled on
nearly every high tide.
   Authorities also extended by five days the deadline for having
the worst of the oil spill damage cleaned off several islands in
Prince William Sound. The original deadline of Wednesday, timed to
allow seals to use the beaches when giving birth, was pushed back
until May 15.
   ``They don't really start pupping until May 20, but with all the
activity we thought we'd give them a chance to reinhabit the area
and settle down,'' said Alaska Department of Fish and Game
spokesman Bill Pilcher.
   Pilcher said cleanup crews planned to sop up oil on the rocky
beaches with peat moss, stuffing it into oily cracks when the tide
is low, then collecting it from the water when the rising tide
washes it into the sound.
   An oil-spill task force of several boats planned to head out
from Kodiak across the Shelikof Strait to Katmai National Park, a
wildlife refuge hard hit by the spill. But reports of wind gusts
and 12-foot seas kept the vessels in port.
   The 11,400-ton Vaidogubsky arrived with great fanfare last
month, but Robbins said that by the time the Soviet ship reached
Alaskan waters, the oil either was too dispersed or too emulsified
for the ship to work effectively.
   The ship's arrival marked the second time in six months that the
Soviets had sent a vessel to Alaska to provide assistance. Last
year, a Soviet icebreaker worked near Barrow to help free two
trapped, California gray whales.
   The Vaidogubsky worked the southern edge of the Kenai Peninsula,
chasing the rapidly moving oil slick that seeped out of Prince
William Sound and headed southwest toward Kodiak Island and Katmai
National Park on the Alaska Peninsula.
   But the leading edge of the slick broke up before the
Vaidogubsky could do much work. ``We were never able to find oil in
places it could work,'' Robbins said.
   Exxon officials said they didn't know exactly how much oil the
ship had collected because it still was being pumped off Tuesday.
</TEXT>
