<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Scherer     05-09 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Scherer,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>R.P. Scherer Reports Quarterly Earnings Decline, Sales Boost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.P. Scherer Corp.'s said Tuesday its
fourth-quarter earnings declined 9 percent from a year earlier,
when profits were inflated by a one-time tax benefit.
   The gelatin capsule manufacturer said it earned $4.83 million,
or 44 cents a share, in the quarter ended March 31, compared with
$5.34 million, or 50 cents a share, in the year-earlier period.
   Sales for the quarter were $89.87 million, up 9 percent from
$82.08 million in the same period of 1988.
   Earnings for the fourth quarter of 1988 included an
extraordinary credit of $3.34 million, or 31 cents a share, that
reflected tax loss carryovers, Scherer spokeswoman Jayne Colombo
said. There was no such credit for the fourth quarter of 1989, she
said.
   Earnings for the 12 months ended March 31 were $7.87 million, or
86 cents a share, down 38 percent from $12.81 million, or $1.38 a
share, for the fiscal year ended March 31, 1988, the statement said.
   Net income for the fiscal year was reduced by $9 million, mainly
because of a one-time charge involving the pending $440 million
acquisition of Scherer by Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc.
   Sales for the 1989 fiscal year totaled $350.59 million, up 21
percent from $290.74 million in the same period a year earlier.
   Earnings for fiscal 1989 included extraordinary credits of $932
million, or 10 cents a share, compared with credits of $3.74
million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier, it said.
</TEXT>
