<FILEID>AP-NR-05-09-89 2258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-CNW-Japonica     05-09 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CNW-Japonica,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japonica, CNW Spar On Request To Postpone Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CNW Corp. and its suitor, Japonica Partners L.P.,
sparred Tuesday over Japonica's request that the transportation
company postpone its annual meeting scheduled for next week.
   Meanwhile, representatives from both sides testified in
Washington before the Interstate Commerce Commission, which wants
to know more about Japonica's financing and plans for Chicago-based
CNW, a railroad holding company.
   Japonica, a New York investment group headed by Paul Kazarian,
released a statement Tuesday saying it was evaluating its options
after CNW rejected a proposal to postpone its scheduled May 16
annual meeting and board election for 30 days.
   Japonica said it sought the delay to give CNW shareholders more
time to fully assess the company's progress toward increasing the
value of its stock.
   Japonica said its proposal included an offer to ``lock in'' for
30 days its takeover bid of $44 a share, or $658 million, for all
the CNW stock that Japonica doesn't already own. The partnership is
CNW's largest shareholder, with an 8.8 percent stake in the firm.
   CNW said in a statement issued later Tuesday it would not
postpone its annual meeting becase ``Japonica's ability to purchase
the company is not affected by the timing of the annual meeting.''
   At that meeting, shareholders will vote by proxy on whether to
replace the company's board of directors with a slate of Japonica
nominees.
   CNW, which owns the Chicago and North Western railroad, a major
freight hauler in the Midwest, is seeking friendly buyout offers
from other companies in an effort to defeat Japonica's hostile bid.
   Chairman Robert Schmiege said Tuesday in Washington the company
was examining one such bid and that more than two other companies
had also expressed interest in CNW.
   ICC Chairwoman Heather J. Gradison gave Japonica until the close
of business Wednesday to provide information about how it plans to
finance a takeover of CNW or face a subpoena.
   Japonica representative Howard Hardesty told the commission his
company would consider the ICC order but he said Japonica doesn't
want to aid and abet other companies working on competing bids to
take over the railroad.
   CNW provides freight service from Chicago to South Dakota, Iowa,
Minnesota, Wisconsin, Nebraska, Wyoming and Missouri. It also has a
profitable franchise to carry coal from Wyoming to Montana, which
company officials say is one of the operations that has made it
attractive to takeover bids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
